<head>
<title>Greenpeace: USA Nuclear Campaign</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FF FF FF" text="#00 00 80" link="#00 80 00" 
vlink="#80 00 00" alink="#FF FF 00" BASEFONT=3>
<center>
<a href="/~usa/index.html"><img src="pix/nuke_upd.gif" WIDTH=504 HEIGHT=101 border=0></a>
<hr>
<h1>Nuclear Campaign Timeline</h1></center>
On <b>July 16, 1945</b>, the United States secretly conducted the first nuclear weapon test, an 18-kiloton blast 
code-named “TRINITY”  near Alamagordo, New Mexico.  The world learned about the immense destructive 
power of these new weapons three weeks later when the United States dropped nuclear bombs on Hiroshima 
and Nagasaki, leading to more than 200,000 casualties.  The Soviet Union conducted its first nuclear test in 
1949.  By 1963, the number of nuclear weapons states had grown to five; the U.S., the Soviet Union, United 
Kingdom, France and China.  The nuclear tests detonated by these nations, as well as a single blast by India in 
1974, have damaged the environment and the health of countless downwinders and atomic veterens, 
squandered scarce economic resources, and have driven a deadly nuclear arms race.  In 1971, a small group of 
citizens in Vancouver, Canada said, “No more nuclear tests!”  Their actions led to the formation of 
Greenpeace. 
<p>
<b>September 15, 1971</b><br> 
With a crew of twelve, Greenpeace sails on its first voyage from Vancouver, Canada intent on stopping a U.S. 
nuclear test at Amchitka, Alaska.  The voyage and another one shortly after it, help to fuel intense public 
opposition to the tests.  Within a year the United States announces that it was canceling further tests at 
Amchitka for “political and other reasons.”
<p>
<b>April 1972 - 1974</b><br>  
Greenpeace undertakes a series of voyages to the French nuclear test sites at Moruroa and Fangataufa atolls.  
In 1974, the French government bows to public pressure and announces that all further nuclear tests will be 
conducted underground.
<p>
<b>1982</b><br>
Greenpeace protest vessel <i>Sirius</i> is towed out of Leningrad after Greenpeace members release thousands of 
balloons and distribute leaflets in the Russian city calling for the Soviet Union to stop nuclear testing.
<p>
<b>August 28, 1983</b><br>
Greenpeace’s hot air balloon <i>Trinity</i> flies over the Berlin Wall into East Germany carrying pleas for nuclear 
disarmament.
<p>
<b>May 1985</b><br>
Greenpeace ship <i>Rainbow Warrior</i> relocates the entire population of the South Pacific island Rongelap.  
These people had been exposed to radioactive fallout from U.S. nuclear testing in the region during the 40s 
and 50s and were suffering high levels of cancer and birth defects.
<p>
<b>July 10, 1985</b><br>
French secret service agents bomb the <i>Rainbow Warrior</i> while in Auckland harbor, killing one crew member. 
The crew had been planning to return to Moruroa and Fangataufa atolls to resume their protest against 
French nuclear testing.
<p>
<b>1985</b><br>
Arms control groups form U.S. Comprehensive Test Ban Coalition.  By 1991, the Coalition includes over 75 
national arms control, peace, faith, environmental, labor and civic organizations.   The  purpose is to gather 
support for Congressional resolutions for a test ban.
<p>
<b>1986</b><br>
Four teams of Greenpeace activists infiltrate the Nevada Test Site and succeed in delaying the "MIGHTY OAK" 
nuclear tests for two days.
<p>
<b>1986-1993</b><br> 
Greenpeace activists participate in annual protests at the Nevada Test Site involving 3,000 to 9,000 people 
that maintain public awareness of nuclear testing and the continuing nuclear arms race.  In 1988 alone, over  
14,000 people attend two demonstrations at the test site with over 4,000 people arrested for non-violent civil 
disobedience.  In 1987, the Greenpeace balloon <i>Trinity</i> sailed into the test site.
<p>
<b>1991</b><br>
Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev initiates unilateral nuclear testing moratorium.
<p>
<b>1992</b><br>
The <i>Rainbow Warrior II</i> returns to Moruroa atoll and is seized by French forces.  In April, Francois 
Mitterrand unexpectedly declares a temporary moratorium on French tests pending the actions of the other 
nuclear powers. Greenpeace activists stage non-violent direct action in front of the White House calling on 
then-President George Bush to initiate a U.S. moratorium.
<p>
After a sustained national grassroots lobbying campaign led by Greenpeace and other disarmament groups, the 
United States Senate adopts the “Hatfield-Exon-Mitchell” amendment that would effect a 9-month U.S. 
testing moratorium: place strict conditions on any further U.S. testing and require the president to complete 
<b>CTBT</b> negotiations by September 1996.  The United States conducts its 1,030th and last nuclear test on 
September 23.
<p>
<b>1993</b><br>
Greenpeace and disarmament groups launch the “Don’t Blow it Bill!” campaign to convince President Clinton 
to maintain the U.S. testing moratorium and initiate <b>CTBT</b> negotiations.
<p>
<b>1994</b><br>
<b>CTBT</b> negotiations begin at the Conference on Disarmament in Geneva.  Pro-<b>CTBT</b> groups press negotiators 
to complete talks by the end of the year and to agree to ban all nuclear explosions, including low-yield hydronuclear tests.
<p>
<b>July 9, 1995</b><br> 
<i>Rainbow Warrior II</i> sails toward Moruroa to protest French plans to resume testing.  The boat is boarded by 
a team of French Navy commandos who lob tear gas, smash equipment and take the boat and crew into 
custody. The incident comes nearly ten years to the day French Secret Service agents blew up the original 
<i>Rainbow Warrior</i> in Auckland harbor, New Zealand and fuels international outrage against French testing.
<p>
<b>September 6, 1995</b><br>
France resumes nuclear tests in the South Pacific despite international opposition and efforts by Greenpeace 
vessels to reach the test zone.  <b>CTBT</b> talks in Geneva end the year without producing an agreement.  The U.S. 
Energy Department announces plan to begin a series of “subcritical” nuclear weapon tests at the Nevada Test 
Site in 1996, prompting an immediate reaction from Greenpeace and a grassroots campaign to cancel them.
<p>
<b>January 27, 1996</b><br>
France conducts its last nuclear test.
<p>
<b>June 17, 1996</b><br>
The United States, bowing to public pressure, “indefinitely postpones” subcritical experiments.
<p>
<b>July 28, 1996</b><br>
China conducts its 45th, and last, nuclear test.
<p>
<b>September 10, 1996</b><br>
The 50th United Nations General Assembly overwhelmingly approves, (158 - 3), the <b>CTBT</b> after negotiators 
at the Conference on Disarmament fail to reach consensus on a final treaty text.
<p>
<b>September 24, 1996</b><br>
After 51 years and 2,046 nuclear weapons test explosions at over 20 locations around the globe, the 
<b>Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty</b> is opened for signature at the U.N. in New York, as Greenpeace celebrates 
25 years campaigning for an end to nuclear testing.  
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<b><a href="index.html">Back</a> to Nuclear/Energy Campaign page.</b>
