<head>
<title>Greenpeace USA Daily News/Campaign Updates</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FF FF FF" text="#00 00 00" link="#00 80 00" vlink="#80 00 00" 
alink="#FF FF 00" basefont=3>
<center><a href="/~usa/index.html"><img src="pix/news_rel.gif" WIDTH=504 HEIGHT=101 border=0 ALT="Campaign News Releases"></a>
<hr>
<tt><font size=+3><b>NUCLEAR UTILITIES PROMOTING PROLIFERATION BY
INTEREST IN TRITIUM AND PLUTONIUM, ACCORDING TO GREENPEACE
</b></font><br>
<p>
<hr width=25%></center>
<i>NOTE TO THE PUBLIC:  Please check for your local utility at the
<a href="#notes">end</a> of this news release and protest about these plans to them as
well as to the Department of Energy.</i>
<center><hr width=25%></center>
<b>WASHINGTON D.C., March 29, 1996</b> --  Greenpeace today voiced
opposition to a plan by the U.S. Department of Energy in which
commercial nuclear power utilities around the U.S. are being
solicited to produce tritium for nuclear weapons and use fuel
made from weapons-grade plutonium.  
<p>
A list of utilities expressing interest to DOE for either
producing tritium, a radioactive gas which fuels thermonuclear
weapons, or using plutonium fuel made from "surplus" weapons
plutonium was expected to reach the DOE public document rooms
today.  In December, DOE solicited "Expression of Interest" from
utilities in the two nuclear missions. 
<p>
Seventeen U.S. utilities and one Canadian utility with a (combined)
total of 41 reactors have expressed interest in using plutonium
fuel, a plutonium-uranium mixture (mixed oxide fuel or MOX) which
would contain up to 30% weapons-grade plutonium.  Fourteen U.S. 
utilities with 22 reactors, many of which are also interested in
MOX, are interested in the tritium mission. 
<p>
"Nuclear power is bad enough, but consumers now will be forced to
produce bomb material and encourage international plutonium use
by simply flipping their light switch," said Tom Clements of
Greenpeace's nuclear campaign.  "Greenpeace will support a
consumer rebellion against this taxpayer subsidized big
government-utility alliance."
<p>
"This program threatens to break the longstanding taboo against
using commercial reactors for military purposes," Said Damon
Moglen, coordinator of Greenpeace's plutonium campaign.  In
addition, the use of plutonium fuel in the U.S. will help to
justify, even encourage the international trade in weapons-usable
plutonium -- a development which threatens U.S. and international
security." 
<p>
DOE is currently going through an Environmental Impact Statement
process to determine what to do with around 50 tons of "surplus"
weapons plutonium.  Options include continued storage, use in
reactors as MOX and vitrification, or solidification in glass or
ceramic material.  A decision on the EIS is expected this fall. 
Greenpeace supports pursuit of the vitrification option as
plutonium is a dangerous nuclear waste which must be isolated
from the environment.
<p>
As a facility to fabricate MOX fuel in the US does not exist, it
is estimated that it could cost $1 billion or more of taxpayer
money to construct such a high-tech facility.  MOX fuel is many
times more expensive to use than conventional uranium fuel and
presents a greater danger in reactors.   European MOX fabricators
in Britain, France and Belgium are pursuing producing MOX for the
US and these same countries are key to continued reprocessing of
nuclear fuel and stockpiling of the plutonium removed in that
dirty and dangerous process. 
<p>
As tritium has a radioactive half-life of 12.5 years, DOE claims
that a new tritium production source will be needed by 2011 to
fuel about 6000 warheads.  No tritium has been produced since
reactors at the DOE's Savannah River Site (South Carolina) were
closed in 1988.  In December 1995, DOE issued a decision that
tritium production in commercial reactors as well as by a linear
accelerator at Savannah River Site would be perused.
<p>
MOX, according to the International Atomic Energy Agency is a
"direct use" material for nuclear weapons as the plutonium in it
can be easily removed.  Shipments of the fuel therefore require
military escort.  New production of tritium runs contrary to
disarmament trends and reveals U.S. intention not to disarm as
required by the <b>Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty (NPT)</b>.
<p>
</tt>
<img src="pix/can_do.gif" width=560 height=23 ALT="What you can do">
<p>
In order to protest these plans, please send letters to:
<p><b>Mr. Stephen Sohinki</b><br>
Office of Reconfiguration<br>
US Department of Energy<br>
1000 Independence Ave., NW<br>
Washington, DC<br>
20585<br>
telephone <b>(202) 586-0838</b><br>
fax <b>(202) 586-1966</b><br>
also send copies to the Office of Fissile Material Disposition at
the same address,<br>fax <b>(202) 586-2710</b>
<p>
<a name="notes"></a>
<hr>
