<html>
<head>
<title>Greenpeace USA Daily News/Campaign Updates</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FF FF FF" text="#00 00 00" link="#00 80 00" vlink="#80 00 00" 
alink="#FF FF 00" basefont=3>
<center><a href="/~usa/index.html"><img src="pix/news_rel.gif" WIDTH=504 HEIGHT=101 border=0 ALT="Campaign News Releases"></a>
<hr>
<tt><font size=+3><b>U.S. DEPARTMENT OF ENERGY URGED TO "JUST SAY 'NO'
TO REPROCESSING"</b></font></tt><br>
<tt><font size=+2><i>National Security, Environmental Groups Urge Energy 
to "Permanently Close" Reprocessing Facilities</i></font></tt>
</center>
<p>
<tt><b>WASHINGTON D.C., March 13, 1996</b> -- The Department of Energy (DOE)
should cease further reprocessing activities at the Savannah
River and Argonne West sites, close these facilities, and just
say "no" to reprocessing, twenty-one national security and
environmental groups told Department of Energy (DOE) Secretary
Hazel O'Leary in a letter released today.
<p>
The DOE has resumed reprocessing activities at the Savannah River
Site in South Carolina to "stabilize" spent fuel and other Cold
War-era nuclear materials left over from operations there, and is
planning to reprocess additional materials at the Argonne West
site in Idaho.  During the Cold War, the U.S. produced plutonium
and tritium for nuclear weapons at Savannah River.  Advanced
reactor technology research took place at Argonne West.
<p>
According to the letter to O'Leary, DOE's plans to resume
reprocessing will cause further environmental damage at DOE
sites, without eliminating the need to safely store large amounts
of similar types of spent fuel.  At the Savannah River Site,
reprocessing operations have resumed despite evidence uncovered
in January and made public last month that the facilities at
Savannah River do not meet earthquake safety criteria.
<p>
In August, the Westinghouse Savannah River Corporation, which
operates the Savannah River Site, prepared a report arguing that
civil spent fuel could be reprocessed at the site as an economic
way to dispose of spent fuel from commercial reactors.  DOE has
called the report "highly speculative and extremely optimistic."
<p>
The groups urge Secretary O'Leary to abandon reprocessing as an
option for waste disposition.  They warn that the resumption of
reprocessing may make it easier for countries seeking nuclear
weapons to acquire reprocessing technologies that could be used
for military purposes.  Reprocessing will "falsely signal" other
countries that reprocessing is a viable waste disposition
strategy, thereby undermining "the Administration's nuclear
weapons non-proliferation objective of not encouraging
reprocessing," the letter says.  Countries seeking weapons "will
find it easier to convince irresponsible supplier nations that
they should receive important items under the cover of 'civil
use.'"
<p>
By backsliding into reprocessing, the DOE will open up new
domestic and national security problems.  The U.S. should set an
example for the rest of the world by rejecting reprocessing as a
waste management tool.  "Rather than breathe new life into
reprocessing," the letter concludes, "the DOE should just say
'no."' 
<p>
REPORTERS MAY CONTACT:<br>
Tom Clements, Greenpeace, <b>(202) 319-2506</b><br>
David Albright, ISIS, <b>(202) 547-3633</b><br>
Daniel Horner, Nuclear Control Institute, <b>(202) 822-8444</b><br>
Brian Costner, Energy Research Foundation, <b>(803) 256-7298</b><br>
<p>
<b>For addtional Nuclear Campaign information, please visit our <a
href="/~usa/campaigns/nuclear/index.html">USA Energy/Nuclear Campaign page</a> and 
our <a href="/~usa/pubinfo/publist.html">Public Information page</a> for available <a
href="/~usa/pubinfo/nukes.html">Nuclear Campaign Reports</a>.</b><p></tt>
