<HEAD>
<TITLE>Greenpeace USA Energy and Toxics Reports</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FF FF FF" TEXT="#00 00 80" LINK="#00 80 00" VLINK="#80 00 00" 
ALINK="#FF FF 00" basefont=3>
<table width=100% border=0><tr><td colspan=2 align=right valign=top>
<a href="/~usa/index.html"><img src="pix/pub_vid.gif" WIDTH=504 HEIGHT=101 border=0></a>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td valign=top><H1>Greenpeace Energy and Toxics Reports</H1>
Reports are listed in chronological order according to publication date. Within each year,
titles are listed in alphabetical order.
<p><b>Also check out our up-to-the-minute <a href="/~usa/campaigns/nuclear/">Nuclear
Campaign page</a>.</b></td>
<td valign=top>
<IMG VSPACE=0 HSPACE=10 SRC="pix/publist.gif" WIDTH=154
HEIGHT=156 ALT="Photo of 3 Greenpeace Reports"></td>
</tr>
</table>
<hr>
<ul>
<li><b>"Outline for a Greenpeace Environmental 'Marshall Plan' -- Chernobyl: The First
Step"</b> This document proposes foreign investment in alternative power generating 
technologies for the Ukraine which will create jobs and electricity while shutting down 
the dangerous (and still operating) Chernobyl nuclear power facility. &#169; Greenpeace 1996.<br>
<b>Only available <a href="/~usa/reports/energy/marshall_plan.html">on-line</a></b></li>
<hr align=left>
<li><b>"AES: Dirty Deals for Dirty Energy"</b> (1995) This report exposes the AES Corporation, which
has worked hard to project an image of itself as an environmentally-friendly and community-oriented power company. The
truth is not so pretty. &#169; Greenpeace<br>
<b>Only available <a href="/~usa/reports/energy/AES.html">on-line</a></b></li>
<hr align=left>
<li><b>"Back to the Future"</b> (1995) This study examines the benefits of hydrocarbon technology
from an environmental and business perspective. &#169; Greenpeace International, 57 pages<br>
<b>$25.00</b><br><i><b>$5.00</b> Greenpeace supporters and non-profits</i></li>
<hr align=left>
<li><b>"A New Generation of Fossil Fired Power Plants: Another Generation of Environmental
Destruction"</B> (1994) This report documents the impact of new and proposed fossil fueled
power plants to the environment. &#169; Greenpeace, 12 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li>
<hr align=left>
<li><b>"Money to Burn"</b> (1994) Details the failure of the Montreal Protocol to protect the
ozone layer and the World Bank's role in ozone destruction. &#169; Greenpeace, 40 pages<br>
<b>$25.00</b><br><i><b>$5.00</b> Greenpeace supporters and non-profits</i></li>
<hr align=left>
<li><b>"The Climate Time Bomb: Signs of Climate Change from the Greenpeace Database"</b>  
(1994) This Greenpeace report chronicles all the major extreme weather events, broken
meteorological and climatic records, and natural climate-related disasters that have occurred since
the publication of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change's First Scientific Assessment,
in May 1990. The report synthesizes the most important estimates of future effects should
concentrated greenhouse gases continue to be emitted into the atmosphere. &#169; Greenpeace
International, 166 pages<br><b>$50.00</b><br><i><b>$25.00</b> Greenpeace supporters and
non-profits</i></li>
<hr align=left>
<li><b>"Fossil Fuels in a Changing Climate [Summary]"</b> (1994)
Climate scientists and energy modelers working with Greenpeace determined that our current
fossil energy dependence is unsustainable and leading us to catastrophic climate change, but that a
fossil free future, using efficient and renewable energy sources, is practical and can be attained
rapidly. &#169; Greenpeace International,  50 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li>  
<hr align=left>
<li><b>"Towards a Fossil Free Energy Future [Technical Analysis]"</b> (1994)
Climate scientists and energy modelers working with Greenpeace determined that our current
fossil energy dependence is unsustainable and leading us to catastrophic climate change, but that a
fossil free future, using efficient and renewable energy sources, is practical and can be attained
rapidly. &#169; Greenpeace International, 239 pages<br><b>$25.00</b></li>
<hr align=left>
<li><b>"Shell Shocked: The Environmental and Social Costs of Living Next Door to Shell"</b>
(1994) This report focuses on the record of Shell in the Niger Delta and the environmental havoc
caused by the largest oil exploration and production venture in Nigeria. 
&#169; Greenpeace International, 30 pages<br><b>$50.00</b><br>
<i><b>$5.00</b> Greenpeace supporters and non-profits</i></li>
<hr align=left>
<li><b>"Emerging Impacts of Climate Change: How Lucky Do You Feel?"</b> (1993) From the
devastation of Hurricane Andrew in Florida to the deteriorating tundra in Arctic Alaska, the
warning signs of climate change are all around us. &#169; Greenpeace International. 24
pages<br>
<b>$15.00</b></li>
<hr align=left>
<li><b>"Natural Gas: Bridging Fuel or Roadblock to Clean Energy?"</b> (1993)
This report provides an overview of the seldom discussed problems created by natural gas.
&#169; Greenpeace. 60 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li>
<hr align=left>
<li><b>"Oil in Arctic Waters: The Untold Story of Offshore Drilling in Alaska"</b> (1993)
Using misguided energy analysis, the oil and gas industry have brought a multitude of looming
crises to the Alaskan Arctic, including global warming, ozone depletion, and chemical and
radioactive contamination. &#169; Greenpeace. 122 pages<br><b>$10.00</b></li>
<hr align=left>
<li><b>"Power to Change: Case Studies in Energy Efficiency and Renewable Energy"</b>
(1993) The case studies in this report show how we can reduce our dependence on fossil fuels and
minimize pollution. They show examples of energy efficient buildings, lights and appliances,
industry, and transport. This report also demonstrates the application of renewable energy
technology and discusses the policies that must be introduced to encourage a market for
renewable energy and the efficient use of energy. &#169; Greenpeace International. 40 pages<br>
<b>$5.00</b></li>
<hr align=left>
<li><b>"Climate Change and the Insurance Industry: Solidarity Among the Risk
Community?"</b> (1992) Climate disasters are already taking a tremendous toll on many of the
major insurance carriers. Many are beginning to realize that climate change could bring about the
collapse of the entire industry. &#169; Greenpeace International. 46
pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li>
<hr align=left>
<li><b>"Climbing Out of the Ozone Hole. A Preliminary Survey of Alternatives to
Ozone-Depleting Chemicals"</b> (1992) This report looks at the problem of ozone depletion,
including recent scientific developments, the use of HCFCs and HFCs, and Greenpeace's
response to the crisis. The second part of the report surveys alternatives. 
&#169; Greenpeace International. 40 pages<br><b>$25.00</b><br><i><b>$8.00</b>
Greenpeace
supporters and non-profits</i></li> 
<hr align=left>
<li><b>"Energy For Employment: How to Heat Up the Economy, Not the Planet"</b> (1992) 
This report dispels the myth that the economy and the environment are competing interests.
Rather, green technologies offer many new possibilities for job creation and economic growth.
Not only will investments in clean energy now help stave off the threat of global warming, they
also can employ more people while reinvigorating the economy and enhancing U.S.
competitiveness. &#169; Greenpeace. 39 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li>
<hr align=left>
<li><b>"The Environmental Impact of the Car"</b> (1992) This report examines all aspects of
the auto industry. Part one looks at historical and future trends. Part two looks at environmental
impacts such as global warming; air pollution; discovering, transporting, and using oil; the
resource cost of making cars; road safety; and cities. Part three examines the car lobby. The
report concludes with recommendations for a reformulation of transportation policy. 
&#169; Greenpeace. 60 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li>
<hr align=left>
<li><b>"The North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) and Energy Trade"</b> (1992) 
This report demonstrates how U.S. energy reform currently under consideration by the Clinton
Administration could be significantly undermined by the passage of NAFTA. As currently written
NAFTA perpetuates North America's heavy reliance on finite and polluting fossil fuel supplies.
It undermines efforts under way in all three countries to integrate demand side management and
renewable energy technologies. It will also result in the export of U.S. jobs. 
&#169; Greenpeace. 41 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li> 
<hr align=left>
<li><b>"Dinosaur's Path: The Exxon Valdez, Oil and National Security"</b> (1990) An analysis
of the flawed U.S. energy strategy and an examination of the Exxon Valdez oil spill. 
&#169; Greenpeace International. 23 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li>
<hr align=left>
</ul>
<pre>

</pre>
