<H1>Greenpeace Human Health and the Environment Reports</H1><P>Reports are listed in chronological order according to publication date. Within each year,titles are listed in alphabetical order.</td><td valign=top><IMG VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10 SRC="pix/publist.gif" WIDTH=154
HEIGHT=156 ALT="Photo of 3 Greenpeace Reports"></td></tr></table><hr><ul>
<li><b>"Not Ready for Roundup: Why Consumers and Farmers Should Avoid Monsanto's Genetically Engineered Soybeans"</b> and 
<b>"Not Ready for Roundup: A Critique of Monsanto's Risk Evaluation"</b> (1996) These two reports
document the potential health and environmental hazards created by Monsanto's genetically engineered soy beans. &#169; Greenpeace<br>
<b>Only available <a href="/~usa/reports/biodiversity/roundup/index.html">on-line</b></a></li>
<hr align=left>
<li><b>"PVC: A Primary Contibutor to the U.S. Dioxin Burden"</b> (1995) This reportdocuments for the first time dioxin at historically high levels in PVC production facilities in theU.S. &#169; Greenpeace 95 pages (with appendices)<br><b>$100</b><br><i><b>$25.00</b> Greenpeace supporters and non-profits</i></li><hr align=left><li><b>"Nuclear Power, Human Health and the Environment: The Breast Cancer Warning in theGreat Lakes"</b> (1995) This report makes an important contribution to the growing body ofevidence linking breast cancer with environmental pollutants.&#169; Greenpeace. 18 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"The Incineration of Dioxin-Contaminated Wastes in Jacksonville, Arkansas: A Review ofthe Inhalation Exposure Assessment"</b> (1995) Controversial report provides data and chartsshowing impact on dioxin levels of people living in the vicinity of the incinerator&#169; Greenpeace. 16 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"Body of Evidence"</b> (1995) This report documents the scientific evidence oforganochlorines on human health, and the failure of current regulatory policies. Alternativestrategies are suggested for a global phase out. &#169; Greenpeace International.<br> <b>[Executive summary]</b> 19 pages <b>$10.00</b><br><i>Greenpeace supporters andnon-profits <b>$5.00</b></i><br><b>[Full report]</b> 89 pages <b>$25.00</b><br><i>Greenpeace supporters and non-profits<b>$10.00</b></i></li><hr align=left><li><b>"Breast Cancer and The Environment: The Chlorine Connection (second edition)"</b> (1993) The worldwide increase in breast cancer rates has occurred during the same period inwhich the global environment has become contaminated with industrial synthetic chemicals,including the toxic and persistent organochlorines. This report examines the contribution syntheticchemicals may make to the increasing rates in breast cancer. &#169; Greenpeace. 25 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"Achieving Zero Dioxin: An Emergency Strategy for Dioxin Elimination"</b> (1994)This report discusses the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency’s Dioxin Reassessment and theformation and sources of dioxin, and it sets forth a national strategy for eliminating dioxin.&#169; Greenpeace. 57 pages<br><b>$25.00</b><br><i><b>$5.00</b> Greenpeace supportersand non-profits</i></li><hr align=left><li><b>"Dressed to Kill-The Dangers of Dry Cleaning and the Case for Chlorine-FreeAlternatives</b> (1994) This report focuses on a particular chlorinated chemicalperchloroethylene (`perc') and its use in the dry cleaning industry. The report presents evidence ofthe harmful effects the use of perc is causing, demonstrates that safe alternatives exist, andproposes regulatory and market mechanisms to end the use of perc. &#169; Greenpeace. 40 pages<br><b>$50.00</b><br><i><b>$10.00</b> Greenpeacesupportersand non-profits</i></li><hr align=left><li><b>"The Medium is the Message: Time Magazine, Pulp Mill Pollution and Clean ProductionOpportunities"</b> (1994) This paper discusses the North American pulp and paper industry,which is the continent's largest discharger of organochlorine pollutants into water. That it hasbeen a primary focus of much of the discussion around the phase-out of chlorine is largely due tothe availability of clean alternatives. If Time, a large purchaser of high-quality printing paper,shifted to totally chlorine-free paper, it would have repercussions far beyond Time’s ownprinting plants and even beyond the magazine sector. &#169; Greenpeace. 33 pages<br><b>$50.00</b><br><i><b>$5.00</b> Greenpeace supporters and non-profits</i></li><hr align=left><li><b>"Transition Planning for the Chlorine Phase-Out–Economic Benefits, Costs, andOpportunities"</b> (1994) This document shows that society can realize significant economicgains in the transition to a chlorine-free economy, if the process is guided by careful planning tominimize costs, maximize benefits, and ensure that both are distributed equitably. &#169; Greenpeace. 32 pages <br><b>$50.00</b><br><i><b>$10.00</b> Greenpeacesupportersand non-profits</i></li><hr align=left><li><b>"Dioxin Factories: A Study of the Creation and Discharge of Dioxins and OtherOrganochlorines from the Production of PVC"</b> (1993) &#169; Greenpeace International. 19 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"Hazardous Waste Incineration: Impacts On Agriculture"</b> (1993) This report looks atcontamination of the food chain from hazardous waste incinerators.&#169; Greenpeace. 20 pages<br><b>$3.00</b></li><hr align=left></ul><pre></pre><h2>Greenpeace Public Information <a href="order_form.html">Order Form</a></h2><h3><a href="publist.html">Return</a> to the main Public Information Page</h3><p>If you have questions about these reports or about ordering these publications in quantity,please contact our Public Information office by <a href="mailto:usa.supporter.services@green2.greenpeace.org">e-mail</a>,fax, or phone (Monday through Friday, 9:30am-5:30pm, EST).<P><b>Greenpeace Public Information<BR>1436 U Street NW<BR>Washington DC<BR>20009<BR>phone (202) 319-2444<BR>fax (202) 462-4507</b><P><i>Prices include shipping and handling. Availability of information is subject to change atany time. You will receive your order within two weeks of our receipt of your request (withpayment), unless the publication is out of print.<p><b>The lists are updated biannually and were last updated in September 1996.</b></i><pre></pre><CENTER><IMG SRC="pix/rnbwbar.gif"><H2>...Because our kids deserve a future</H2><IMG SRC="pix/rnbwbar.gif"></CENTER><P><H5>photo of Greenpeace reports &#169; Jay Townsend/Greenpeace 1995</H5><pre></pre></BODY></HTML>
