<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Greenpeace USA Toxics Reports</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FF FF FF" TEXT="#00 00 80" LINK="#00 80 00" VLINK="#80 00 00" ALINK="#FF FF 00" basefont=3><table width=100% border=0><tr><td colspan=2 align=right valign=top>
<a href="/~usa/index.html"><img src="pix/pub_vid.gif" WIDTH=504 HEIGHT=101 border=0></a>
</td></tr>
<tr><td valign=top>
<H1>Greenpeace Toxics Reports</H1>
Reports are listed in chronological order according to publication date. Within each year,
titles are listed in alphabetical order.
</td><td valign=top>
<IMG VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10 SRC="pix/publist.gif" WIDTH=154HEIGHT=156 ALT="Photo of 3 Greenpeace Reports"></td></tr>
</table><hr><ul><li><b>"Dow Brand Dioxin...Makes You Poison Great Things"</b> (1995) This report presentsevidence that Dow Chemical is a driving force behind facilities and the production of products thatproduce dioxin.  It also examines the role of Dow Chemical's corporate resources and power toinfluence legislative and regulatory processes to protect its investment and the cost of our health and harm to future generations. &#169; Greenpeace. 44pages<br><b>$30.00</b><br><i><b>$10.00</b> Greenpeacesupporters and non-profits</i><br><b>Also available <a href="/~usa/reports/dow_brand_dioxin.html">on-line</a></b>.</li><hr align=left> <li><b>"Death in Small Doses:  The Effects of Organochlorines on Aquatic Ecosystems"</b> (1992) This report draws on a range of scientific findings, including recent research that begins topiece together the complex mechanisms that make these chemicals so damaging, to demonstratethe urgent need for a complete phase-out of all releases of organochlorines. &#169; Greenpeace International. 28 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>Playing With Fire"</b> (1991) A comprehensive report on hazardous waste incineration,addressing the theory and practice of incineration. Covers the release of unburned wastes andmetals, products of incomplete combustion (PICs), the hazards associated with ash residues, andhealth and environmental effects. &#169; Greenpeace. 63 pages<br><b>$10.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"The Product is the Poison: The Case for a Chlorine Phase-out"</b> (1991) This reportexposes the threat posed to the global community and the Great Lakes ecosystem by industrialproduction of chlorine and its releases and by-products. &#169; Greenpeace. 59 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"The Product is the Poison, Part 2: Chlorinated Solvents and the Great Lakes AutoIndustry"</b> (1991) This report examines five industrial chemicals widely used by the auto,metalworking, manufacturing, and electronics industries. These chemicals are a major source oftoxic pollution in the Great Lakes; they contribute an estimated annual 6.8 million pounds ofpersistent and bioaccumulative toxic chemicals to the Great Lakes. &#169; Greenpeace. 31 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"Waste Management, Inc.:  An Encyclopedia of Environmental Crimes andMisdeeds"</b> (1991) The "big book" on Waste Management, Inc., the world's largest disposalcompany. &#169; Greenpeace. 285 pages<br><b>$50.00</b><br><i><b>$20.00</b>Greenpeacesupporters and non-profits</i></li><hr align=left><li><b>"Trash into Cash"</b> (1991) An abstract of a forthcoming Greenpeace report on WasteManagement, Inc.'s environmental crimes and misdeeds, this is the short version of our fullencyclopedia on the world's largest waste disposal company. &#169; Greenpeace. 37 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"Breaking Down the Degradable Plastics Scam"</b> (1990) This report uncovers thetruth behind manufacturers' claims of so-called environmentally safe degradable andbiodegradable plastics. &#169; Greenpeace. 97 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li> <hr align=left><li><b>"A Citizen's Toxic Waste Audit Manual"</b> (1990) This guide has been prepared toassist citizens in uncovering and identifying the pollution produced by local facilities. A wasteaudit is an assessment of the types and amounts of chemical wastes that are being emitted by aparticular facility in a community. &#169; Greenpeace. 71 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"A Shot in the Dark: Underground Injection of Hazardous Waste"</b> (1990) Thisreport examines one of the cheapest and most poorly regulated of all disposal methods. &#169; Greenpeace. 31 pages<br><b>$5.00</b>  <hr align=left><li><b>"Liquid Waste Disposal Inc: The Greenpeace Report"</b> (1989) A report of theoperating violations and unsound practices of the hazardous waste incineration firm Liquid WasteDisposal, Inc. &#169; Greenpeace. 80 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li> <hr align=left><li><b>"The Politics of Penta"</b> (1989) This report exposes EPA collusion with the woodpreservatives industry that has allowed one of the nation's worst dioxin polluters to avoid strictregulation. &#169; Greenpeace. 148 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li><hr align=left> <li><b>"Sham Recyclers, Part I: Hazardous Waste Incineration in Cement and AggregateKilns"</b> (1989) This report examines the EPA loophole that allows hazardous waste to beincinerated as a fuel in unregulated kilns. &#169; Greenpeace. 45 pages<br><b>$5.00</b> <hr align=left><li><b>"We All Live Downstream: The Mississippi River and the National Toxics Crisis"</b> (1989) The most comprehensive report to date detailing the catastrophic state of the nation’slargest river. &#169; Greenpeace. 181 pages<br><b>$10.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"Burn Out: Danger in Chicago's Garbage Incinerator Program"</b> (1988) A study ofhow Chicago's garbage incineration program poses an immediate threat to human health and theurban economy. &#169; Greenpeace. 30 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li> <hr align=left><li><b>"Great Lakes: An Abused Ecosystem"</b> (1988) This booklet focuses on some of themost contaminated sites in the Great Lakes basin and examines waste disposal options used by thegovernments bordering the Great Lakes. &#169; Greenpeace. 23 pages<br><b>$5.00</b> <hr align=left><li><b>"Hazardous Waste Incineration in New Jersey"</b> (1988) This report details some ofthe problems with current hazardous waste incinerators in New Jersey. It examines proposals fornew incinerators and looks at what can be done to avoid the dangerous additions to the state'stoxic burden. &#169; Greenpeace. 25 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"International Paper: A Greenpeace Report"</b> (1988) A study of the world's largestpulp and paper company and polluter. &#169; Greenpeace. 28 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li> <hr align=left><li><b>"Marine Shale Processors, Inc."</b> (1988) Sham recycling and hazardous wasteincineration in Amelia, Louisiana. &#169; Greenpeace. 17 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li> <hr align=left><li><b>"Monsanto Corporation: A Greenpeace Report"</b> (1988) A study of MonsantoCorporation's toxic discharge into the Mississippi River.  &#169; Greenpeace. 20 pages<br><b>$10.00</b></li> <hr align=left><li><b>"Mortality and Toxics Along the Mississippi River"</b> (1988) A study of mortality ratesand toxic pollution in cities and counties along the Mississippi. &#169; Greenpeace. 112pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li> <hr align=left><li><b>"Pentachlorophenol: Poison on Your Street"</b> (1988) This report defines the effect ofthe wood preservative penta in the Puget Sound region and presents safe alternatives. &#169; Greenpeace. 67 pages<br><b>$10.00</b></li> <hr align=left><li><b>"Time to Cut Calvert City's Toxic Waste"</b> (1988) A study of the industrial complexin Calvert City, Kentucky, responsible for at least 20.2 million pounds of toxic waste each year. &#169; Greenpeace. 21 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li> <hr align=left><li><b>"Toxic Waste and Mortality in Louisiana's Chemical Corridor" </b>(1988) A study of theconcentration of manufacturers, users, emitters, and dischargers of toxic chemicals and themortality and cancer rates along the Mississippi between Baton Rouge and New Orleans. &#169; Greenpeace. 56 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li> <hr align=left><li><b>"Dupont Chambers Works"</b> (1987) A study of one of the nation's largest chemicalmanufacturers and producers of chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs) and HCFCs and solid hazardouswaste. Dupont also runs treatment facilities for commercial hazardous waste. &#169; Greenpeace. 14 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"Incineration in Louisiana"</b> (1987) A report on hazardous waste burners operating inand proposed for Louisiana. It offers environmentally-safe recommendations. &#169; Greenpeace. 24 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li> <hr align=left><li><b>"Polaroid: Instant Pollution, #1 in Toxic Waste"</b> (1987) An environmental review ofthe worst toxic polluter on Boston Harbor. &#169; Greenpeace. 9 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li> <hr align=left><li><b>"Recycle or Burn: Hennepin County Incinerator"</b> (1987) A report on the incineratorproposed for downtown Minneapolis. &#169; Greenpeace. 28 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"Boston Harbor Toxics Project"</b> (1985) A report on toxic discharges into the BostonHarbor and its tributaries by companies along the harbor, nonpoint sources, and companiesconnected to the sewer system. &#169; Greenpeace. 20 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li> <hr align=left><li><b>"Incineration of Hazardous Waste"</b> (1985) A report of the hazards of andalternatives to the Stauffer Chemical Company's toxic waste incineration proposal. &#169; Greenpeace. 7 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li> <hr align=left><li><b>"License to Pollute: Discharge in Washington State"</b> (1985) A report on major toxicdischargers in Washington state whose permits were renewed under the Federal Clean WaterAct's "Pollution Permit" program, the National Pollutant Discharge Elimination System. &#169; Greenpeace. 97 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li><hr align=left></ul><p><h2>Greenpeace Public Information <a href="order_form.html">Order Form</a></h2><h3><a href="publist.html">Return</a> to the main Public Information Page</h3><p>If you have questions about these reports or about ordering these publications in quantity,pleasecontact our Public Information office by <a href="mailto:usa.supporter.services@green2.greenpeace.org">e-mail</a>,fax, orphone (Monday through Friday, 9:30am-5:30pm, EST).<P><b>Greenpeace Public Information<BR>1436 U Street NW<BR>Washington DC<BR>20009<BR>phone (202) 319-2444<BR>fax (202) 462-4507</b><P><i>Prices include shipping and handling. Availability of information is subject to change atany time. You will receive your order within two weeks of our receipt of your request (withpayment), unless the publication is out of print.<p><b>The lists are updated biannually and were last updated in September 1996.</b></i><p><CENTER><IM