<tr><td valign=top><H1>Greenpeace Toxic Trade Reports</H1><P>Reports are listed in chronological order according to publication date. Within each year,titles are listed in alphabetical order.</td><td valign=top>
<IMG VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10 SRC="pix/wt.gif" WIDTH=133
HEIGHT=152 ALT="Ban Waste Trade logo">
</tr></table><hr><ul><li><b>"Greenpeace Toxic Trade Update"</b> (1988-1994) Greenpeace no longer publishes thisnewsletter which summarized the international trade in toxic wastes, toxic products and toxictechnologies. &#169; Greenpeace International. Back issues are available for<br> <b>$3.00</b><i>each</i><br><b>Back issues also available via <a href="gopher://gopher.igc.apc.org:70/11/pubs/gptox">on-line  gopher.</a></b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"Waste Trade in the Mediterranean: Toxic Attack Against Lebanon"</b> (1995) In 1987,waste traders illegally exported 2,411 tons of toxic chemical waste from Italy to Lebanon. Theschemetook place during Lebanon's civil war which ended in 1990. The Italian government promised toretrieve all of the waste, but most of it remains scattered throughout Lebanon, and along theMediterranean shores. &#169; Greenpeace International. 34 pages plus notes andannexes<br><b>$10.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"Implementing the Basel Ban: The Way Forward"</b> (1995) This paper provides anapproach for implementing the United Nations' historic Basel Convention Decision II/2 whichprohibits the export of hazardous waste from Member States of the Organization for EconomicCooperation and Development (OECD) to non-OECD States. The paper was distributed at theGlobalWorkshop on the Implementation of Decision II/2 which took place in March 1995, in Dakar,Senegal. &#169; Greenpeace International. 13 pages plus appendices and copies of leakeddocumentsfrom the U.S. State Department, the European Union Commission, the International Chamber ofCommerce, and the U.S. Chamber of Commerce indicating full intent to overturn DecisionII/2.<br><b>$10.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"Greenpeace Submission to the Fourth Session of the London Tribunal on IndustrialHazardsand Human Rights on the Occasion of the Tenth Anniversary of the Bhopal Tragedy"</b> (1994)Tenyears after the tragic explosion at the Union Carbide chemical plant in Bhopal, India,chemicalizationof the planet continues. This report explains how the chemical industry is thriving despitecontinuedcontamination of the planet and countless industrial disasters. It focuses heavily on the expansionofthe chlorine industry in the Third World. It also provides a comprehensive list of substancesbannedfor use in one country or more, or targeted for elimination by a given date. &#169; GreenpeaceInternational. 20 pages including annexes<br> <b>$10.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"The Heavy Metal Content of MSW Incinerator Ash From the City of Philadelphia,Dumpedin Gonaives, Haiti"</b> (1995) Ash from a municipal waste incinerator in Philadelphia remains onabeach in Haiti, some eight years after the crew of the vessel Khian Sea dumped it there. InDecember1994, Greenpeace conducted an analysis of the toxic ash, and the soil and water in the vicinity ofthedumpsite. Six of eleven heavy metals analyzed were present at a higher concentration in the soilthanthey were in the ash itself. &#169; Greenpeace International. 9 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"The Transfer of Genetically Modified Organisms"</b> (1995) This report concludes aGreenpeace investigation into the potential for distributing and releasing genetically modifiedorganisms (GMOs) throughout the world. Greenpeace used regular postal services to sendostensiblydangerous packages around the world. Although labels on the packages identified the contents asbiohazards, the parcels actually contained mixtures of water and baker's yeast. Almost allpackagesarrived at their destinations unchecked. The report exposes the lack of control surrounding theinternational transport of GMOs. &#169; Greenpeace International. 9pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"The Greenpeace International Toxics Investigator Newsletter"</b> This quarterlynewslettercontains the latest information on industrial pollution, legislative measures to control pollution,andactivist movements to halt pollution. The text focuses heavily on the chlorine industry, its marketsandits expansion into the Third World. It also summarizes important developments in the cleanproductiontechnologies. &#169; Greenpeace International. Averages 16 pages. Annual subscriptionis<br><b>$10.00</b> <i>students</i><br><b>$20.00</b> <i>standard</i><br><b>$50.00</b> <i>corporations</i></li><hr align=left><li><b>"Death in Venice"</b> (1995) This report shows that the Venice Lagoon in Italy isextremelycontaminated with cancer-causing dioxins and furans. Sediments in the Lagoon showed levels ofcontamination up to 54,000 parts per billion. The report was written as part of a larger campaigntofight contamination of the Mediterranean Sea. &#169; Greenpeace International. 4pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"Chlorine Chemicals in Cod Liver Oil: The Threat to Food and Health"</b> (1995)Concernover contamination of the food chain by organochlorines led Greenpeace to commission anindependent analysis of fish oils (mainly cod liver oil) used as a dietary supplement. Significantlevels of organochlorine compounds were found in the oils. Twenty one of the samples werefound to contain detectable levels of organochlorine pesticides such as DDT and lindane, PCBsand the highly toxic chlorine by-product hexachlorobenzene. &#169; Greenpeace International. 6pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"Toward Clean Production: A Greenpeace Guide for Activists"</b> (1995) This guideillustrates how industrial waste management techniques and strategies have evolved and failed,andexplains how communities can move toward clean and sustainable production systems. This guideisproduced with the activist in mind. It is a reference tool for people who want their communities todevelop sustainably. It describes the environmental mistakes that industries have made in thewesternworld, and suggests methods of avoiding those mistakes. &#169; Greenpeace International. 144pages<br><b>$20.00</b> <i>(Available October 1995)</i></li> <hr align=left>  <li><b>"Toxic Waste in Disguise"</b> This is a series of fact sheets detailing the environmentalimplications of polyvinyl chloride (PVC). The packet is divided into ten fact sheets, providingoverviews of the PVC industry and efforts to phase out the use of PVC. Copies are available inDutch,English, French, German, Italian, and Spanish. &#169; Greenpeace International.<br><b>$10.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"Argumentos Para Una Prohibici&#243;n Total de la Importaci&#243;n de DesechosPeligrosos en Mexico"</b> (1994) This report argues that hazardous wastes should not beimportedinto Mexico under any circumstances, even under the pretext of further use or recycling. &#169; Greenpeace International. 24 pages<br><b>$10.00</b> <i>Available in Spanishonly</i></li> <hr align=left><li><b>"Database of Known Hazardous Waste Exports from OECD to Non-OECD Countries,1989-March 1994"</b> Greenpeace prepared this document for the Second Conference of Partiestothe Basel Convention, which took place in March 1994. The 154-page inventory is a compilationofstatistical data on Western wastes exported to Eastern Europe and the Third World over the pastfewyears under the pretext of recycling. The report also provides summaries of health andenvironmentalproblems associated with commonly exported wastes. &#169; Greenpeace International. 153 pages plus references<br><b>$20.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"Death on the Tracks"</b> (1994) Greenpeace released this short report on the Italiangovernment's efforts to rid its rail cars of asbestos. Many of Italy's old, asbestos-laden rail carshavedisappeared or been sent to Eastern Europe for use there. &#169; Greenpeace International 12pages<br><b>$10.00</b></li> <hr align=left><li><b>"Environmental Justice for All? How the U.S. Poisons South Africa"</b> (1994)Greenpeaceargues for an end to U.S. hazardous waste recycling in other countries by examining the companyBorden Chemicals and Plastics. In 1993 Borden shipped approximately 7.5 tons of mercuricchlorideto the Thor Chemicals mercury recycling facility in South Africa. The mercury trade in SouthAfricahas caused extensive harm to human health and the environment. &#169; GreenpeaceInternational.16 pages plus endnotes<br><b>$10.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"Lead Astray: The Poisonous Lead Battery Waste Trade"</b> (1994) Greenpeaceactivistsinvestigate the trail of discarded lead acid batteries from heavily industrialized countries(particularlyAustralia, the U.K., and the U.S.) to Asia and Latin America. &#169; Greenpeace International.29pages<br><b>$20.00</b></li> <hr align=left><li><b>"The Case for Prohibiting Hazardous Waste Exports, Including Recycling, From OECDtoNon-OECD Countries"</b> (1994) Greenpeace prepared this document for the Second Meetingof theConference of the Parties to the Basel Convention, which took place on March 21-25, 1994, inGeneva, Switzerland. The document is available in English, French and Spanish. &#169; Greenpeace International. 13 pages plus appendixes<br><b>$20.00</b></li> <hr align=left><li><b>"The Waste Invasion of Asia: A Greenpeace Inventory"</b> (1994) The latest in a seriesofwaste trade inventories, this report explains how Asia has become the favorite dumping region ofinternational waste brokers. Since 1990 Western countries have attempted to exportapproximately10.5 million tons to of waste to Asia. The inventory provides analysis of national and regionalwastetrade policies, statistical overviews of wastes imported, and brief summaries of waste tradeschemes. 94 pages<br><b>$20</b> from the<ul><li>Greenpeace Toxic Trade Campaign<br> 1436 U Street NW<br> Washington,DC<br> 20009<br> USA<br></li></ul> <i>Also available as a comic book,</i><b>"Waste Trade in Southeast Asia"</b> The comic bookisavailable in three editions: <i>English, Bahasa (Indonesian), and Tagalog (Filipino),</i> and isfreewith a self-addressed stamped envelope. <i>(Please specify which edition you arerequesting)</i>&#169; Greenpeace International</li><hr align=left><li><b>"Wasted Lives: Mercury Waste Recycling at Thor Chemicals"</b> (1994) This reportdescribes in shocking detail the history of mercury waste imports and recycling in South Africa.Through mercury poisoning the Thor facility has irreparably harmed human health and theenviroment. The facility has also stockpiled approximately 10,000 barrels of mercury wastes. &#169; Greenpeace International. 42 pages<br><b>$20.00</b></li> <hr align=left><li><b>"We've Been Had! Montreal's Plastic Dumped Overseas"</b> (1993) This report outlinesthe environmental effects of plastic, the problems of plastic recycling, and plastic exports fromQuebec. It also describes plastic import facilities in Asia. &#169; Greenpeace International. 13pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"Latin America: Toxic Dumping Ground?"</b> (1993) Greenpeace prepared this reportforthe UN-sponsored meeting of the Economic Commission on Latin America and the Caribbean,whichtook place in Santiago, Chile. This document describes the dangerous and growing trend towardrelocating toxic wastes, products, and technologies from heavily industrialized countries to LatinAmerica and the Caribbean. A companion video by the same name documents foreign wastedumping incidents in Honduras, Mexico, Bolivia, and Brazil, and features interviews withwaste-importing company officials and workers, and government officials. Both the report and thevideo are available in English and Spanish. &#169; Greenpeace International. 36pages<br><b>$10.00</b><br><b>$10.00</b> <i>Video version (VHS only)</i></li><hr align=left><li><b>"Poisons in Paradise"</b> (1993) Greenpeace produced this report in collaboration withthePesticides Action Network. It surveys Information on the availability, use, storage, and disposalofpesticides in the south Pacific to sketch the most comprehensive picture yet available on theirgrowinghealth and environmental effects on the region. &#169; Greenpeace International. 32 pages<br><b>$20.00</b></li> <hr align=left><li><b>"Russia: The Making of a Waste Colony"</b> (1993) In this report Greenpeacedocuments103 attempts by more than 100 firms to export 34 million tonnes of hazardous wastes fromGermany,Switzerland, Austria, Spain, Italy, and the U.S. to the territory of Russia. The figures indicate thatthe trade has increased dramatically, with 65 of the cases having been discovered since 1992. Afull 90% of the schemes involved some form of alleged recycling or further use. Greenpeacereports that either the recycling facilities do not exist or "further use" involves a highly pollutingoperation that would never be allowed in the west. Available in Russian, German, and English. &#169; Greenpeace International. 72 pages<br><b>$10.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"Annotations by Greenpeace International on the Agenda of the Meeting: Prepared fortheFirst Conference of Parties to the Basel Convention, November 30-December 4, 1992, Piriapolis,Uruguay"</b> This paper evaluates the Basel Convention on the Transboundary Movement ofHazardous Wastes. It includes stark examples of the failure of "Prior Informed Consent" and theneed for a total ban on waste exports. It also includes several examples of actual waste tradecontracts signed by government officials. &#169; Greenpeace International. 35pages<br><b>$10.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"The Need for a New Approach to Locust Control"</b> (1993) Greenpeace Internationalprepared this report for the FAO International Workshop on Research and Planning for DesertLocustControl held in Morocco, May 24-28, 1993. The report provides an overview of environmentalproblems relating to pesticides, quantifies the gravity of the locust plague, evaluates emergencyresponses to the plague, discusses the economics of the locust control program, and suggestsalternative methods of locust control. &#169; Greenpeace International. 11pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"Plastic Waste to Indonesia: The Invasion of the Little Green Dots"</b> (1993)Greenpeacedocuments 16 schemes to export wastes to Indonesia, all of which are sham recycling schemes.Copiesare available in English and German. &#169; Greenpeace International. 35pages<br><b>$10.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"Waste Trade Free Zone Community Action Kit"</b> (1993) This Greenpeace ToxicTradeCampaign resource is a campaigning tool for people trying to ban the international trade inwastes.The kit is a compilation of written material from the Greenpeace Waste Trade Project and severalnon-Greenpeace documents. It is designed for students, grassroots activists, community groups,church groups, and other interested parties who want their town officials to stop the export ofwastes from their communities. Although the main focus of the kit is the export of wastes, thetechniques, tools, and skills described can be used to campaign on any issue, from getting a roadrepaired to opposing the military budget. The kit is designed for activism in the U.S., but it couldbe used by activists in other countries. Includes valuable tips on how to lobby public officials,organize demonstrations, talk to the media, and more. &#169; Greenpeace. 70pages<br><b>$3.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"Wheels of Misfortune"</b> (1993) This report discusses a proposal by three tirerecyclingcompanies based in Houston, Texas, to ship more than 50,000 pounds of shredded tires to CentralAmerica to be burned in a cement kiln in Honduras. It also discusses environmental and healthproblems associated with the burning of tires. Greenpeace calls on the U.S. government and thestateof Texas to ban waste exports. &#169; Greenpeace. 10 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"The Greenpeace Book of Greenwash"</b> (1992) A look at corporate behavior exposesthereality hidden under the green image transnational corporations (TNCs) are creating. Despite theirnew rhetoric, TNCs are not saviors of the environment or of the world's poor. They remain theprimary creators and peddlers of dirty, dangerous, and unsustainable technologies. This bookletexamines nine corporations. &#169; Greenpeace. 32 pages<br><b>$10.00</b></li> <ul><li><i>Also available:</i> Greenwash case studies on ICI, Bayer, Siemens, ABB, Alcoa,BFI,Ciba-Geigy, Dow, International Paper, Mobil, Monsanto, and Norsk Hydro. &#169; Greenpeace.5pages each<br><b>$5.00</b> each.</li></ul> <hr align=left><li><b>"Dumping on our World Neighbors: The International Trade in Hazardous Wastes andtheCase for an Immediate Ban on All Hazardous Waste Exports from Industrialized toLess-Industrialized Countries"</b> (1992) This article appeared in the Green Globe Yearbook1992.The article gives an excellent overview of the international trade in toxic wastes. &#169; Greenpeace International. 14 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"FMC/Wath Recycling"</b> (1992) This report describes an international waste tradescandal that began n 1989 when U.S. waste brokers from Amlon Metals, Inc., purchased 403 tonsofheavily ontaminated copper hydroxide sludge from the U.S. multinational chemical company FMCCorporation. Amlon sent the waste to a UK metals reclamation plant called Wath Recycling,where it was discovered that the wastes were not what Wath had ordered. &#169; GreenpeaceInternational. 24 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"Romania: The Toxic Assault"</b> (1992) Greenpeace Germany produced this report,whichillustrates the illicit dumping of West European wastes in Romania. The report is available inEnglishand German. &#169; Greenpeace International. 35 pages<br><b>$10.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"U.S. Hazardous Waste Dumping in Bangladesh: The Toxic Fertilizer Crisis"</b> (1992)Greenpeace and the Dhaka-based organization UBINIG (Policy Research for DevelopmentAlternatives) produced this report, which documents the export and dumping of lead- andcadmium-contaminated fertilizer from the U.S. in Bangladesh. &#169; Greenpeace. 11 pages<br><b>$10.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"Waste Attacks on the New Baltic States: Waste Export Projects of Western CompaniestoLithuania, Latvia and Estonia"</b> (1989-1992) Greenpeace documents 19 waste export schemesinvolving the Baltic republics. Copies available in English and German. &#169; Greenpeace. 23pages<br><b>$10.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"We've Been Had! Seattle's Plastic Recycling Myth"</b> (1992) This report reveals themythof "recyclable" plastics in Seattle, Washington. It gives annual plastic waste export figures andanalysis of the largest plastic waste recycling facilities in the city. It also summarizes the plasticsrecycling industry in Asia. &#169; Greenpeace. 13 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"When Green is Not: The OECD's "Green" List As An Instrument of Hazardous WasteDe-Regulation"</b> (1992) This document provides a scientific and policy review of theOrganization for Economic Cooperation and Development’s recently adopted Red, Amber,Greenpolicy. &#169; Greenpeace International. 39 pages<br><b>$10.00</b></li> <hr align=left><li><b>"Avoiding Western Mistakes: A Guide to Clean Investment in Eastern and CentralEurope"</b> (1991) This document was prepared by Greenpeace International for the Conferenceonthe Environment, Industry, and Investment Decisions, November 20-22, 1991, in Budapest,Hungary. &#169; Greenpeace International. 38 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"Dumping by Another Name: The Recycling of Imported Hazardous Wastes in Bilbao,Spain, by the ASER Company"</b> (1991) This report reveals the devastating environmentalabusethat the city of Bilbao, Spain, has suffered from the importation of hazardous wastes in the formofmetal scraps, slags, and filter dusts. Greenpeace focuses on the ASER company, which releasesmanythousands of tons of heavy metals into the environment each year. The majority of the wastesprocessed by ASER (an estimated 61%) comes from heavily industrialized countries in northernEurope. &#169; Greenpeace International. 57 pages<br><b>$10.00</b> <i>Available in Spanishand English (please specify in order)</i></li><hr align=left><li><b>"German Waste in Essex"</b> (1991) This document uncovers the shipment of 470 tonsofGerman wastes to the UK. The wastes consisted of laboratory chemicals, paint thinners andresidues,sealants and solvents, and other toxic substances. Some of the waste was disposed of in Essex,UK, some was returned to Germany, and some was sent to Poland. &#169; Greenpeace International. 24 pages<br><b>$10.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"The Great Cover-Up: The Transport and Dumping of Foreign Hazardous Wastes inAlmad&#233;n, Spain"</b> (1991) This report, produced by Greenpeace Spain and GreenpeaceInternational, exposes an international environmental disaster that occurred on the property of amineowned by the Spanish government, known as Minas de Almadén. Throughout the 1980s at least25industries, from Australia, France, Germany, Italy, the Netherlands, Norway, Sweden,Switzerland,the UK, and the U.S., sent their mercury-contaminated hazardous wastes to the remote ruraldistrict ofcentral Spain. The wastes were intended for recycling but were simply stored in five dump sitesopen to the weather. &#169; Greenpeace International. 50 pages<br><b>$10.00</b><i>Available inEnglish and Spanish (please specify in order)</i></li><hr align=left><li><b>"The Single European Dump: Free Trade in Hazardous and Nuclear Wastes in the NewEurope"</b> (1991) This document illustrates how the union of the European EconomicCommunityspells environmental doom for the continent. The EEC Treaty gives precedence to marketconsiderations over environmental ones in many instances. With the new economic legislation,hazardous waste will move freely around the continent and be difficult to monitor and control.The report concludes that without dramatic amendments to the EEC Treaty itself, a singleEuropean market can easily become a single European dump. &#169; Greenpeace International.32pages<br><b>$10.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"The Toxic Threat to Indian Lands"</b> (1991) This report discusses how majorpollutingindustries in the U.S. have threatened the sovereignty of Native Americans and attempted toexploittheir environment. The report cites 53 different industrial schemes to develop large waste disposalfacilities on Indian lands. &#169; Greenpeace. 17 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"Poland: The Waste Invasion"</b> (1990) Greenpeace reveals 65 waste trade schemes inwhich Poland was targeted as the recipient of Western hazardous wastes. Most of the schemeswereplotted during 1989 and 1990. The tally represents only 6 months of research and collection. &#169; Greenpeace International. 47 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"Pollution for the Marshall Islands Equals Profits for the U.S."</b> (1990) An UpdatedGreenpeace Report on Admiralty Pacific's and Micromar's Proposals to Export U.S. Waste to theMarshall Islands. &#169 Greenpeace International. 23 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"Michigan's International Waste Imports: An Inventory of Canadian Waste ShipmentsintoMichigan - 1988-1991"</b> This report reveals all the Canadian notifications that the U.S.Environmental Protection Agency received for proposed hazardous waste imports into Michiganfrom 1988 through February 1991. Canadian companies proposed shipping over 11,653 loadstotalling 83 million gallons (301 million liters or 665 pounds) of hazardous waste to Michiganduring these four years. &#169; Greenpeace. 41 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"Waste Traders Target the Marshall Islands"</b> (1989) A Greenpeace Report onAdmiraltyPacific's Proposal to Dispose of U.S. Municipal Garbage in the Marshall Islands. &#169;GreenpeaceInternational. 32 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"Burnt Offerings I"</b> (September 1987) and <b>"Burnt Offerings II"</b> (February1988). These two reports chronicle plans to dump Philadelphia’s incinerator ash in Panama anditsactual dumping in Haiti. &#169 Greenpeace. 44 pages<br><b>$5.00</b> <i>each</i></li><hr align=left><li><b>"Never Registered Pesticides: Rejected Toxics Join the Circle of Poison: Four CaseStudies ofPesticides Manufactured by DowElanco, Mobay Corporation, and Monsanto AgriculturalCompany"</b> (1990) Case studies of four pesticides banned from U.S. use but exportedoverseas.Examines U.S. pesticide export policy and problems. &#169 Greenpeace. 26 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li><hr align=left></ul><p><h2>Greenpeace Public Information <a href="order_form.html">Order Form</a></h2><h3><a href="publist.html">Return</a> to the main Public Information Page</h3><p>If you have questions about these reports or about ordering these publications in quantity,pleasecontact our Public Information office by <a href="mailto:usa.supporter.services@green2.greenpeace.org">e-mail</a>,fax, orphone (Monday through Friday, 9:30am-5:30pm, EST).<P><b>Greenpeace Public Information<BR>1436 U Street NW<BR>Washington DC<BR>20009<BR>phone (202) 319-2444<BR>fax (202) 462-4507</b><P><i>Prices include shipping and handling. Availability of information is subject to change atany time. You will receive your order within two weeks of our receipt of your request (withpayment), unless the publication is out of print.<p><b>The lists are updated biannually and were last updated in September 1996.</b></i><p><CENTER><IMG SRC="pix/rnbwbar.gif"><H2>...Because our kids deserve a future</H2><IMG SRC="pix/rnbwbar.gif"></CENTER><P><H5>Greenpeace Waste Trade logo by Keith Haring  &#169; Greenpeace 1991</H5><pre></pre></BODY></HTML>
