<HEAD>
<TITLE>Greenpeace USA Ocean Ecology and Biodiversity Reports</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FF FF FF" TEXT="#00 00 80" LINK="#00 80 00" VLINK="#80 00 00" 
ALINK="#FF FF 00" basefont=3>
<table width=100% border=0><tr><td colspan=2 align=right valign=top>
<a href="/~usa/index.html"><img src="pix/pub_vid.gif" WIDTH=504 HEIGHT=101 border=0></a>
</td></tr>
<tr><td valign=top>
<H1>Greenpeace Ocean Ecology and Biodiversity Reports</H1>
Reports are listed in chronological order according to publication date. Within each year,
titles are listed in alphabetical order.
</td>
<td valign=top>
<IMG SRC="pix/publist.gif" WIDTH=154 HEIGHT=156 ALT="Photo of 3 Greenpeace Reports">
</td></tr>
</table>
<hr>
<ul>
<li><b>"Sinking Fast: How Factory Trawlers Are Destroying U.S. Fisheries and Marine Ecosystems"</b> 
(1996) This report examines the rise of massive industrial-scale factory fishing trawlers and the damage
caused to marine ecosystems by these floating factories. &#169; Greenpeace.<br><b>Only available <a href="/~usa/reports/biodiversity/sinking_fast/index.html">on-line</a></b></li>
<hr align=left>
<li><b>"The Big Business Takeover of U.S. Fisheries: Privatising the Oceans through ITQ's"</b> 
(1995) This report examines the issue of ITQ’s and their detrimental effect on small scale
fisheries and the debate over privatization. &#169; Greenpeace.  21 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li>
<hr align=left>
<li><b>"Genetically Engineered Plants: Releases and Impacts on Less Developed Countries"</b> 
(1994) Plants represent one of the fastest growing applications of genetic engineering with the
possibilty of causing serious environmental damage.  This study shows the hollow promises on
which genetic engineering is sold and the use of less developed countries as testing grounds and
Greenpeace's oppostion to the release of all genetically manipulated organisms. (Submitted to the
first conference of parties of the convention on biological diversity). &#169; Greenpeace
International. 44 pages<br> 
<b>$5.00</b></li>
<hr align=left>
<li><b>"A Precautionary Approach to Fisheries"</b> (1994) 
&#169; Greenpeace International. 6 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li>
<hr align=left>
<li><b>"Fisheries on the Brink: Major Trends in Global Fisheries"</b> (1994) &#169;
Greenpeace International. 12 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li>
<hr align=left>
<li><b>"Greenpeace Fisheries Index"</b> (1994) A list of some surprising, current facts about
fishing. &#169; Greenpeace. 2 pages<br><b>No charge</b></li>
<hr align=left>
<li><b>"And Then There Were None: Overfishing and Ocean Ecosystems in the Northeast
Pacific"</b> (1993) This report looks at the problems plaguing the U.S. fisheries, by focusing on
the Northeast Pacific fishery, the largest single fishery in the world. &#169; Greenpeace. 12
pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li>
<hr align=left>
<li><b>"Groundfish Fisheries and Dynamics of Northeastern Pacific Ecosystems"</b> (1993) An
independent, in-depth report on the large scale, nearly irreparable destruction of the Northeastern
Pacific ecosystems. Includes suggested solutions. &#169; Greenpeace. 44
pages<br><b>$10.00</b></li>
<hr align=left>
<li><b>"In The Race for Tuna... Dolphins Aren't the Only Sacrifice"</b> (1993) This report
exposes the myth of "dolphin safe" tuna and how it is used as a PR ploy by the powerful tuna
industry, which encourages reckless, uncontrolled fishing in most of the world's oceans and
contributes to the growing global fisheries crisis. &#169; Greenpeace International. 20
pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li>
<hr align=left>
<li><b>"It Can't Go On Forever: The Implications of the Global Grab for Declining Fish
Stocks"</b> (1993) Fishing today is a massive global industry with the capability to radically alter
the balance of nature in marine ecosystems around the world, with devastating consequences. This
report examines the implications of this crisis and offers the Greenpeace approach to fisheries.
&#169; Greenpeace International. 20 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li>
<hr align=left>
<li><b>"Whales In A Changing Ocean"</b> (1993) A look at the threats to the marine
environment, home to the great whale populations, posed by human activities. Threats include
climate change; decreased protection from UV-B radiation by the diminishing ozone layer;
pollution by organochlorine compounds; and increasingly intensive fisheries. &#169; Greenpeace
International. 29 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li>
<hr align=left>
<li><b>"The Barents Sea: A Pantry"</b> (1991) Translation of a report published by Greenpeace
Norway covering seabirds, fisheries, sealing, petroleum, and nuclear weapons issues. 
&#169; Greenpeace. 35 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li>
<hr align=left>
<li><b>"Disappearing Dolphins"</b> (1991) A report on problems affecting small cetaceans
throughout the world. &#169; Greenpeace. 25 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li>
<hr align=left>
<li><b>"A Review of the Bioaccumulative Effects of Pollution on Marine Turtles"</b> (1991) 
&#169; Greenpeace. 30 pages<br><b>$10.00</b></li>
<hr align=left>
<li><b>"World Driftnet Map"</b> (1991) This map shows the waters where the driftnet fleets
"stripmine the sea" and driftnetting's devastating effect on target fish populations and the entire
marine ecosystem. &#169; Greenpeace.<br><b>$5.00</b></li>
<hr align=left>
<li><b>"The Baltic Sea: Live or Let Die"</b> (1990) &#169; Greenpeace International. 30
pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li>
<hr align=left>
<li><b>"Greenpeace: Mediterranean"</b> (1990) &#169; Greenpeace International. 20
pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li>
<hr align=left>
<li><b>"International Coral Reef NGO Directory"</b> This directory contains a list of
International NGO's committed to improving the prognosis for coral reefs and averting the serious
consequences from destruction of reefs for marine life and humans. 48 pages<br>
<ul><li>Available from:<br><i>The Center for Clean Development<br>1227 W. 10th
St.<br>Eugene, OR<br>97402<br>USA</i></li></ul><b>$5.00</b></li>
<hr align=left>
</ul>
