<H1>Greenpeace Magazine Index (1982-1992)</H1>
Greenpeace in the U.S. regularly published a magazine between 1982-1992.  
This index lists back-issues of the magazine in reverse chronological order 
by publication date.  The feature articles appearing in each issue are 
indicated.</p><p>Each back-issue (if available) is <b>$2.00</b>. 
Photocopies of individual articles from each issue are <b>$2.00</b> 
per article.</td><td valign=top>
<IMG VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10 SRC="pix/gpmag.gif" WIDTH=123HEIGHT=160 ALT="Image of GP magazine"></td></tr></table>
<h2>Also available</h2><p><b>"Greenpeace Quarterly"</b> Published quarterly, this magazine keeps you up to dateon the issues and what we're doing to help create a green and peaceful planet.  Available toGreenpeace <a href="/~usa/membership/membership.html">members</a> for an annual<b>$30.00</b> donation.<hr>
<p><ul><li><b>January/February/March 1992<i> (Final Issue)</i></b><br>   Corporate Fronts: Inside the Anti-Environmental Movement<br>    Our Twentieth Anniversary (Greenpeace History)<br>California's Peregrine Paradox</li><hr align=left><li><b>October/November/December 1991</b><br>     Home Street USA: Living with Pollution<br>After Desert Storm, The Deluge<br>Not Getting the Lead Out (Exporting leaded gasoline to developing countries)<br>Barren Harvest (Toxic pesticides in Costa Rica)</li><hr align=left><li><b>July/August 1991</b><br>Who Owns Alaska? (Big business vs. citizens)<br>The Fate of the Stellers (Sea lions, factory trawlers)<br>Why Not Here? Green Politics in America</li><hr align=left><li><b>May/June 1991</b><br>Green Like Me (Public relations hype)<br>Fueling the Fantasy (Geothermal energy/Hawaiian rainforests)<br>The Dioxin Deception (Paper manufacture and bleaching)</li><hr align=left><li><b>March/April 1991</b><br>What Price Oil? (War in the Gulf)<br>Open Season (Lake Ontario)<br>Power Ploy (National Energy Strategy)<br>At Our Peril: False Promise of Risk Assessment<br>Exploding the Great Secret (Moruroa)</li><hr align=left><li><b>January/February 1991</b><br>The Children of Chernobyl (Eyewitness account)<br>Target Novaya Zemlaya: The Soviet Nuclear Test Zone<br>Sharks on the Line (Overfishing)<br>How to Stop Incinerators: A Community Manual</li><hr align=left><li><b>November/December 1990</b><br> Will the Dolphins Survive? (Global survey)<br>Fiddling While the World Burns (Greenhouse)<br>Deadly Secret of the Deep (Driftnets, Rainbow Warrior)</li><hr align=left><li><b>September/October 1990</b><br> The Forever Forests (Timber politics vs. ecosystem)<br>Trading Away the Planet (General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade)<br>Taking Off the Gloves (Environmentalists harassed)</li><hr align=left><li><b>July/August 1990</b><br>    Defenders of the Rainforest (Borneo)<br>Snake Oil: Washington's Pitch for Offshore Oil<br>So Much Hot Air (Ozone, DuPont, CFCs)<br>Reefs on the Rocks (Coral reef development)</li><hr align=left><li><b>May/June 1990</b><br>A Bill of Goods? Green Consuming in Perspective<br>Car Sick: Automobiles Ad Nauseam (Global spread)<br>Of Apartheid and Pollution (South Africa poisons)<br>The Bummers: 12 Nuclear Bombs that Could Ruin the  90s</li><hr align=left><li><b>March/April 1990</b><br>The Agony of Tibet (Genocide and ecological damage)<br>The Folly of Trident (Greenpeace protests)<br>Covering the World, Ignoring the Earth (Press)</li><hr align=left><li><b>January/February 1990</b><br> How Can We Save It? (Where do we go from here?)<br>What Works: Oral History of Five Greenpeace Campaigns<br>Not in Anyone's Backyard (Toxics)</li><hr align=left><li><b>November/December 1989</b><br> Can Rock and Roll Save the World?<br>The Disease of Development (DDT in Amazon)<br>Second Chance (Sea turtles, Turtle Excluder Devices)</li><hr align=left><li><b>September/October 1989</b><br> The Ivory Trail (Elephants)<br>Why We Have Failed (Environmental legislation)<br>Crime in the Suites</li><hr align=left><li><b>July/August 1989</b><br> The Emerald Desert (Water management)<br>Fish Story (Dolphins)<br>Naval Nuclear Accidents</li><hr align=left><li><b>May/June 1989</b><br>Nuclear Free Seas Comes of Age <br>The Heat Is On (Greenhouse effect)<br>Nasty Business (Hazardous waste)<br>How One Rainforest Was Saved<br>What's Behind the Spills<br>Throw the Dinosaur a Bone (Nuclear power)</li><hr align=left><li><b>March/April 1989</b><br> Queensland's Last Stand (Rainforest)<br>Whitewash: The Dioxin Cover-Up<br>Indonesia's Pest Management Miracle (Pesticides)<br>The Ties that Blind (Australia and nuclear testing)</li><hr align=left><li><b>January/February 1989</b><br>Rising Storm in the Pacific (Conflict, struggle, and hope)<br>The New Economics: Accounting for a Healthy Planet<br>The System Works (Recycling)</li><hr align=left><li><b>November/December 1988</b><br> The Seal Plague (North Sea)<br>Return to Sender (Waste trade)<br>Is Poland Lost? (Environmental problems)<br>Satellite Views of Amazon</li><hr align=left><li><b>September/October 1988</b><br>   On Thin Ice (Antarctica)<br>Weird Science (Science and whaling)<br>You Are My River (Mississippi toxics)<br>Protection Act of 1972<br>Persistent and Poisonous (Toxics in the market)</li><hr align=left><li><b>July/August 1988</b><br> The Politics of Radiation (Public health)<br>A Desert of Waters (Great Lakes)<br>Nuclear Testing at the Crossroads (Limited and Comprehensive Test Ban Treaties)<br>Dolphins Threatened</li><hr align=left><li><b>May/June 1988</b><br> Rising from the Ashes (Garbage incineration)<br>The Death of Ellenton (Plutonium in South Carolina)</li><hr align=left><li><b>March/April 1988</b><br> A Sea of Troubles (Ocean incineration)<br>Small Wonders (Energy conservation)</li><hr align=left><li><b>October/December 1987</b><br>Loose Cannons: The Nuclear Navies<br>A Forgotten War (Rainforests)<br>The Toxic Cloud (Air pollution)</li><hr align=left><li><b>July/September 1987</b><br>Taking Action: Higher Law of the Nuclear Age<br>Living Next to the Landfill (Toxic waste)<br>Diet for a Poisoned Planet (Pesticides)<br>Antarctica</li><hr align=left><li><b>April/June 1987</b><br>The Tangled Web (Driftnets, South Pacific)<br>A Return to Nuclear Disarmament<br>Cry of the Beluga (St. Lawrence River)<br>The Doom of Damocles (Nuclear weapons)</li><hr align=left><li><b>January/March 1987</b><br>Unbalanced Coverage: Failure of the U.S. Media<br>And Then There Were None (Sea turtles)<br>Going to the Source (Solution to toxic waste)<br>Platform Removal (Derricks' threat to marine life)<br>The Rainbow Warrior Bombing (Auckland, NZ)</li><hr align=left><li><b>October/December 1986</b><br> Fifteen Years at the Front Lines (Early campaigns)<br>Green and Peace: A Visionary Link<br>Whaling at the Crossroads (IWC Malmo meeting)</li><hr align=left><li><b>June 1986</b><br>Water for Life (Bering Sea, Alaska, Australia, Mediterranean, ocean floor, Great Lakes)<br>Chernobyl<br>The Saga of Windscale: Profits at Any Cost<br>In Nevada: The Hike to Stop Nuclear Testing<br>Reunion in the Marshalls Continues "Voyage for Life"</li><hr align=left><li><b>March 1986</b><br>Peace Now: Security in the Nuclear Age<br>Summit Time (U.S.-Soviet weapons negotiations)<br>Citizens to EPA, Chem Waste: Ban the Burn<br>Round, Round It Goes (Ocean incineration)<br>Driftnets: Economy Joins Ecology<br>Awed by the Majesty (Antarctic, M/V Greenpeace)<br>On the Beach: A Shipwreck's Deadly Legacy<br>Seismic Testing (Oregon, ARCO)</li><hr align=left><li><b>December 1985</b><br>Antarctica<br>L'Affaire Greenpeace (Bombing of the Rainbow Warrior)</li><hr align=left><li><b>September 1985</b><br>Seal Hunt Subsides in the Pribilofs<br>Sabotage and Sorrow but the Spirit Survives  (Rainbow Warrior)<br>Taking the First Step (Nuclear testing)<br>A Summer's Sail for Water and Life (Great Lakes)<br>Sirius Escape (Belgian chemical dumping)</li><hr align=left><li><b>April/June 1985</b><br>On the Fresh Inland Seas (Great Lakes)<br>The End to a Decade of Harp Seal Hunts<br>A Tale of Justice Withheld (Whaling)<br>For Their Children (Rongelap, South Pacific nuclear tests)<br>By What Right? (Nuclear, Elbe 1945 vs. Geneva 1985)</li><hr align=left><li><b>January/March 1985</b><br> Killing Wolves to Kill Moose (Alaska wildlife)<br>Verging on Chaos in the Virgin Continent<br>Assault on the Whales (Soviets, International Whaling Commission limit)<br>The Meek Shall Lose the Earth (Interview with David Brower)<br>Ocean Incineration<br>Nuclear Winter<br>Rainbow Warrior</li><hr align=left><li><b>Winter 1984</b><br>Objectors' Strategies Take New Direction (Whaling)<br>Pribilof Seals Face Uncertain Future<br>Women Tend the Fires of Hope<br>The Odontocetes (Pull-out poster)<br>The Aleyka: Taking on Toxic Dumpers<br>How's the Water?  The Verdict's Not Good</b>Radwaste Accidents Terrorize UK Coast</li><hr align=left><li><b>Fall 1984</b><br>Toxics by the Sea (Titanium Dioxide)<br>From Air, Land, and Sea (Disarmament)<br>Can Paradise Lost Be Found? (Marshall Islands)<br>United Against Uranium Mining (Roxby Downs)<br>Unnatural Selection (Kangaroo)<br>Rich Estate Seeks Guardian (Antarctica)<br>Trouble for the Whales<br>Whodunit? The Killer is Plastic<br>Pribilofs: Speaking Silently for the Seals<br>Dolphins: Turning Past Companions into Captives</li> <hr align=left><li><b>Spring 1984</b><br> Going Up Against Poison in the Sky<br>Memorial Trek to the Test Site<br>Objectors Tactic Paving the Way<br>Dimes? Dollars? It's for the Future<br>Dolphins Get Their Day in Court<br>Lowering a Sonic Boom on Whales<br>Alaskan Coastline Pushed to the Limit<br>Stormy Skies Over the Seal Hunt<br>Dynamite Defused for the Penguins</li><hr align=left><li><b>Winter 1983</b><br>Peru Pressed to Retract International Whaling Commission Objection<br>Dolphin Protection Set Back Ten Years  (Tuna, Marine Mammal Protection Act)</li><hr align=left><li><b>Fall 1983</b><br> Memories of a Siberian Sojourn<br>The Warrior Goes Wind Power<br>Whaling Industry Sinking Fast<br>Hot Debate over the Frozen Continent<br>Protesters Link Up to Stem the Toxic Tide<br>Nuclear Waste Dumpers Blocked at the Docks</li><hr align=left><li><b>Summer 1983</b><br> Industries Turn Their Waste Into Profit<br>Nuclear Madness Ad Infinitum (Spent nuclear fuel)<br>Doing the Whalers Shuffle at the International Whaling Commission (IWC)<br>Invisible Killer: This Ghost Is Real (Ghost nets)<br>Captive Orcas: Must the Show Go On? (Seaworld) <br>On-Site Protest at the Nevada Test Site<br>Plugging Away at the Chesapeake Bay</li><hr align=left><li><b>Spring 1983</b><br> 128,000 Seal Pups Saved<br>Protesters Delay Outer Continental Shelf Seismic Testing<br>Behind the Campaign (Life on the Rainbow Warrior)<br>Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty: A Step Toward Peace (Disarmament)<br>Navy's Sub Dump Plan Meets Bold Resistance</li><hr align=left><li><b>Winter 1982</b><br>Prisoners of War (Military use of Beluga whales)<br> The U.S. Dolphin Kill (Tuna fleets)<br>Fighting for Air (Clean Air Act)<br>North Sea Showdown (Ocean dumping)<br>Trouble in Paradise (French testing at Moruroa)<br>Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty: Farewell to Arms</li><hr align=left><li><b>Fall 1982</b><br>Another Captive Orca Dies<br>Industries Close Plant (Raritan Bay, NJ)<br>Debunking the Myth of Jobs vs. Ecology<br>Protest at Toxic Falls (Niagara)<br>Dutch End Nuclear Dumping After Epic Campaign</li><hr align=left><li><b>Summer 1982</b><br>    International Whaling Commission (IWC) Votes to End Commercial Whaling by 1985<br>Dalls Porpoise (Incidental kill by Japanese fishermen)<br>Ocean Dumping (New York Blight)<br>U.S. Nuclear Testing at Belau (South Pacific)</li><hr align=left></ul><pre></pre><h2>Greenpeace Public Information <a href="order_form.html">Order Form</a></h2><h3><a href="publist.html">Return</a> to the main Public Information Page</h3><p>If you have questions about these issues or about ordering in quantity,  please contact ourPublicInformation office by <a href="mailto:usa.supporter.services@green2.greenpeace.org">e-mail</a>, fax, or phone(Monday through Friday, 9:30am-5:30pm, EST).<P><b>Greenpeace Public Information<BR>1436 U Street NW<BR>Washington DC<BR>20009<BR>phone (202) 319-2444<BR>fax (202) 462-4507</b><P><i>Prices include shipping and handling. Availability of  printed copies of  these magazines issubject to change at any time. You will receive your order within two weeks of our receipt ofyourrequest (with payment), unless the publication is out of print.<p><b>This list is updated biannually and was last updated in September 1996.</b></i><pre></pre><CENTER><IMG SRC="pix/rnbwbar.gif"><H2>...Because our kids deserve a future</H2><IMG SRC="pix/rnbwbar.gif"></CENTER><P><H5>photo on cover of Greenpeace magazine &#169; Robin Heid/Greenpeace 1984, cat.#0.84.50.01.09</H5><pre></pre></BODY></HTML>
