<td align=right><tt><b><font size=+2>
Changing Targets:<br>
Nuclear Doctrine from the Cold War<br>to the Third World
</font></b></tt>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>
<b>[Revised and abridged version for the Internet]</b><br>
<font size=-1>
An early version of this paper was released on 26 January 1995 at the Fourth Preparatory
Committee Meeting in New York for the April 1995 Conference of the Parties to the 
Non-Proliferation Treaty. This on-line version is presented without the attachments and
appendices available <b>only</b> in the printed version.  To order the printed version, please send 
$5.00 with a completed copy of the <a href="/~usa/pubinfo/order_form.html">USA Public 
Information order form</a> to our USA Public Information office.</font>
<p>
<b>Written by Hans M. Kristensen and Joshua Handler</b><br>
<i>Greenpeace International</i><br>
<p>
1 March 1995
<hr>
<i>About the Authors:</i>
<p>
<font size=-1>Hans M. Kristensen is a research associate with Greenpeace's Disarmament Campaign in
Washington.  He is co-author of Neptune Papers No. 6 (US Naval Nuclear Weapons in Sweden,
October 1990) and No. 7 (Aircraft Carriers: The Limits of Nuclear Power, June 1994), and has
written numerous articles and background papers on nuclear weapons issues.  He coordinated the
Greenpeace Nuclear Free Seas Campaign in Scandinavia from 1987 to 1991.
<p>
Joshua Handler is research coordinator for Greenpeace's Disarmament Campaign.  Aside
from co-authoring the Neptune Papers series, he is the author of numerous articles and reports
about the nuclear arms race at sea and the U.S. and Russian militaries.
<p>
The authors would like to acknowledge the input and contributions made to this paper by
Stephanie Mills of Greenpeace International, Ben Cramer of Greenpeace France, and William
Peden of Greenpeace U.K.</font>
<p>
<hr>
