<p>
<hr>
<a name="intro"></a>
<p>
<font size=+2><b>I. Introduction</b></font>
<p>
The United States and the United Kingdom, along with their NATO allies, still retain
hundreds of nuclear bombs "forward deployed" in half a dozen European countries, including: 
Belgium, Germany, Greece, Italy, Netherlands and, Turkey.  The United States, moreover, bases
U.S. nuclear weapons in the United Kingdom.  Although NATO's North Atlantic Council
predicted in November 1991 that arms control agreements would "result in an unprecedented
degree of military transparency in Europe, thus increasing stability and mutual confidence," the
number and precise location of the nuclear bombs remain cloaked in military secrecy.
<p>
With end of the Cold War and the disappearance of the threat of a large-scale military
attack on Europe due to the break-up of the Soviet Union and the demise of the Warsaw Pact,
NATO has now outlined a more general mission for its nuclear forces of "maintaining peace" and
"preventing war," as well as countering the alleged threat from Middle Eastern and other
countries seeking to acquire nuclear weapons.
<p>
The role of these nuclear weapons has been a matter of some controversy.  In the context
of NATO eastward expansion debate many questions are being raised about what the extension of
NATO nuclear guarantees to new member states would mean.  Also, the basing of these weapons
in non-nuclear NATO countries was the subject of a major dispute at the historic Review and
Extension Conference of the <b>Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty (NPT)</b> in New York in April-May
1995.  <b>Article I</b> of the <b>Treaty</b> prohibits the transfer of nuclear weapons by a nuclear weapons state
to any state, whether a party to the <b>Treaty</b> or not, whether a nuclear-weapons state or not, and
whether the transfer takes place directly or indirectly.  <b>Article II</b> prohibits non-nuclear weapons
states from receiving nuclear weapons or control over nuclear weapons directly or indirectly.
<p>
Many non-nuclear countries at the conference questioned whether the basing of U.S.
nuclear weapons in non-nuclear NATO countries is compatible with the <b>NPT's Article I and II</b>. 
Some even suggested it contravenes the Treaty.  Except for about 90 bombs stored in Britain, all
of the U.S. nuclear bombs in Europe are stationed in non-nuclear countries.  All of which,
however, are actively involved in NATO nuclear planning, and all allocate and train national
military personnel in peacetime to deliver U.S. nuclear weapons currently deployed on their soil.
<p>
This report provides an overview of the hundreds of U.S. and British nuclear bombs
currently deployed in Europe.  It also outlines the stated rationales attributed to these weapons by
NATO and the United States, and it discusses their implications for the <b>NPT</b> regime.  An earlier
version of the report was distributed at the <b>NPT</b> Conference in April-May 1995 and was cited
extensively during Main Committee I discussion on compliance with <b>Articles I, II</b> and <b>VI</b> of the
<b>NPT</b>.  This earlier version was covered in the Belgian, Dutch, French, Greek, and Italian media. 
In response to questions raised by the report, the Belgian Air Force Chief of Staff confirmed on
Belgian television that "there are indeed nuclear weapons in Belgium" and six other European
countries.
<a name="europe"></a>
<p>
<font size=+2><b>II. NATO and Nuclear Weapons In Europe</b></font>
<p>
During 1991-92 the United States made large reductions in land-based nuclear weapons
forward deployed in Europe.  In September 1991, President Bush announced the withdrawal to
the United States of all overseas U.S. ground-launched nuclear weapons and naval nuclear depth
bombs.  Britain and Russia also responded to his initiative by taking similar steps.  At the NATO
Nuclear Planning Group (NPG) meeting in Taormina, Sicily, in October 1991, the NPG endorsed
an 80 percent cut in tactical nuclear weapons in Europe.
<p>
Since 1991-1992, however, no plans have developed for further reducing the number of
U.S. nuclear weapons in Europe.  NATO, in fact, has reiterated its commitment to keeping U.S.
nuclear weapons in Europe.  At the North Atlantic Council meeting in Rome in November 1991,
the NATO heads of state announced a new Strategic Concept which concluded that, "the
presence of ... US nuclear forces in Europe remain vital to the security of Europe."  The meeting
agreed to "maintain for the foreseeable future an appropriate mix of nuclear and conventional
forces in Europe" and upgrade them as necessary.
<p>
Two types of nuclear bombs are currently forward deployed in Europe:  U.S. B61s and
British WE-177A/Bs.  The B61 tactical nuclear bomb is deployed by the U.S. Air Force, and has
a selective yield ranging from less than one kiloton to 175 kilotons.  The B61 exists in three
versions:  Mod-3, -4, and -10.  The Mod-10 is a converted W85 nuclear warhead that was
previously deployed in Europe on Pershing II missiles that were withdrawn under the <b>1987 INF
Treaty</b>.  The United Kingdom deploys the WE-177A/B nuclear free-fall bomb.  The A version
has a yield of up to 200 kilotons, the B version up to 400 kilotons.
<p>
The nuclear bombs are assigned to A-7, F-15, F-16, and Tornado aircraft.  The United
States has dual-capable F-16 Falcons at Aviano Air Base (AB) in Northern Italy, and rotates F-16s from bases in the United States to Ramstein AB, Germany, and Incirlik AB in Turkey.  It also
deploys two squadrons of F-15E Eagles at RAF Lakenheath in the United Kingdom.  U.S. B61
bombs are also assigned to Belgian F-16s at Kleine Brogel AB, German Tornados at Buechel AB,
Memmingen AB, and Norvenich AB, Italian Tornados at Ghedi-Torre, Dutch F-16s at Volkel
AB in the Netherlands, Turkish F-16s at Balikesir AB and Murted AB, as well as Greek ex-US
Navy A-7 Corsairs at Araxos AB are also assigned U.S. B61 nuclear bombs.  Finally, Britain
deploys four squadrons of Tornado planes with WE-177A/B nuclear bombs at RAF Br&#252;ggen in
Germany, but these will be loose their nuclear capability in 1998 with the British announcement to
scrap all WE-177 bombs.  (The WE-177s were introduced between 1966 and 1971 and, with an
estimated life of 25 years, were approaching retirement in any event).
<a name="where"></a>
<p>
<font size=+1>A. Where the Bombs Are</font>
<p>
Seven European countries are thought to host foreign nuclear weapons.  
They include Belgium, Germany, Greece, Italy, Netherlands, Turkey, and United Kingdom.  
Six of these nations are participants in secret programs (called "Programs of
Cooperation") where their equipment is certified to deliver nuclear bombs (the exception 
is the United Kingdom, which has its own nuclear bombs).  An Allied Command Europe Nuclear
Operations Plan is published by SHAPE (Supreme Headquarters Allied Powers Europe).
<p>
The nuclear bombs are stored at 14 European bases, 13 of which host U.S. bombs.  Four 
of the bases are U.S. Air Force bases, while nine are operated by the host
country's armed forces.  Britain has four nuclear-capable Tornado squadrons based at 
RAF Br&#252;ggen, Germany, that are thought to carry the WE-177A/B nuclear bomb.
<p>
Over the last 10 years, the number of nuclear air bases in Europe has decreased by 
almost 50 percent, from 23 in 1985 to 14 in 1995.  The reduction has 
been most dramatic in Britain, Germany, and Turkey.
<p>
There have been rumors that nuclear bombs may have been removed from Belgian, German,
Greek, and Dutch air bases.  However, the governments of these countries have not 
commented on these speculations, and the indications are that the weapons still remain.  
The U.S. Nuclear Posture Review's (NPR) in September 1994 decided to retain the 
"current strength" of nuclear bombs in Europe.  Also, President Clinton's February 1995 
National Security Strategy report said the United States was committed to the "current 
posture and deployment of non-strategic nuclear forces."  The bases in question 
continue to be nuclear certified and staffed by nuclear weapons personnel.  Following 
release of the earlier version of this report on 18 April 1995, the Belgian Air Force 
Chief of Staff, Lieutenant General G. Vanhecke, confirmed on television that, "there 
are indeed nuclear weapons in Belgium" and in six other European countries.  At the 
NATO Nuclear Planning Group meeting in Brussels in June 1995, it was decided to 
preserve the "widespread basing" of NATO's dual-capable aircraft.  Finally, the June 
1995 U.S. Department of Defense paper on the "United States Security Strategy for 
Europe and NATO," provided further details, listing Belgium, Germany, Greece, Italy, 
the Netherlands, and Turkey as contributing to NATO's nuclear defense forces.
<p>
The focus of NATO nuclear planning has shifted from the former "central front" and
Eastern Europe to the Middle East and beyond.  This has resulted in a greater proportional
reduction of nuclear forces at northern Europe air bases compared with southern European air
bases.  Since 1992, U.S. nuclear bombs have been removed from one British base (RAF Upper
Heyford) and the total number of U.S. bombs in Britain and Germany has been cut in half, from
625 to about 335.  Moreover, two F-16 squadrons previously based at Ramstein Air Base in
Germany have been moved -- along with their designated nuclear bombs -- to Aviano in
northern Italy, which now serves as the main nuclear support facility for this new southern
focus.
<p>
The United States signed a memorandum of understanding with Italy on 30 November
1993, permitting the basing of two squadrons F-16s of the 401st Tactical Fighter Wing (renamed
the 31st Fighter Wing as of 1 April 1994) at the Aviano Air Base.  The first F-16s moved from
Ramstein Air Base in Germany in April 1994, and discussions are continuing to ensure the
successful conclusion of an Aviano technical agreement.
<a name="number"></a>
<p>
<font size=+1>B. The Number of Nuclear Weapons</font>
<p>
The precise number of forward deployed nuclear bombs in Europe remains classified, but
estimates indicate that it involves about 520 nuclear bombs.  Approximately two or three dozen
are British WE-177A/B bombs while the remaining 480 or so are U.S. B61 nuclear bombs.
<p>
U.S. Deputy Secretary of Defense John Deutch told the U.S. Congress in 1994 that the
NPR would maintain the "current strength" of non-strategic nuclear weapons in Europe.  The
arsenal peaked in 1967 at 7,200 warheads and declined to approximately 4,300 in 1987.  Shortly
after the U.S. announced the removal of all ground-launched nuclear weapons from Europe in
September 1991, the number of nuclear bombs was reported to be some 1,400.  A senior NATO
official predicted "significant reductions" below that level, and at the NATO Nuclear Planning
Group (NPG) meeting in Taormina, Sicily, in October 1991, the NATO defense ministers decided
to reduce the number to about 700 in the next two to three years.  By August 1992, the
reduction had brought it down to approximately 970, and by May 1993, the NATO Nuclear
Planning Group Meeting reported that "the substantial reduction of air-delivered [nuclear]
weapons has now been accomplished.
<p>
The number continued to decline, however.  A Western European Union report from May
1994 reported the number of nuclear bombs was down to about 700,  and when the <b>NPR</b> was
announced in September 1994, the U.S. stockpile in Europe was reported to be down to nine
percent of the Cold War level, corresponding to some 630 warheads compared with the 1967
peak level.  <i>The Washington Post</i> and <i>The Times of London</i> reported the <b>NPR</b> left roughly 480
nuclear bombs in Europe, while other reports ranged from approximately 300 to "several
hundred" bombs.
<p>
As of mid-1995, most nuclear bombs were estimated to be stored in Germany, a total of
approximately 275 (245 U.S. B61s and about 30 British WE-177A/Bs).  Britain stores 90 U.S.
bombs, Italy approximately 40 bombs, while Turkey stores about 75 U.S. nuclear bombs.  The
three smaller European "nuclear" countries, Belgium, Greece, and the Netherlands, each are
estimated to store 10 B61 nuclear bombs.
<p>
The combined explosive power of all the forward deployed nuclear bombs in Europe is
estimated to be about 98 megatons at its maximum yield, corresponding to over 6,533 times the
explosive power of the bomb that destroyed Hiroshima.  The combined yield is equivalent to 16
times the explosive power of all the bombs that were dropped in the Second World War.  The
largest megatonage is thought to be stored in Germany (48.9 megatons), while Britain stores 15.5
megatons.  Turkey stores 13.1 megatons, Italy seven megatons, while Belgium, Greece, and the
Netherlands each host 1.8 megatons of explosive power.
<a name="rationale"></a>
<p>
<font size=+1>C. The Rationales for Keeping Nuclear Weapons in Europe</font>
<p>
Only a few years ago the role of tactical nuclear weapons in Europe was to deter a Soviet
conventional attack on Western Europe and provide nuclear warfighting capabilities if war with
the Warsaw Pact occurred.  But with the break-up of the Soviet Union and the demise of the
Warsaw Pact this rationale has disappeared.  Throughout the early 1990s, NATO formulated new
reasons for keeping U.S. and British tactical nuclear bombs in Europe.  The rationales are more
general and vague and not tied to one specific enemy.  They include such reasons as providing
"the ultimate security," concern over proliferation of weapons of mass destruction, prevention of
wars, and "burden sharing" within NATO.  In September 1994, as part of the <b>NPR</b>, the United
States announced its plans to maintain the "current strength" of nuclear bombs in Europe at least
until 2003.
<a name="nato"></a>
<p>
<b>1. NATO Justifications</b>
<p>
The question of air-delivered nuclear bombs in the European theater was taken up at the
NATO Nuclear Planning Group (NPG) in Taormina, Italy, in October 1991.  The meeting
decided that 700 nuclear bombs would remain in Europe, and the final communique specifically
pointed to "the proliferation of nuclear weapons, which remains a matter of great concern."  The
conference communique concluded:
<p>
<blockquote>Nuclear weapons will continue for an indefinite future to cover their essential role
in the general strategy of the alliance, since conventional forces alone cannot
ensure the prevention of war.</blockquote>
<p>
At a press conference after the meeting, NATO General-Secretary General Manfred
Woerner added that, despite the changes in Eastern Europe, the danger of nuclear proliferation,
and Iraq specifically, meant that "it would not be reasonable to renounce all nuclear weapons and
to denuclearize Europe."  Woerner added:
<p>
<blockquote>Nuclear weapons will never be disinvented.  That is why I do not foresee a
situation where we will denuclearize Europe.  These weapons provide the ultimate
guarantee of our security.</blockquote>
<p>
The recommendations from the NPG meeting were endorsed by the NATO heads of state
and governments at their subsequent meeting in Rome in November 1991.  The NATO leaders
approved a new Strategic Concept which also pointed to the threat from proliferation, specifically
in the southern Mediterranean and Middle East.
<p>
The NATO leaders, however, also added another and much more general justification for
the nuclear weapons:  "to preserve peace, and prevent war or any kind of coercion."  The threat
of a large-scale military attack on European territory had disappeared, the leaders concluded. 
Instead, economic, social, and political difficulties, including ethnic rivalries and territorial
disputes, were likely to be the new risks to NATO security.  Since "conventional forces alone
cannot ensure the prevention of war," the new Strategic Concept expanded the potential role of
nuclear weapons to all sorts of conflict scenarios:  "Nuclear weapons make a unique contribution
in rendering the risk of any aggression incalculable and unacceptable.  Thus, they remain essential
to preserve peace."
<p>
The NATO state leaders therefore agreed to "maintain for the foreseeable future an
appropriate mix of nuclear and conventional forces in Europe," and keep them up to date where
necessary.  The numbers would be significantly reduced compared with Cold War levels, but the
Strategic Concept concluded that nuclear and conventional forces "are essential to Alliance
security and cannot substitute one for the other."
<p>
In late 1991, NATO also approved a 30-page document, known as MC-400, detailing
NATO strategy for conventional and nuclear forces in the post-Cold War era.  The document
concluded that the NATO alliance now faces risks from instability in a variety of areas, including
the former Soviet Union and the Middle East, and provided military guidance for implementing
the new strategy.  The alliance's nuclear arsenal was mainly a political weapon, MC-400
reiterated, but added that they could be used selectively to end a conflict, by convincing an
attacker to end a conflict by confronting him with overwhelming costs if continuing the war. 
Nuclear weapons would be used especially on an initial strike, in a way that is "constrained,
discriminate and measured," the document says.  Targets would include high-priority military
targets, especially on an enemy's home territory, using either air-delivered nuclear bombs or
missiles launched from ships and/or submarines.
<p>
Following the Rome meeting, articles written by NATO officials began to appear in a
variety of papers and magazines explaining the new direction.  In an outline of NATO's nuclear
strategy, entitled "Nuclear Forces -- The Ultimate Umbrella," British Air Chief Marshal Sir
Brendan Jackson wrote that Third World nuclear proliferation was even "more chimerical" than
the threat from Russian nuclear weapons.
<p>
The communique from the NPG meeting in Brussels in November 1994 also expressed
concern over proliferation, pointing to "the growing risks to Alliance security interests" posed by
the spread of weapons of mass destruction, ballistic missiles, and related technologies to more
countries.  The reference to proliferation as a justification for keeping nuclear weapons matches
a trend in the nuclear weapons states towards increasingly linking the role of nuclear weapons to
countering the acquisition and use of weapons of mass destruction by "proliferating" countries.
<p>
Other rationales for retaining nuclear weapons in Europe relate to maintaining Alliance
solidarity.  One relates to the principle of burden sharing within NATO.  Deploying nuclear
weapons in a number of European countries gives these nations both the declared benefits and
risks associated with having nuclear weapons on their territory.  Another suggestion is that
European NATO allies traditionally have welcomed nuclear deployment cooperation programs
because of the access it grants to U.S. nuclear planning.  Without this admittance, future nuclear
planning in the Alliance might take place on a more restricted basis.
<a name="us"></a>
<p>
<b>2. U.S. Justifications</b>
<p>
When the U.S. pulled its ground-launched tactical nuclear weapons out of Europe in
1991-1992, but left several hundred air-delivered nuclear bombs behind, Soviet President Mikhail
Gorbachev suggested that the bombs also should be removed from forward airfields.  Initially,
U.S. Defense Secretary Dick Cheney seemed interested in the proposal, and a senior defense
official told <i>The Washington Post</i> that NATO would study where the new storage sites might be
located.
<p>
But in a speech to the NATO North Atlantic Council a few days later, the U.S. chairman
of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, General Colin Powell, rejected the proposal, saying he wanted to be
"hedging against our having guessed wrong and the world's not turning out to be quite as nice a
place as we prayed."  One way of hedging was to keep nuclear bombs in Europe.  "The essential
nuclear linkage remains in the form of our dual capable aircraft,"  Powell said.
<p>
Since 1991, the United States has reaffirmed numerous times its commitment to keeping
U.S. nuclear weapons and has outlined several justifications for this:  countering the proliferation
of nuclear weapons, maintaining alliance solidarity, deterring aggression against the NATO
alliance, and promoting U.S. interests.
<p>
Concerns about nuclear weapons proliferation have become a significant U.S. rationale for
retaining nuclear bombs in Europe.  The U.S. Joint Chiefs of Staff (JCS) suggested in their annual
"Joint Military Net Assessment Report," that tactical nuclear weapons "could assume a broader
role globally in response to the proliferation of nuclear capability among Third World nations." 
And, at the NATO summit in Rome in November 1991, the United States signed on to the
Alliance's new Strategic Concept linking the presence of tactical nuclear weapons in Europe to the
proliferation of nuclear weapons.
<p>
The <b>NPR</b>, which was completed in September 1994, also examined the role of U.S.
forward deployed nuclear forces.  It concluded that nuclear bombs would continue to be stored in
Europe "as part of our commitment to the Alliance."  Deputy Secretary of Defense John Deutch
explained to Congress that the "non-strategic nuclear forces we maintain [in Europe] have both
military purposes and very important political purposes with respect to the NATO alliance."
<p>
In his briefing, Deutch provided a chart entitled the "Adjusted Nuclear Posture."  The
chart listed three or four Alliance commitments served by nuclear weapons in Europe, including
"deter attack on allies" and "maintain [non-strategic nuclear forces] capabilities."  One or two
other roles were deleted from the public record.  Deutch outlined the change that had taken
place:
<p>
<blockquote>There was a time when the military purpose of the non-strategic nuclear forces in
Europe was to assure that we could blunt a conventional Russian Soviet attack, if
it were to break through into Europe.  That was the purpose of the tactical nuclear
weapons in Europe.  That need, that military requirement, has disappeared because
the Soviets do not exist and the Russians no longer have the military capability to
mount that kind of conventional attack.
<p>
So the military purpose of the non-strategic nuclear forces is changing.  On
the other hand, the political purpose of those weapons to maintain within the
alliance shared responsibility for nuclear forces and make sure the Europeans know
that they can rely in a serious way on our nuclear forces as well as our
conventional forces is an important element in understanding what changes are
possible and that pace of changes with respect to non-strategic nuclear forces.
</blockquote>
<p>
Russian non-strategic nuclear forces were not presented by the <b>NPR</b> as a rationale for
keeping tactical nuclear weapons in Europe.  But Deutch did express "great concern" about the
disparity between Russian and U.S. non-strategic nuclear forces, and pointed out that "most of
the non-strategic nuclear weapons in Russia are located at distances which can easily be delivered
against European targets."
<p>
During the congressional hearings on the <b>NPR</b>, Deutch insisted that the political value of
tactical nuclear weapons as a commitment to NATO remains high, but he admitted considerable
uncertainty over the role of U.S. nuclear weapons in Europe:
<p>
<blockquote>I believe we have a very long diplomatic road to travel to understand better with
NATO what the role is of nuclear weapons in NATO.  Indeed, one of the most
important outcomes of the Nuclear Posture Review was this notion about how
we're going to address non-strategic nuclear weapons, of which the NATO
question is one.
<p>
But I've tried, Mr. Chairman, to say to you that we have to, over time, re-look at
this question, with respect to NATO.</blockquote>
<p>
The <b>NPR</b> emphasized the international nature of U.S. nuclear forces.  In his 1995 annual
report to the President and the Congress, Defense Secretary William Perry stated that, the United
States extends the deterrent protection of its nuclear arsenal to its allies.  "A very progressive
aspect of U.S. nuclear posture, is that it is, in part, an international nuclear posture.  The <b>NPR</b>
strongly supports continued commitment to NATO and Pacific allies....  Nowhere is this more
evident than in the area of [air-delivered tactical nuclear bombs], which are not covered by
<b>START I</b> and <b>START II</b>."  Specifically, Perry explained:
<p>
<blockquote>
... maintaining U.S. nuclear commitments with NATO, and retaining the ability to
deploy nuclear capabilities to meet various regional contingencies, continues to be
an important means for deterring aggression, protecting and promoting U.S.
interests, reassuring allies and friends, and preventing proliferation.</blockquote>
<p>
European allies helped shape the future U.S. nuclear arsenal by providing justifications to
the NPR to retain nuclear weapons in Europe.  "With input from allied countries," Deputy
Secretary of Defense John Deutch stated in 1994, "we concluded that there continues to be a
nuclear element to NATO's defense posture and that the US will sustain its commitment to both
NATO and Pacific allies."  According to Defense Secretary Perry annual report:
<p>
<blockquote>Alliance commitments and the unique characteristics of nonstrategic nuclear forces
were primary considerations in the NPR's consideration of what the [non-strategic
nuclear weapons] force structure should be.</blockquote>
<p>
In early 1995, the Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, General John Shalikashvili,
reaffirmed the role of tactical nuclear bombs in Europe, telling Congress in February, that the
bombs will be maintained in Europe, "to protect our allies."  The 1995 JCS National Military
Strategy stipulates:
<p>
<blockquote>We still need to maintain a mix of forward deployed and deployable nonstrategic
nuclear weapons, both to provide deterrent coverage over our allies, and because
extended deterrence, in many cases, is a decisive factor in our nonproliferation
effort.</blockquote>
<p>
The most recent National Security Strategy issued by President Clinton in February 1995,
acknowledges that the <b>NPR</b> "reaffirmed the current posture and deployment of non-strategic
nuclear forces," and the new U.S. Security Strategy for Europe and NATO lists seven NATO
countries (in addition to France) as contributing nuclear defense forces.
<a name="upgrade"></a>
<p>
<font size=+2><b>III. Upgrading the Nuclear Weapons Infrastructure</b></font>
<p>
Upgrades to support the deployment of nuclear bombs in Europe continue to be made. 
The JCS 1991 "Joint Net Assessment," noted that "the proliferation of nuclear weapons means
that U.S. nuclear forces will require C3 [command, control, and communication] systems with
increased capabilities."  One system being fielded is the MILSTAR/SCOTT satellite system which
reportedly will improve the command, control, and communication in relation to non-strategic
nuclear forces.
<p>
Following the U.S. decision in September 1991 to reduce but retain tactical nuclear
weapons in Europe, NATO officials told The Washington Post that a NATO program for
installing new bunkers for the remaining air-delivered bombs at air bases in Europe was
underway.
<p>
The NATO Nuclear Planning Group meeting in Brussels in November 1993 "reviewed the
process of adoption of NATO's nuclear posture to the new security environment."  This included
restructuring tactical nuclear forces and updating and adjusting consultation and planning
procedures in support of the nuclear posture required by the Strategic Concept.
<p>
General George A. Joulwan, the Commander-in-Chief of the U.S. European Command,
told Congress in March 1994, that part of changing the U.S.-NATO Infrastructure Program from
Cold War priorities to "meeting emerging readiness requirements in the theater" included funding
"Command and Control Systems for the security of residual nuclear weapons."
<p>
This nuclear modernization was reflected in the U.S. Department of Defense military
construction budget request for FY 1995 for the NATO Infrastructure Program, which included
the language, "Upgrade and maintenance of nuclear weapons safety, security, and survivability
systems (WS3)."
<p>
Nuclear modernization is slated to continue in 1996.  The NATO Infrastructure Program -- now renamed the NATO Security Investment Program -- for FY 1996 includes "upgrade and
enhancements to hardware and software systems supporting the NATO Nuclear Planning
System."
<a name="forward"></a>
<p>
<font size=+2><b>IV. Forward Deployed Nuclear Weapons and the Non-Proliferation Treaty</b></font>
<a name="issue"></a>
<p>
<font size=+1>A. Issue of Control or Transfer of Nuclear Weapons</font>
<p>
All of the non-nuclear NATO countries which host nuclear weapons on their territory
(Belgium, Germany, Greece, Italy, the Netherlands, and Turkey) have signed the <b>1970 Nuclear
Non-Proliferation Treaty (NPT)</b>.  Under <b>Article II</b> of the <b>Treaty</b> they pledge:
<p>
<blockquote>Each non-nuclear-weapon State Party to the <b>Treaty</b> undertakes not to receive the
transfer from any transferor whatsoever of nuclear weapons or other nuclear
explosive devices or of control over such weapons or explosive devices directly, or
indirectly; not to manufacture or otherwise acquire nuclear weapons or other
nuclear explosive devices; and not to seek or receive any assistance in the
manufacture of nuclear weapons or other nuclear explosive devices.</blockquote>
<p>
Likewise, as nuclear weapons states party to the <b>NPT</b>, the United States and Britain have
committed themselves under <b>Article I</b> to:
<p>
<blockquote>
Each nuclear-weapon State Party to the <b>Treaty</b> undertakes not to transfer to any
recipient whatsoever nuclear weapons or other nuclear explosive devices or
control over such weapons or explosive devices directly, or indirectly; and not in
any way to assist, encourage, or induce any non-nuclear-weapon State to
manufacture or otherwise acquire nuclear weapons or other nuclear explosive
devices, or control over such weapons or explosive devices.</blockquote>
<p>
Yet, as non-nuclear members of the NATO alliance, Belgium, Canada, Denmark,
Germany, Greece, Iceland, Italy, Luxembourg, the Netherlands, Norway, Portugal, Spain, and
Turkey take part in widespread collective nuclear defense planning, in approving deployment and
modernization of nuclear arsenals, in command, control, and communication arrangements, and --
in case of the six non-nuclear European NATO countries described in this report -- in peacetime
basing of nuclear forces.
<p>
U.S. forward deployed nuclear weapons in Europe are extensively integrated into the
military infrastructure of the countries that host these weapons.  Nuclear cooperation agreements
exist with Belgium, Germany, Greece, Italy, the Netherlands, and Turkey to allow national pilots
to deliver U.S. nuclear bombs with their own planes in times of war.  In peacetime, these "non-nuclear" 
nations train and prepare for their assigned nuclear mission.  Their aircraft are nuclear-certified to 
carry and deliver U.S. nuclear bombs by U.S. inspectors.  Finally, for those countries
that have nuclear weapons on their soil, they also exercise "negative" control in that they can veto
the use of nuclear weapons by the U.S. in NATO.
<a name="history"></a>
<p>
<font size=+1>B. History of Issue</font>
<p>
In 1965, the General Assembly passed a resolution calling for a treaty on non-proliferation
of nuclear weapons based on five main principles, including Principle (a), which stated:
<p>
<blockquote>The <b>Treaty</b> should be void of any loop-holes which might permit nuclear or non-nuclear
Powers to proliferate, directly or indirectly, nuclear weapons in any form.</blockquote>
<p>
Principle (a) was the basis for a major controversy between the U.S. and the Soviet Union
over the language of <b>Articles I</b> and <b>Articles II</b> of the <b>NPT</b>.
<p>
The Soviet Union was eager to preclude any western arrangement, such as the Multi-Lateral Force (MLF) under discussion at the time, which could have allowed non-nuclear NATO
members and  particularly West Germany to have access to U.S. nuclear weapons.  The U.S. was
equally eager to make sure the NPT did not give the Soviet Union any right to interfere with
NATO arrangements for nuclear weapons, particularly the deployment of U.S. nuclear weapons in
Europe, and the necessary consultations, planning, and training which were involved.
<p>
In September 1965, the Soviet Union offered a draft of the <b>NPT</b> which would have
precluded allied consultations and planning around nuclear weapons and so ultimately the
deployment of U.S. nuclear weapons in Europe under the existing NATO arrangements.  This
lead to protracted discussions about their differences, and the U.S. and Soviet Union achieved a
modus vivendi in 1966.  The U.S. dropped its plans for a multi-lateral NATO nuclear force, and
the Soviet Union then did not object to the deployment of U.S. nuclear weapons in Europe with
two-key control and intensive NATO consultations on nuclear matters.
<p>
The United States stated in 1968 that in its view "the treaty deals with only with what is
prohibited, not with what is permitted."  Thus according to the U.S. interpretation, consultations
and planning on defense with the NATO were not prohibited and so were permitted "so long as
no transfer of nuclear weapons or control of them results."  The United States also stated the
NPT "does not deal with arrangements for deployments of nuclear weapons within allied territory
as these do not involve any transfer of nuclear weapons or control of them unless and until a
decision were made to go to war, at which time the treaty would no longer be controlling."
<p>
However, several non-aligned states objected to the foreign deployment of nuclear
weapons under the NPT:
<ul>
<li>Mauritius considered it a weakness of the NPT that it did not prohibit storing and
transporting nuclear weapons within the territories of non-nuclear weapons states;</li>
<li>Tanzania expressed doubt that the deployment of nuclear weapons within NATO was
compatible with non-proliferation;</li>
<li>Ceylon said such deployments were against the spirit of the NPT;</li>
<li>Uganda saw such deployments as a loop-hole and held that the area of any non-nuclear
weapons State should automatically become nuclear free.</li>
</ul>
<p>          
Subsequent to the signing of the treaty the issue of foreign deployed nuclear weapons has
come up at least three times in review conferences.
<p>
In the interpretative statements in connection with the final declaration of first review
conference in 1975, Ghana, Nepal, Nigeria, Romania, and Yugoslavia submitted a draft resolution
which advocated the withdrawal from the territories of the non-nuclear weapons states all nuclear
weapons delivery systems, particularly tactical nuclear weapons.
<p>
During the second review conference in 1980, non-nuclear weapons states complained
that the deployment of nuclear weapons in non-nuclear countries and in international waters was
contrary to the nuclear non-proliferation objective of the Treaty.  Delegations also expressed the
view informally that further sophistication of tactical nuclear weapons in Europe and concomitant
doctrines for their use, might require transfer of control over such weapons to members of the
military alliance.  The Second Review Conference failed to adopt a consensus declaration, partly
attributable to the deployment of U.S. and Soviet weapons deployed in Europe.
<p>
Most recently, during the Main Committee I review of compliance with <b>Articles I, II, VI,</b>
and <b>VII</b> of the <b>NPT</b> at the April-May 1995 Review and Extension conference, the participating
countries were unable to agree on a final document partly because of dispute over deployment of
nuclear weapons in non-nuclear NATO countries.
<a name="concl"></a>
<p>
<font size=+2><b>V. Conclusion</b></font>
<p>
The continued forward deployment of hundreds of U.S. and British nuclear weapons in
Europe contravenes both the spirit and the objectives of the <b>Non-Proliferation Treaty (NPT)</b>, 
and specifically raises questions about compliance with <b>Articles I, II</b> and <b>VI</b> of the 
<b>Treaty</b>.  It also represents a barrier to furthering the creation of nuclear weapons free 
zones as addressed by the <b>NPT's Article VII</b>.  In general, deploying nuclear weapons in 
non-nuclear countries is out of step with international efforts to stem the spread of nuclear 
weapons capabilities to more countries.
<p>
A paramount objective of the international non-proliferation effort under the <b>NPT</b> is to
prevent the creation of more nuclear weapons states.  Yet, clearly, the forward deployment of
nuclear weapons in Europe blurs the distinction between nuclear and non-nuclear countries.  The
nuclear bombs of nuclear weapons states are based on the territory of "non-nuclear" European
countries, and these "non-nuclear" host countries assign and train national military personnel in
peacetime to use the nuclear weapons in times of war.  Moreover, the "non-nuclear" countries in
NATO are actively involved in nuclear war planning as part of their membership of NATO.
<p>
The United States and its allies claim that no transfer of control would take place until
wartime and at that time the <b>NPT</b> would no longer apply is rather cynical.  In war, not all laws
remain silent.  Past and current U.S. policy is endorsing the concept that non-nuclear countries
may adopt "surrogate" nuclear roles on behalf of nuclear powers.  If this policy is not a strictly
legal violation, it certainly contravenes both the objective and the spirit of the Treaty.
<p>
How U.S. nuclear weapons in Europe were treated under the <b>NPT</b> negotiations and the
resulting treaty itself was a result of the state of U.S.-Soviet relations and U.S.-NATO nuclear
weapons planning in the mid-1960s.  The United States and its allies interpreted Articles I and II
of the treaty as compatible with maintaining the deployment of U.S. nuclear weapons in Europe. 
Although some objections to the foreign deployment of nuclear weapons were made by Non-Aligned Movement members, mainly this was seen as an issue to be resolved between the two
Cold War blocs.  The Soviet Union did not object to the U.S. interpretation of the NPT in regards
to foreign deployments, and so the U.S. and its NATO allies have relied on these views ever
since.  Yet, however beneficial the Cold War understanding reached by the United States and the
Soviet Union was to reaching a satisfactory conclusion of the <b>NPT</b> negotiations, it cannot be
allowed to obscure the fact that this understanding left a loophole which muddles the <b>NPT</b>
regime.
<p>
Ironically, the non-nuclear European states which permit nuclear weapons on their soil are
also among the most prominent advocates of non-proliferation and vocal critics of countries
trying to acquire weapons of mass destruction.  For NATO to claim the "benefits" of a "nuclear
umbrella" of foreign deployed nuclear weapons in Europe, while insisting that other nations
cannot seek the same security, is hypocritical and impedes the development of universal and
non-discriminatory non-proliferation norms.
<p>
Furthermore, the forward deployment of nuclear weapons in Europe is an obstacle to
creation of nuclear weapons free zones (NFZs).  Such zones are implicitly encouraged by <b>Article
VII</b> of the <b>NPT</b>, and creating NFZs, according to the U.S. Arms Control and Disarmament
Agency, particularly in the Middle East and Africa is a foreign policy objective of the United
States.  However, the basing of so many nuclear weapons in Italy, Turkey, and Greece, in close
proximity to the Middle East and Africa could undercut attempts to create such zones.
<p>
The recent expansion of U.S. nuclear doctrine to use nuclear forces to counter chemical
and biological weapons, would undermine the achievement of the <b>African Nuclear Weapon Free
Zone Treaty</b>, at least as it appears in its current draft.  Reportedly, U.S. planners have 
identified Libya as a potential future target for nuclear forces.  Yet, <b>Article I</b> of 
<b>Protocol I</b> of the current draft of the <b>Treaty</b> reads:
<p>
<blockquote> Each Protocol Party undertakes not to use or threaten to use a nuclear explosive device
against:
<p>
(a) Any Party to the <b>Treaty</b>; or<br>
(b) Any territory within the African nuclear-weapon-free zone....</blockquote>
<p>
Also, in terms of military uses, a credible role for forward deployed nuclear weapons does
not exist.  The threat that these weapons were initially designed and deployed to counter has
vanished, and NATO has been unable to present new believable missions other than dubious
rationales such as countering proliferation, preventing wars, and providing the ultimate security
for the Alliance.
<p>
Moreover, nuclear weapons in Europe are becoming a major issue in NATO expansion,
with Russia opposing potential future deployment of NATO nuclear weapons in former Warsaw
Pact countries.  Expanding the U.S. nuclear umbrella in Europe -- only a few years after Soviet
nuclear weapons were removed from some of the same countries -- will reverse the progress
towards nuclear disarmament in Europe that has been evolving since the <b>INF Treaty</b> was signed in
1987.  In short, nuclear weapons are a burden to the new security challenges facing Europe today.
<p>
As a means toward further reducing the role of nuclear weapons, as a refutation of the
importance of nuclear weapons for national status and prestige, and as a measure of their
commitment to non-proliferation and further nuclear disarmament following the recent extension
of the <b>NPT</b>, NATO should cease the forward deployment of nuclear weapons in Europe, and non-nuclear states whose armed forces are involved in nuclear weapons missions should discontinue
such programs.  The British government's announcement on 4 April 1995 of its plans to withdraw
its nuclear free-fall bombs from service by the end of 1998 is a positive development, even if late
in coming.  With the 1997 "mini" review of the <b>NPT</b> on the horizon, it would be logical and
timely to adopt the same timeline -- if not an earlier date -- for removing the U.S. bombs.
<p>
<hr>
<a name="abb"></a>
<p>
<font size=+1>Abbreviations</font>
<p>
<table width=100% cellpaddding=10 border=0>
