<head>
<title>TNT-5 Rad Waste Tanker Crisis Report</title>
<body background="pix/nukerpt4.gif" text="#00 00 00" link="#00 80 00" 
vlink="#80 00 00" alink="#FF FF 00" basefont=3>
<table width=100% border=1>
<tr>
<td>
<img src="pix/nukerpt3.gif" width=474 height=80 ALT="GP Nuclear Campaign Report logo">
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align=right><tt><b><font size=+2>"TNT-5 Radioactive Waste Tanker and Naval Nuclear
Waste Crisis in Far East"</b></tt></font>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>
<b>Written by Joshua Handler</b><br>
<i>Research Coordinator<br>
Disarmament Campaign</i>
<p>
10 May 1994<br>
[Revised 7 July 1994]<br>
<p>
<hr>
<p>
The Russian Navy TNT-5 radioactive waste tanker is tied-up at the Zvezda shipyard in the closed
city of Bolshoi Kamen in the Russian Far East near Vladivostok.
<p>
Decommissioned in 1992, the decrepit 30-year old TNT-5 is full of 794 cubic meters of liquid
radioactive waste offloaded from Russian nuclear-powered submarines.
<p>
According to Russian Navy officers, small cracks in the hull may be allowing the waste to leak
into Bolshoi Kamen bay.  The extent of the leakage has been difficult to verify due to
contamination of the bay by previous leakages from nuclear-powered submarines.
<p>
An official commission will inspect the TNT-5 on 15 May 1994 to ascertain its condition before it
is towed to the nuclear submarine base at nearby Pavlovsk sometime during 15-20 May.<font
size=-1><b><a href="#1">1</a></b></font>
<p>
The TNT-5 is in such poor shape it may have to be supported by pontoons during the tow
otherwise it may sink on the way.  If the ship reaches Pavlovsk, further contamination may result
there.
<p>
Local civilian officials and naval officers have advocated dumping the whole ship with its cargo at
sea, but have been prevented from doing so by authorities in Moscow on the condition that
foreign assistance reaches the area to deal with the mounting naval nuclear waste problem in
the Russian Far East.
<p>
In Bolshoi Kamen alone there seven ships containing 2,253 cubic meters of liquid radioactive
waste with at least 30 curies of radioactivity.  The ship are virtually all full.  Around 180 cubic
meters of storage space is left on the large service vessel Pinega, while about 20 cubic meters
of space is left on the other vessels, mainly on the small PEK barges.
<p>
In addition, the Russian Pacific Fleet will decommission some 62 nuclear-powered submarines
by the end of the decade.  Most submarines contain two nuclear reactors, which means the
spent fuel from some 120 nuclear reactors, plus the reactors themselves, and additional solid
and liquid waste will have to be disposed of.
<p>
Russian Pacific Fleet officers claim the government is not providing financing to deal with this
mounting problem.  As a result, due to the fact there is nowhere to put the waste, implementation
of the <b>START</b> treaty may be affected since ballistic missile submarines would no longer
be able to be decommissioned and scrapped.
<p>
However, the Russian Navy has just started construction of a new nuclear-powered submarine at
Severodvinsk in the Russian North at a cost of hundreds of billions of roubles.  Also, Russian
nuclear-powered submarines continue to operate.  Resources for these projects, which will only
generate more nuclear waste,  could instead be going to resolve the current nuclear waste crisis.
<p>
<hr>
<a name="1"></a>
<p>
<font size=-1><b>1</b> <i>Due to the huge ammunition dump explosion in 
the Shokotovo region near Bolshoi Kamen and subsequent poor weather the TNT-5 was not
moved to Pavlovsk bay until 27 May. Also, as it happened, the inspection may have never
occurred.</i></font> 
<p>
<hr size=10>
