</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>U.S. Military Activity in the Arctic In the 1990s: 
Is It Needed?</title>
<body background="pix/nukerpt4.gif" text="#00 00 00" link="#00 80 00" 
vlink="#80 00 00" alink="#FF FF 00" basefont=3>
<table width=100% border=1>
<tr>
<td>
<img src="pix/nukerpt3.gif" width=474 height=80 ALT="GP Nuclear Campaign
Report logo">
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align=right><tt><b><font size=+2>"U.S. Military Activity in the<br>
Arctic in the 1990s:<br>Is It Needed?"</font></b></tt>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>
<b>Written by Joshua Handler</b><br>
<i>Research Coordinator<br>
Greenpeace Nuclear Free Seas Campaign</i><br>
Washington, D.C.
<p>
<center>Comments prepared for the panel <i>"Evolving Issues of National 
Security in the Arctic,"</i> part of <i>"The Changing Role of the United 
States  in the Circumpolar North"</i> Conference University of Alaska, 
Fairbanks 12-14 August 1992</center>
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<font size=+1><b>I. Introduction: Military Activity in the Arctic During the
Cold War</b></font>
<p>
In the lower forty-eight, during the Cold War the Arctic was often 
thought of as a strategic backwater when it came to
examining U.S. national security.  It was little understood that
the frozen North was on the geographic front-lines of the
superpower arms race.  Alaska flanked the USSR on one side.  On
the other, Norway, a key NATO ally, shared a common border with
the Soviet Union.  In the center, Canada was fully integrated to
U.S. defense planning through NATO and NORAD.  And, further to
the east, Greenland and Iceland were NATO allies, and housed
important military bases.  Finally, the Arctic literally was the
area over which a strategic nuclear war would be fought. 
Nuclear-armed intercontinental bombers and ballistic missiles
would fly over the North Pole on the way to their targets.  Thus
strategic defense plans generally involved the Arctic area.
<p>
Military facilities and forces above the Arctic Circle and
in neighboring territory were substantial, widespread and
important.  In the West, the closest U.S. nuclear-weapons to the
USSR based on U.S. territory, B57 nuclear-depth bombs, were at
Naval Air Station Adak in Alaska.  Major Air Force and Army bases
also were in Alaska.  The DEW early warning line was strung
across the northern Arctic landscape.  Canada housed 
fighter-intercept bases and training ranges.  Critical U.S. Air 
Force and Navy bases were in Greenland and Iceland.  Smaller forward
facilities were located in Northern Norway.  In the East, the
Soviet Union had a large military presence in its Far North and
Far East.  Sizable numbers of strategic nuclear weapons were at
its ballistic missile submarine bases on the Kola and Kamchatka
peninsulas.
<p>
Military activity -- primarily air and naval -- in the
region or directed at the region was considerable.  Fighter
intercepts of probing Russian bombers by Alaska based U.S.
fighters occurred regularly.  Spy planes were launched from
Shemaya Air Force base in the Aleutians.  Various U.S. plans for
strategic defense against bombers and ballistic missiles involved
intercepts over Canadian territory.  Naval and Air Force planes
based in Iceland patrolled Arctic air space and northern Atlantic
waters looking for Soviet planes, ships and submarines.  Since
the late 1950s, U.S. nuclear-powered submarines operated under
the Arctic ice-cap and along the northern coast of the Soviet
Union.  Large-scale naval exercises were conducted in the
Northern Pacific and Northern Atlantic by the U.S. and Soviet
navies.  And, U.S. nuclear-armed strategic bombers were kept on
air-born alert over the Arctic.  Soviet forces and activities in
the Arctic were broadly similar to the West's, with one
significant addition: a permanent nuclear-weapons test site
located on Novaya Zemlya.
<p>
<font size=+1><b>II. Effects of Military Activity in the Arctic Region</b>
</font>
<p>
The intense Cold War military activity in the region was not
without its problems or critics.  Some of these problems are
well-known, but some are still being uncovered today.
<p>
Of the known incidents the most notable include:  the crash
of a B-52 bomber loaded with 4 1.1 megaton H-bombs in Thule,
Greenland, on 21 January 1968, after a fire broke out on board
while the plane was on patrol over the Arctic.  The clean-up
effort, called project Crested Ice, involved shipping almost
240,000 tons of contaminated ice and snow to the United States
and took eight months.  Shortly after this incident which was the
second serious accident involving an airborne-alert nuclear-armed
bomber in two years, the U.S. Secretary of Defense, Robert
McNamara, ordered the removal of nuclear weapons from planes on
airborne alert.  The crash also raised questions about
environmental contamination and health hazards, particularly to
Danish workers involved in the clean-up.  Twenty-years later, 200
Danish workers filed suit in the United States for damages for
radiation-related health problems.
<p>
A second well-known incident was the sinking of the Soviet
Mike-class nuclear-powered submarine off Norway in April 1989. 
One nuclear-reactor and at least two nuclear-armed torpedoes were
carried to the bottom with it.  Since 1989, there have been
persistent concerns about the nuclear fuel or fissile materials
in the warheads leaking into the ocean and threatening the rich
fishing grounds near the spot of the sinking.  Plans to raise the
sub have come and gone, and now some St. Petersburg-based Russian
scientists propose to encase the sub with special materials to
keep it from corroding and leaking, or even tow the sub
underwater back to Russia for final disposal.
<p>
The above incidents were known at the time of their
occurrence.  However, a new set of concerns involving previously
secret Soviet military activities has arisen.  Within the last
year much information has come to the for about the tremendous
problems the Soviet Union had with its naval nuclear propulsion
program since its first nuclear-powered submarines went to sea in
the late 1950s.
<p>
One of the first Soviet nuclear accidents happened not in
the Soviet Union but in the Norwegian Sea.  On 4 July 1961,
shortly after finishing a patrol off the U.S. East Coast and
seemingly operating under the ice, the K-19 Hotel-class ballistic
missile submarine suffered a serious primary coolant leak some
100 miles from the Jan Mayen islands.  But for the heroism of the
crew the submarine could have sunk.
<p>
Several other Northern Fleet submarines suffered serious
reactor accidents in the 1960s.  Also, the first Soviet nuclear-powered ice-breaker had a massive reactor accident in the mid-1960s.  None of these reactors could be successfully repaired,
but until last year their fate was unknown.  In September 1991,
at a Greenpeace/Russian Information Agency Moscow conference on
the legacy of the Soviet nuclear Navy, a Murmansk nuclear
specialist, Andrei Zolotkov, revealed the reactors of the Lenin
were sunk with some of their fuel off Novaya Zemlya.  Several
months later, in February 1992, a former Soviet people's deputy
from Arkhangel'sk Alexander Emelyanenkov further revealed that 12
reactors from damaged submarines, including six that contained
their nuclear fuel, were also dumped off Novaya Zemlya. 
Furthermore, over 10,000 barrels of low-level waste were also
dumped.  All told, over 500,000 curies of radiation may have been
dumped.
<p>
Finally, recent reports from Russia suggest the Arctic may
face a nuclear threat from the Chelyabinsk and Krasnoyarsk
nuclear-weapons complexes.  Both are deep within Russia, but are
linked to the Arctic through the Ob and Yenisey rivers.  Russian
scientists fear that substantial amounts nuclear waste stored at
these sites could leak and be transported to the Arctic and
beyond.  The amounts of radiation involved are considerable. 
Russian reports estimate that the Chelyabinsk area holds almost a
billion curies of radiation alone, mostly in closed underground
waste containers, but some in open ponds next to the Techa river
which feeds into the Ob river.
<p>
In addition to these environmental-military problems,
military activity in the Arctic region lead to heightened
political tensions, and tragic consequences.  From the early
1960s, U.S. nuclear submarines operating off Russian naval ports
or actually in Soviet territorial waters were a source of
constant irritation.  Several collisions between U.S. submarines
and Soviet vessels in the 1960s and 1970s in or near Russian
waters fortunately did not lead to any known fatalities or
sinkings.  But this was a real possibility.  In one case in the
North Pacific in June 1970, U.S. submariners actually though a
Soviet submarine sank after it collided with the U.S. sub.
<p>
In the early to mid-1980s, with the heightening of the Cold,
the situation worsened, particularly in the case of naval
activities.  The U.S. Navy adopted an aggressive Maritime
Strategy which called for U.S. naval operations close to the
Soviet Union in northern waters in time of war.  U.S. attack
submarines were explicitly given the mission of hunting and
destroying Soviet ballistic missile submarines in the Arctic. 
Training in the Arctic, particularly by submarines was increased. 
Support for Arctic submarine operations was increased, with new
submarines incorporating features for underice operations, and
new facilities being constructed; e.g. Naval Air Station Adak
received upgrades to pier facilities to ease handling of 
nuclear-powered attack submarines in the mid-1980s.
<p>
Several large scale U.S. naval exercises took place in the
Northern Pacific and Atlantic.  Some of the largest maneuvers
since World War II, called FleetExs, took place in the mid-1980s
in the Pacific and involved emission-controlled transits of the
Northern Pacific by carrier battle groups ending with surprise
simulated attacks on the Kamchatka peninsula.  Afterward, these
large exercises major surface ships ventured into the Sea of
Okhotsk.  Similar exercises took place in the North Atlantic,
such as the large annual Teamwork exercises, which ended with
battleship tours of the Baltic Sea.
<p>
The Soviet Union for its part was also activity engaged in
the cat and mouse games in Northern waters.  Also there was a
noticeable increase of simulated attacks on Alaska by Soviet air
forces located in the Far East.
<p>
It is within this context of superpower tension and military
rivalry that the tragedy of KAL-007 occurred after it went off
course and strayed over Kamchatka.  The aggressive military
activity also made some defense analysts fear that a conventional
or nuclear war could start by virtue of these forward operations
in northern waters.  Of particular concern were attack submarine
operations off Soviet naval ports, which in a time of crisis,
rather than having the dampening effect the Navy planned,
actually could escalate a crisis into war.
<p>
<font size=+1><b>III. Current and Future National Security 
Interests in the Arctic Region</b></font>
<p>
Military activity in the region was closely tied to the
superpower competition.  Thus, the collapse of the Soviet threat
has removed the major reason for a U.S. military mission in the
Arctic Ocean area.  Russian submarine operations from the Kola
peninsula are minimal and non-threatening.  The Russian military
is reducing and continuing to implement its late 1980s defensive
doctrine.   The United States does not suffer from military
competition with Canada, Denmark (Greenland), Iceland, or Norway
(or other Scandinavian countries).  It enjoys good relations with
all, and will do so for the foreseeable future.  The border with
Canada is one of the oldest if not the oldest unfortified border
between two countries.  Nor do these countries suffer from any
serious competition or conflicts with one another or Russia. 
Compared to the rest of the world, none of the few resource or
boundary questions in the region threaten conflict.
<p>
So what are the military related problems in the region? 
Ironically, a problem for the region is the remaining military
activities of the former Soviet Union, particularly Russia's
nuclear-powered submarines and ships, and its nuclear weapons
programs.  Yet this is not a military problem, but an
environmental one.
<p>
Despite their astoundingly questionable safety record,
Russian nuclear-submariners reassure me that their reactors are
safe.  However, they do admit there are problems with as one
termed it the "human-technological" interface; i.e. poor
training, equipment, maintenance, design, etc., which can
contribute to accidents.  Regardless of the competence of
individual Russian submarine officers, they do not work in a
vacuum.  The human and industrial infrastructure in the country
is in bad shape.  Even in "good" times the Soviet Navy suffered
some terrible disasters on nuclear submarines.  Given the bad
times the Russian Navy now faces, there is considerable reason to
be alarmed about the possibility of a possible serious accident
involving a Russian nuclear-submarine in the next few years.
<p>
Another predicament created by Russian nuclear submarine
operations is the disposal of nuclear waste.  Reports persist
that the Russian Navy continues to discharge liquid wastes into
the Barents Sea.  Theoretically these should be aged and filtered
coolant waters from submarines involving very low-levels of
radiation.  But given questions past Soviet dumping practices, an
official international investigation of past and present
practices is needed.
<p>
The disposal of decommissioned Russian nuclear-powered
submarines also has to be investigated.  The Russian Navy now has
some 60-80 decommissioned nuclear-submarines, and has hardly
begun to process them for final burial.  There are no prepared
land-burial sites, and many submarines still with their 
nuclear-fuel in them are standing at dockside, in an unknown material
condition.  Russian naval officers hint a land-based burial site
for reactor compartments will be constructed in Novaya Zemlya or
in the permafrost, but details of plans are scant.  Again, until
a full program is made known, there should be concerns about how
these submarines will be disposed of.
<p>
One more future Russian threat to the Arctic is the possible
resumption of nuclear testing on Novaya Zemlya.  The Russian
Ministry of Atomic Energy is quite eager to resume testing after
the year-long Russian moratorium expires in October 1992.  The
head of the Ministry, Victor Mikhailov, admits some 30 percent of
Russian tests vent, raising the possibility of continued
environmental contamination of the area.  A 1991 Finnish
government report on the environmental safety of underground
nuclear testing concluded that based on current knowledge of the
geology of Novaya Zemlya that the slate bedrock of the island may
crack under the pressures generated from testing and thus make
the releases of radiation into the atmosphere possible.
<p>
<font size=+1><b>IV. Future U.S. Military Options in the Arctic 
Region</b></font>
<p>
Objectively, the Russian military should be prepared to halt
all nuclear submarine operations in the region, as well as stop
nuclear testing unilaterally.  But, this is a bit idealistic to
expect, particularly since the Russians will continue to point at
U.S. military activities as justification for their own. 
Incidents such as the U.S.-CIS submarine collision in the Barents
Sea off Russian in February 1992 continue to irk the Russians,
and underscore in their minds the need to keep their own
submarines on patrol.  (These incidents also underscore the
danger of peacetime nuclear operations.  As one Russian Admiral
told me in Moscow, the two submarines could have sunk killing
hundreds of men and taking their nuclear reactors to the bottom). 
While continued U.S. nuclear-testing in Nevada is the main reason
cited by Russian officials for the need for Russia to continue
testing.  Thus to reduce Russian military activities, the major
priority of the U.S. military in the region should be to reduce
its presence, particularly of nuclear-powered submarines.  In
addition, a ban on nuclear testing should be put into place.
<p>
These goals which seemed far-fetched even a few years ago
are now more realizable than ever.  The U.S. nuclear-submarine
program is under tremendous pressure.  Due to monetary
constraints and a lack of a clear mission, the 1980s goal of a
100 front-line nuclear-powered attack submarines has been
abandoned.  Some 85 subs are in service today, and the number
will shrink to at least 63 by the end of the decade and many
analysts feel the number may go lower than 50.  Last year the
U.S. arms control community was beginning to advocate limits on
the numbers of nuclear-powered submarines, and the Russian Navy
like the Soviet Navy before it continues to be interested in
limiting submarine operations.  Anti-submarine warfare, the main
mission of U.S. submarines in the Arctic is no longer a priority
mission for the U.S. Navy.  Moreover, the U.S. Navy, troubled by
scandals over the last several years, is having trouble clearly
articulating its mission in the post-Cold War, post-Persian Gulf
era.  These political combined factors suggest it could be
possible to stop nuclear-submarine patrols in the Arctic, and
eventually reduce or even eliminate nuclear-powered attack
submarines.
<p>
Nuclear-powered ballistic missile submarines, long the
unquestioned main-stay of the U.S. nuclear deterrent, are now
also worth considering for elimination.  Only 18 subs will be in
the force by the end of the century.  Under the current
Bush/Yeltsin plans for long-term reductions in strategic weapons,
may carry only some third of the projected 3,000 odd nuclear
weapons in the arsenals.  Due to de-MIRVing and warhead
restrictions as well as continuing reduced political tensions it
will become feasible or even necessary to start eliminating
SSBNs.  Already, there could be a reduction in SSBN patrols. 
Russia has reduced the number of SSBNs at sea, and President
Yeltsin in his response to President Bush's January 1992 State of
the Union address even suggested Russia would halt its SSBN
patrols if the United States did the same.
<p>
As for nuclear testing, there is a greater chance than ever
that U.S. nuclear testing will stop in the near future.  Both
houses of Congress have passed bills supporting a moratorium or
even eventual elimination.  The Scandinavian countries in varying
degrees have all been concerned about Russian nuclear-testing in
the past.  In a interesting recent development, local Russian and
native people populations have voiced opposition to nuclear-testing on Novaya Zemlya.  They are concerned about the possible
environmental impacts of the testing.  But also that the testing
in general legitimizes the use of the islands for nuclear
purpose, including the construction of nuclear waste sites. 
Also, they see the continuation of nuclear-testing as
strengthening the hand of the conservative military-industrial
complex in Russia, or more specifically, as some Russians are
calling it, the nuclear mafia of scientist and military men who
favor nuclear weapons.  Thus opposing nuclear testing also has a
broader internal political goal as well.
<p>
The final set of military activity I wish to consider is the
military-scientific activity in the Arctic.  Clearly, the
military has considerable scientific data about the Arctic and
scientific resources.  This data and resources should be
transferred to civilian agencies such as the Coast Guard or NOAA. 
In the 1980s, in an attempt to mitigate military competition in
areas of conflict it seemed worthwhile to try to make military
activities more benign and suggest military resources should be
used for gathering scientific data for civilian use.  With the
end of the Cold War and the possibility for more positive
international relations, we have to move beyond such thinking. 
Civilian agencies need to take the lead on these issues, and they
need to have the resources to do so.  Also, historic scientific
data about the Arctic environment needs to be released to the
public post-haste.  We can no longer afford to have our
scientific and foreign policy set by default by military
activities due to the preponderance of resources allocated to the
DOD.
<p>
This train of logic also applies to policing functions and
the more general concepts of the freedom of the seas. 
Enforcement of international agreements on drift nets, patrolling
EEZs, etc., needs to be given to the Coast Guard.  Again, it
becomes very important for keeping military tension in the region
low that the military is not given a lead role in these
activities.
<p>
<font size=+1><b>V. Conclusions</b></font>
<p>
With the end of the Cold War, the Arctic really now has
become a strategic backwater.  There are number of well-known
U.S. national concerns in the Arctic:  economic, environmental,
scientific, human, and continuing reasonable relations among the
nations bordering the region.  However, from the national
security perspective U.S. military activity in the region will do
little to further U.S. national interests, and in certain cases
is working to their detriment.
<p>
In fact, to achieve the goals of limiting environmental
degradation and increase regional stability, reductions in the
U.S. military's presence and activities are needed.  Nuclear
submarine operations and nuclear testing are the two largest
military sources of regional environmental threats, and also
contribute to lingering regional and global military tensions. 
Thus the U.S. needs to reduce and preferably eliminate submarine
operations and production, and stop nuclear testing.
<p>
Fortuitously, the current budget pressures, political
developments and a lack of military missions are making these
goals more possible than ever.  The remaining military activity
of scientific and maritime policing operations in the Arctic
needs to and could be transferred to civilian agencies such as
NOAA and the Coast Guard.
<p>
These prescriptions if followed, could have wider
implications for U.S. policy elsewhere.  They may provide the
basis for reestablishing the preeminence of civilian agencies
such as the DOS and the scientific community in setting the U.S.
foreign policy and scientific agenda rather than the DOD.  The
latter's influence on policy has suffered by default due to the
massive resources enjoyed by the DOD during the period of 
east-west competition.
<p>
The new world order may not be as new or different than the
old.  But clearly in the wake of the chill of the cold war, we
are at a crossroads in international relations.  We need to make
every effort in this period of opportunity to strengthen civilian
agencies and international cooperation, rather than find
unnecessary missions for military forces.
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<b>For the latest campaign information, please go to our 
<a href="/~usa/campaigns/nuclear/">USA Nuclear Campaign page</a>.</b>
<pre>






</pre>
