<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>What is Greenpeace?</TITLE>
<META Name="description" Content="Official website for the environmental organization, Greenpeace, in the USA.">
<META Name="keywords" Content="Greenpeace USA environment NGO clean earth water air action protest">
<link rev="made" href:"mailto: jay.townsend@wdc.greenpeace.org">
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FF FF FF" TEXT="#00 00 80" LINK="#00 80 00" VLINK="#80 00 00" 
ALINK="#FF FF 00">
<center><a href="/~usa/index.html"><img src="pix/whatis1.gif" WIDTH=504 HEIGHT=101 border=0></a></center>
<p>
<font size=+3><b>The Fight for the Forests</b></font>
<p>
<IMG ALIGN=RIGHT VSPACE=1 HSPACE=10 SRC="pix/clrcut2.gif" WIDTH=288
HEIGHT=193  ALT="photo of clearcut trees">Right now, the planet's forests are
being devastated. It's big business! Commercial operations use
logging, bulldozing and burning to clear land for agriculture,
cattle, and commercial tree plantations. These radical tactics
lead to the release of millions of tons of carbon dioxide,
causing climatic instability and contributing to global
warming.
<P>
Greenpeace is working around the world to preserve the rich
diversity of life in tropical, temperate and boreal forests.
What's at stake? Biological diversity, environmental balance,
indigenous peoples, and economic options.
<H3>Deforestation is driving millions of species to
extinction.</H3>
<P>
In the tropics, vast areas of forests are opened up in search
of mohogany and other valuable species. A network of logging
roads accelerates the rate of deforestation as farmers and
developers move into an area. In temperate and boreal forests,
entire valleys and mountainsides are stripped of trees destined
for timber and paper products.
<P>It is estimated that over half of all the plant and animal
species on the earth are found in tropical forests which cover
less than seven percent of the world's land surface. Species are
being lost which could provide new pest-resistant crops or cures
for diseases such as cancer and AIDS. And the unique ecosystems
and plant life of temperate and boreal forests are no less
threatened.
<H3>Floods, landslides, pollution...what's next?</H3>
<P>Large tropical rainfalls are filtered through thick forest
cover, regulating their impact on the local environment.
Worldwide, 200 million indigenous people live in and depend on
forests for their livelihood, food and medicine. The rights of
these people are central to the struggle. When their forests are
destroyed, floods follow, along with the loss of thousands of
tons of top soil, and life-threatening landslides. The enusing
situation of rivers and streams endangers fish populations, local
food sources, and commerical fishing operations.
<H3>Both producers - and cosumers - must share the blame for
deforestation.</H3>
<P>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=1 HSPACE=10 SRC="pix/mvgp.gif" WIDTH=216
HEIGHT=137 ALT="photo of the M/V GREENPEACE">Throughout 1994,
one of our largest ships, the <b><i>M/V GREENPEACE</b></i>, visited some of the
largest forest countries in the world - Russia, Canada, and
Brazil - challenging destructive logging and supporting the
struggle of indigenous people against deforestation.
<P>The <b><i>M/V GREENPEACE</b></i> activists protested
clearcutting of ancient forests in the Russian Far East by the
Korean giant, Hyundai. Using blockades and generating a
government inquiry helped stop several logging operations in
precious oldgrowth forests. Other recent, highly successful
actions were also carried out against unrestricted logging in
western Canada's Clayoquot Sound and in Brazil's Amazon River
region.
<p>
<b>For the latest on our campaigns to protect the forests, visit our
<a href="/~usa/campaigns/biodiversity/index.html">USA Biodiversity/Fisheries/Forests page</a>.
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<ul>
<LI><b><A HREF="nukes.html">Nuclear Disarmament and Safe
Energy</A></LI>
<LI><A HREF="toxics.html">Toxic Poisoning...Environmental
Justice</A></LI>
<LI><A HREF="can_do.html">What <I>YOU</I> Can Do</A></b></LI>
</UL>
