<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>What is Greenpeace?</TITLE>
<META Name="description" Content="Official website for the environmental organization, Greenpeace, in the USA.">
<META Name="keywords" Content="oceans Greenpeace USA environment NGO clean earth water air action protest">
<link rev="made" href:"mailto: jay.townsend@wdc.greenpeace.org">
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FF FF FF" TEXT="#00 00 80" LINK="#00 80 00" VLINK="#80 00 00" 
ALINK="#FF FF 00">
<center><a href="/~usa/index.html"><img src="pix/whatis1.gif" WIDTH=504 HEIGHT=101 alt="Where is Greenpeace" border=0></a></center>
<p>
<A NAME="nukes"></A><font size=+3><b>Nuclear Disarmament and Safe Energy</b></font>
<P><IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=1 HSPACE=10 SRC="pix/nukdemo4.gif"
WIDTH=324 HEIGHT=213 ALT="photo of anti-nuke protest">Many countries,
disappointed with slow progress towards nuclear disarmament, are
demanding deep cuts in current arsenals. Meanwhile, others are
beginning their own nuclear weapons programs. The growing trade
in nuclear materials and technologies for "peaceful nuclear
energy" threaten to provide dozens of nations with the capability
to construct a nuclear bomb.
<P>Clearly the world has arrived at a nuclear crossroads. Nucler
disarmament must become a top international priority. The trade
in nuclear materials and technologies must cease and nuclear
power must be replaced with safe, renewable energy sources and
energy efficiency.
<H3>Steps to a nuclear-free future.</H3>
<P>For over two decades, Greenpeace has campaigned against
nuclear weapons testing, development, and deployment. Our
activists have opposed nuclear weapons around the globe, using
direct actions, along with lobbying, original research and
citizen education. In 1992, Greenpeace played a major role in
obtaining an international moratorium on nuclear testing. Still,
there is much more to accomplish.  That's why all of us must
continue to work towards --
<UL>
<LI>Protecting the recently signed <b>Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty</b> which prohibits all nuclear
tests</LI>
<LI>An immediate halt to all research, testing, and development
of new nuclear weapons systems</LI>
<LI>Deep cuts in existing nuclear arsenals and a strong
commitment to nuclear disarmament</LI>
<LI>An international ban on production, stockpiling, and use of
nuclear weapons-usable plutonium and uranium for any purpose</LI>
</UL>
<H3>When you flip on the porch light...</H3>
<P><IMG ALIGN=RIGHT VSPACE=1 HSPACE=10 SRC="pix/windmill.gif" WIDTH=144
HEIGHT=239 ALT="photo of the power-generating windmills">
<P>When most people flip on the porch light, environmental
destruction is far from their minds. However, many of the
planet's most serious environmental crises can be linked directly
to the production of electricity - electricity that powers
everything from porch lights to industrial machinery.
<P>According to the Department of Energy, about 70% of the
electricity in the U.S. is generated by plants burning "fossil
fuels" - oil, coal, and natural gas. Nuclear reactors produce 20%
of the nation's electricity, with most of the remainder coming
from hydroelectric dams. Yet, clean, cheap, reusable energy
sources are ready to replace these obsolete forms of energy
production.
<H3>The use of fossil fuels inflicts long-term damage.</H3>
<P>The environmental damage caused by fossil fuels begins when
these fuels are mined from deep under the Earth's surface and
continues as they are refined, transported, and ultimately burned
into gases that pollute our atmosphere.  Fossil-fired power
plants are also a major cause of acid rain, as well as smog which
is harmful to both humas and plantlife. A gases, such as carbon
dioxide, trap heat in our atmosphere resulting in global warming.
Among scientists, the only debate is how severe the impact will
be.
<H3>Nuclear energy - catastrophic accidents are all too
possible.</H3>
<P>The core meltdown at the Chernobyl nuclear complex and
Pennsylvania's Three Mile Island plant radiation releases are
unmistakable examples of what can go wrong - and does. Moreover,
lethal radioactive debris is piling up at over 100 reactor sites
around the U.S. That's why Greenpeace is calling for an immediate
moratorium on construction of new power plants and the shutdown
of all existing nuclear reactors.
<H3>It's time for renewable energy and conservation.</H3>
<P>The costs of renewable resources compare favorably with
conventional power plants. Across the U.S., alternative energy
sources - wind and solar power - have already proven themselves
to be clean, effective and reliable. And implementation of high-
efficiency lighting heating, cooling, and motor technologies
would cut national electricity consumption dramatically.
<P>The decision to build a wind or gas-fired power plant, or to
implement energy efficiency programs, must be moved out of
obscure corners of bureaucracies that respond to vested interests
and into the political arena where political leaders can respond
to all of us.<p>
<b>For the latest energy and nuclear campaign information, visit the <a href="/~usa/campaigns/nuclear/">USA Nuclear Campaign 
page</a>.</b>
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<ul>
<LI><b><A HREF="toxics.html">Toxic Poisoning...Environmental
Justice</A></LI>
<LI><A HREF="can_do.html">What <I>YOU</I> Can Do</A></b></LI>
</UL>
<pre>
</pre>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="pix/rnbwbar.gif">
