<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>What is Greenpeace?</TITLE>
<META Name="description" Content="Official website for the environmental organization, Greenpeace, in the USA.">
<META Name="keywords" Content="oceans Greenpeace USA environment NGO clean earth water air action protest">
<link rev="made" href:"mailto: jay.townsend@wdc.greenpeace.org">
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FF FF FF" TEXT="#00 00 80" LINK="#00 80 00" VLINK="#80 00 00" 
ALINK="#FF FF 00">
<center><a href="/~usa/index.html"><img src="pix/whatis1.gif" WIDTH=504 HEIGHT=101 alt="Where is Greenpeace" border=0></a></center>
<p>
<font size=+3><b>Toxic Poisoning...Environmental
Justice</b></font>
<P><IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=1 HSPACE=10 SRC="pix/ejustic2.gif" WIDTH=197
HEIGHT=207 ALT="photo of protest">One of the major myths of the
industrial era is that there are "safe" and "acceptable" levels of
toxic pollution.  For many toxic substances, this simply is not
true. Produced by the chemical industry for a wide variety of
uses, these toxic chemicals are encountered in the workplace, in
products, and by living near factories and disposal
facilities.
<P>Often those who bear the burden of toxic poisoning -
communities of color, poor and rural communities, and children -
are the least able to influence decisions about toxics use and
pollution. The injustice does not end here at home either.
Increasingly, toxic waste and polluting technologies themselves
are exported to less developed countries when they become
unacceptable in the United States.
<P>Greenpeace has long been committed to ending the production
and use of persistent bio-accumulative toxins as well as toxic
waste disposal methods, and to working for environmental justice
in the U.S. and globally. We must eliminate the continued
poisoning of this planet with these long-lived and dangerous
chemicals. It is possible - we know the alternatives and we know
the benefits.
<H3>The chlorine crisis.</H3>
<P>All over the world, chlorine-containing industrial compounds
are wreaking havoc with the environment and our health. And
Greenpeace is leading the fight to end chlorine poisoning.
<P>Chlorine chemistry is a 20th century and largely post World
War II phenomenom. Today, chlorine is the common link in many of
the world's most notorious environmental poisons:
<UL>
<LI>dioxin</LI>
<LI>DDT</LI>
<LI>Agent Orange</LI>
<LI>PCBs</LI>
<LI>and ozone-destroying chloroflurocarbons (CFCs)</LI>
</UL>
<P>How specifically to these substances affect us? Scientific
studies implicate these chemicals in severe and widespread health
problems both in people and wildlife, including infertility,
impaired childhood development, birth defects, immune system
damage and cancer.
<P>At present, most chlorine is used in the chemical industry to
bleach paper or to combine with petrochemicals to produce PVC
plastics (vinyls), pesticides and solvents, including those used
in dry cleaning. The fact is, there are readily available and
affordable alternatives for all major chlorine uses.
<H3>Fighting to ban the burn</H3>
<P>For a decade, Greenpeace has been fighting the spread of
incinerators that burn household garbage, industrial toxic waste
and medical waste. This includes cement kilns burning toxic waste
as fuel, a process erroneously touted as recycling. The
facilities are unsafem unnecessary and unwanted by the
communities targetted to host them. Contrary to what the waste
industry and many government regulators say, incinerators emit a
host of toxic heavy metals such as mercury and other toxic
poisons.
<P>According to the EPA, we do not need new toxic waste
incinerators; we already have double the capacity that current
demand requires. Policy efforts should be directed towards
reducing waste at the source and phasing out existing burners.
Garbage incinerators not only emit dangerous pollutants, but
bring economic burdens and compete with reduction and recycling
programs. Medical waste, because of its high PVC content, is an
enormous source of dioxin; a combination of reduction of one-use
plastic items and alternative sterilization methods can eliminate
the demand for medical waste burners.
<P>Greenpeace believes individuals and communities should support
efforts to redirect waste policies toward reducing the use of
toxic materials, limiting the generation of unnecessary waste,
and eliminating polluting disposal methods.
<p>
<hr>
<p>
