<HEAD>
<TITLE>Greenpeace: Stop PVC!</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="pix/pvc.gif" TEXT="#00 00 80" LINK="#00 80 00"
VLINK="#80 00 00" ALINK="#FF FF 00" basefont=3>
<center><a href="/~usa/index.html"><img src="pix/get_inv.gif" WIDTH=504 HEIGHT=101 border=0></a></center>
<p>
<table width=560 cellspading=0 cellpadding=0 border=0>
<tr><td>
<center>
<img src="pix/out_up.gif" vspace=5 width=560 height=23 ALT="Outreach Update">
</center>
<font size=+3>Government Discovers PVC Miniblinds Pose Lead Hazard</font>
<p>
On June 25, the U.S. Consumer Product Safety Commission (CPSC) concurred with the states of North Carolina and Arizona that  miniblinds made from Polyvinyl Chloride (PVC or "vinyl") present a lead poisoning hazard for young children.  Shortly there after, Greenpeace issued letters to all 48 remaining state health departments, as well as over 200 retailers and distributors requesting public warning and the immediate removal of the leaded PVC mini-blinds from the store shelves.
<p>
Twenty-five million non-glossy, vinyl miniblinds that have lead added to stabilize the plastic in the blinds are imported each year from China, Taiwan, Mexico, and Indonesia.  The CPSC found that over time sunlight degrades the PVC and they can leach lead in the form of dust.
<p>
Lead poisoning in children is associated with behavioral problems, learning disabilities, diminished intelligence, growth retardation and kidney disorders.  Lead exposure is particularly dangerous for children under the age  of six because they are still growing and developing.  Concerns over lead poisoning have caused society to ban the use of lead in gasoline and paint.  Now the CPSC has recommended that parents with young children remove vinyl miniblinds from their homes. 
<p>
PVC is an extremely toxic product and the presence of lead is only one of the problems.  PVC products also carry significant quantities of other toxic chemicals added as stabilizers and plasticizers. Lead is one such compound of concern.
<p>
At the time of this writing Greenpeace has learned that only 25 states have taken any action on this matter. Not a single health department has required retailers to remove the leaded PVC miniblinds from their store shelves.  Only four retailers Home Depot, Lowe's, Home Base and Kmart have responded to our letter and removed the miniblinds from their shelves. 
<p>
On July 16, the California Department of Justice sued makers and sellers of lead tainted vinyl miniblinds, alleging the companies failed to warn consumers about the presence of lead in the product that poses a health hazard. The defendants include Wal-Mart, Kmart, Home Base, J.C. Penny, Jencraft and Target.
<p>
Greenpeace advises consumers not to buy PVC products, which can contain toxic additives and release toxic compounds like dioxin when burned in fires or garbage incinerators.
<p>
<img src="pix/can_do.gif" vspace=5 width=560 height=23 ALT="What you can do:">
<table cellpadding=0 border=0>
<tr>
<td><ol>
<li> Take any PVC miniblinds back to the retail store where you bought them and demand a refund.  Do not purchase any brand of PVC blinds to replace them.  Cloth blinds are available at most major retailers.</li>
<li> Call or write to your state health authority and major retail outlets to find out what they are doing to warn people.</li>
<li> Make sure your schools, daycare centers, churches and other community institutions know about the dangers of PVC miniblinds and take similar measures to replace them.</li>
<li> Write a letter to the editor of your local paper and call your local radio talk show to discuss the issue.</li>
<li> Avoid PVC products in your everyday shopping.  Avoid purchasing plastic products with the number "3" in the recycling triangle, as well as other vinyl products.  Most PVC products aren't usually clearly labeled -- you may have to ask the manufacturer or retailer to be sure you are not buying a PVC product. PVC is used to make shower curtains, boots, credit cards, some packaging, construction materials and dozens of other kinds of products.</li>
<li> Call us at <b>(800) 326-0959</b> if you want more information on the dangers of PVC and please let us know what you've done.</li>
</td><td valign=top>
<table cellpadding=10 border=0><tr><td>
<center><i><font size=+2>Brand Names of Some Miniblinds Found to Contain Lead Include:</font></center>
<p>
<ul>
<li>Prisma Jencraft</li>
<li>Color Classics</li>
<li>Lotus & Windoware</li>
<li>(Generic) Kmart MB</li>
<li>Kirsch-Cooper</li>
<li>Jencraft</li>
<li>Spectrim/Newell</li>
<li>Basic Trends</li>
<li>Ultima MB-Window Concepts</li>
<li>Sunsations 1" Light Filtering</li>
</ul></i><p><center>
<img src="pix/pvc2.gif" width=143 height=143 ALT="PVC symbol"></center><hr>
</td></tr>
</table>
</td></tr>
</table>
<p>
<font size=+3> <b>PVC:</b> Toxic Plastic at the Heart of the Chlorine Industry</font>
<p>
<font size=+1>For several years Greenpeace has been campaigning against PVC because PVC is the single most environmentally damaging of all plastics.</font>
<p>
Polyvinyl Chloride (PVC) plastic, commonly known as "vinyl" is the second most common but single most environmentally damaging of all plastics.  PVC is also the largest and fastest growing use of chlorine, a chemical which is at the root of many toxic disasters -- from the hole in the ozone layer to the global spread of numerous infamous chemicals, including DDT, PCBs and dioxin.  As the biggest industrial use of chlorine, PVC accounts for more dioxin than any other family of products.
<p>
PVC resin is compounded with hundreds of different kinds of additives to give it the properties desired in the final product. Flexible products typically incorporate a plasticizer in the compounded formulation.  Shower curtains, furniture and auto seat coverings, flooring, cable and wire covering, film packaging and hoses are a few common flexible PVC products.   Rigid PVC products such as piping, siding and window frames require the use of other additives, such as stabilizers, colorants and fillers, many of which, like lead, can be toxic.
<p>
Consumers should avoid PVC altogether since manufacturers are not required to label the contents of their products, which can contain one or more toxic additives.  It is also important to remember that because PVC is made from chlorine it cannot be made or burned without creating and releasing highly toxic compounds such as dioxin.
<p>
<font size=+1>Safer substitutes exist for virtually all PVC applications.</font>
<p>
The move by the CPSC, the first US warning on PVC, follows a number of measures taken by other countries to protect the public from the dangers of PVC.  The controversy over PVC has caused the Swedish government to phase out certain types of PVC products containing harmful additives.  The Danish Parliament is considering a proposal -- backed by the country's EPA -- to phase out PVC by the year 2000, largely because of the toxic effects of certain plasticizers.  In Germany and Austria numerous community and regional governments have banned or restricted the use of PVC in public building construction because of the dangers caused by PVC during accidental building fires.  The centerpiece of the year 2000 Olympics, the Sydney Olympic Stadium, is being designed to minimize the use of PVC plastic.
</td></tr>
</table>
<pre>

</pre>
</body>
