<html>
<head>
<title>Greenpeace USA Biodiversity Campaign</title>
<META Name="description" Content="Greenpeace USA Biodiversity Campaign information updates.">
<META Name="keywords" Content="oceans fish forests Greenpeace USA environment NGO clean earth water air action protest">
<link rev="made" href:"mailto: jay.townsend@wdc.greenpeace.org">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FF FF FF" text="#00 00 80" link="#00 80 00" 
vlink="#80 00 00" alink="#FF FF 00" basefont=3>
<center><a href="/~usa/index.html"><img src="pix/bio_upd.gif" WIDTH=504 HEIGHT=101 border=0></a>
<h3>Current Biodiversity/Fisheries/Forests Campaign Information</h3>
<p>
<font size=+3>One fish, two fish -- there's too few fish!</font>
<table width="100%" border=0>
<tr>
<td>
<img src="pix/trawler4.gif" vspace=0 hspace=15 width=285 height=174 
ALT="Photo of factory fishing trawler"></td>
<td>
<font size=+2><b>Factory Trawler</b> <i>n.</i> </font>An industrial scale fishing vessel,
150-300 feet in length, which catches fish by towing a large funnel-shaped net.  In around the
clock operation, factory trawlers catch and process fish in an on-board factory. This allows the
factory trawlers to stay at sea indefinitely, constantly fishing and wasting.</td>
</tr>
</table></center>
<p><a href="http://www.interactivism.com"><img align=right src="pix/inter2.gif" width=126 height=50 hspace=10 border=0></a>
<font size=-1>Greenpeace is calling for a ban on factory fishing trawlers by the year 2001. 
Concerned citizens can send a <b>free fax</b> in support of the ban to
the CEO's of Tyson Foods and American Seafoods (the largest owners
of these trawlers) by going to <b><a href="http://www.interactivism.com">www.interactivism.com</a></b><p></font>
<p><center>
<a name="diary"></a>
<hr>
<img align=middle src="pix/smtitle1.gif" width=400 height=39 ALT="Bering Sea Diary"><br>
Daily reports and photos from the ship, <i>M/V Greenpeace</i>, during our recent anti-factory trawler campaign.<p>
<table cellpadding=4 border=1>
<tr><td><b> August </b></td><td width=16><a href="ber826.html">26</a></td><td width=16><a href="ber827.html">27</a></td><td width=16>28</td><td><a href="ber829.html">29</a></td><td width=16><a href="ber830.html">30</a></td><td width=16><a href="ber831.html">31</a></td><td colspace=4></td></tr> 
<tr><td><b> September </b></td><td width=16 align=right><a href="ber91.html"> 1</a></td><td width=16 align=right><a href="ber92.html"> 2</a></td><td width=16 align=right><a href="ber93.html"> 3</a></td><td width=16 align=right><a href="ber94.html"> 4</a></td><td width=16 align=right><a href="ber95.html"> 5</a></td><td width=16 align=right><a href="ber96.html"> 6</a></td><td width=16 align=right><a href="ber97.html"> 7</a></td><td width=16 align=right><a href="ber98.html"> 8</a></td><td width=16 align=right><a href="ber99.html"> 9</a></td><td align=right><a href="ber910.html">10</a></td><td align=right><a href="ber911.html">11</a> <font size=-1>(final entry)</font></td></tr>
</table>
<p>
</font>
For more information about our campaign against factory fishing trawlers, please read our new report, </b><a href="/~usa/reports/biodiversity/sinking_fast/index.html"><img src="/~usa/reports/biodiversity/sinking_fast/pix/sinkhed5.gif" width=565 height=100 ALT="Sinking Fast"></a><br>
<p>
<h3>...here's just a few frightening factory trawler facts...</h3></center>
<ul>
<li>There are approximately 55 Seattle-based factory trawlers operating in the North Pacific. 
Just these 55 vessels were responsible for taking 60% of the 4.4 billion pounds of fish taken in the
North Pacific.</li>
<li>Some of the factory trawlers use nets with an opening as large as 2 miles in circumference. 
You could fit 228 houses on half acre lots in the opening of just one of these nets.</li>
<li>Our fisheries are drying up. Currently, 82% of managed fish stocks in the U.S. are fully or
over-exploited. In 1994, Alaskan groundfish factory trawlers threw overboard, dead or dying, over 572 MILLION
pounds of fish because they were the wrong sex, size or species.</li>
</ul><center>
<b><a href="fishfact.html">...more frightening factory fishing facts....</a></b><br>
<b><a href="itq.html">Why is this happening?</a></b></center>
<p>
<hr width=25%>
<p>
<ul>
<li><font size=+1><a href="tuna.html">What about dolphins caught in tuna fishing nets?</a></font></li> 
<li>Text of <b><a href="panama.html">Panama Declaration</a></b></li>
<li><a href="tunatest.html">Testimony of Clifton Curtis</a> on behalf of Greenpeace 
before the Subcommittee on Fisheries, Wildlife and Oceans of the U.S. House of Representatives
Committee On Resources On Tuna/Dolphin-Related Issues as Addressed in
<b>H.R. 2823</b> and <b>H.R. 2856</b></li>
</ul>
<p>
<hr size=10><center>
<a href="guidprin.html"><img src="pix/cqbanr.gif" width=501 height=54 ALT="Stop
Rainforest Logging!" border=0></a></center>
<ul><font size=+1>
<li><a href="macblo.html">Campaign to protect Clayoquot Sound</a> from destructive
logging by MacMillan Bloedel</li>
<li><a href="guidprin.html">Guidelines and Principles</a> for ecologically responsible forest
use</li>
<p>
<li>Help save the <b>Headwaters Forest</b>, the last unprotected ancient redwood forest in the world, by checking out the <a href="http://www.igc.apc.org/headwaters/">Headwaters page</a>.</li>
</font>
</ul>
<hr size=10>
<p>
<b>Take action to protect the most significant wetland in the Caribbean!</b> The Nariva Wetlands, 
located on the east coast of the Caribbean island of Trinidad, is under growing development 
pressure and needs your help to survive.  Join with 
<a href="http://web.trinidad.net/nariva/">Trinidad's Pointe-A-Pierre Wild Fowl 
Trust</a> in a campaign to save this unique area. Nariva has been declared a wetland of 
international significance and is home to 57 different species of mammals and 171 bird species.
<p>
<b>You may also want to check out</b> a site created by the Korean Federation for Environmental Movement to
call attention to Korea's <a href="http://kpd.cybercom.co.kr/dokyu/dukeng.html">endangered forests</a>.
<hr>
<pre>
</pre>
<center><h4>Also see our <a href="/~usa/pubinfo/publist.html">Public Information pages</a> 
for available <a href="/~usa/pubinfo/biodiversity.html">Biodiversity/Fisheries Campaign
Reports</a>.</h4></center>
<p>
<center><img src="pix/rnbwbar.gif"></img>
<h2>...Because our kids deserve a future</h2><p></p>
<img src="pix/rnbwbar.gif"></img></center>
