<DOCNO>WT04-B26-93</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA083-000586-B036-82</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://greenpeace.org:80/~usa/reports/nuclear/stop_plutonium/part2.html 193.67.176.1 19970103203218 text/html 10984
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Fri, 03 Jan 1997 20:34:56 GMT
Server: Apache/1.0.0
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 10812
Last-modified: Sat, 14 Dec 1996 22:40:39 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>"Greenpeace Bulletin - Stop Plutonium"</title>
<META Name="description" Content="Greenpeace bulletin documenting the lethal radioactive threat from tranportation of plutonium waste around the world.">
<META Name="keywords" Content="plutonium nuclear transport shipments radioactivity secret IAEA Akatsuki Maru Pacific Sandpiper Greenpeace USA environment">
<body background="pix/amchbck.gif" text="#00 00 00" link="#00 80 00"
vlink="#80 00 00" alink="#FF FF 00" basefont=3>
<table width=575 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td colspan=2>
<img src="pix/nuke-hr2.gif" width=553 height=6><center>
<img src="pix/stopluto.gif" width=504 height=100 ALT="Stop Plutonium"></center>
<img src="pix/nuke-hr2.gif" width=553 height=6></td></tr>
<tr>
<td valign=top>
<img src="pix/plutorad.gif" width=121 height=121 ALT="radiation symbol"><br>
<img src="pix/plutoqt4.gif" width=121 height=338 ALT="The terms of the contract between Britain, France, and Japan have been kept secret from politicians and the public.">
</td>
<td valign=top>
<img align=left src="pix/plutoqt5.gif" width=108 height=127 ALT="How Will the Plutonium Waste Be Transported?">
The plutonium waste scheduled to be returned has been concentrated and glassified. The molten radioactive glass is poured into stainless steel canisters which are then welded shut. Current estimates suggest that some 1,190 British and 2,030 French waste canisters will be shipped to Japan. These figures are based on the industrys desire to reduce costs by putting as much waste as possible into each canister.  However, as serious technical and safety problems could require that less waste go into each block, a greater number of blocks may need to be produced and transported.  This could have the effect of greatly increasing the number of waste canisters to be transported over the course of the next 15 years.      
<p>
<img align=right src="pix/plutop2.gif" width=200 height=332 ALT="rad transport container ship loading cargo in Cherbourg, France, 1992">
The canisters of plutonium waste will be loaded into heavy-weight transport containers known as casks. The cask, designed by Transnucleaire and constructed in Japan, is called the TN 28 VT. These casks are designed to carry 28 canisters of waste -- four tiers of 7 canisters each.
<p>
The casks of plutonium waste will be transported onboard one of the five ships operated by the British company Pacific Nuclear Transport Limited (PNTL). While it is likely that either the PNTL ship <i>Pacific Pintail</i> or the <i>Pacific Teal</i> will make the December/January waste transport, Japanese authorities have been unwilling to confirm which vessel will be used. The other dedicated nuclear freighters which could transport the waste are PNTL's <I>Pacific Crane</I> or <I>Pacific Swan</I>.
<a name="secret"></a>
<p>
<img align=left src="pix/plutoqt6.gif" width=115 height=24 ALT="A Secret Route">
Secrecy also shrouds the route that the plutonium waste shipments will follow.  As is shown on the <a href="pluto_map.html"><b>map</b></a>, four basic routes are possible:
<ul>
<li> through the Caribbean Sea and Panama Canal, then passing near  Hawaii while crossing the Pacific;</li>
<li> around South America (Cape Horn) and across the Pacific;</li>
<li> around Southern Africa (Cape of Good Hope), across the Indian Ocean and either through the Straits of Malacca and the South China Sea or around Australia and North through the islands of the South Pacific;</li> 
<li> through the Mediterranean and Suez Canal.</li>
</ul>
While covert transports of irradiated nuclear fuel have occurred along all of these routes, it should be noted that the transports of Japanese irradiated nuclear fuel bound for France and Britain are most commonly transported through the Panama Canal and Caribbean Sea (despite the regional opposition of the Caribbean Community [CARICOM] Heads of State).  It should also be noted that the Japanese plutonium transport of 1992/93 onboard the <I>Akatsuki Maru</I> followed the route around the Cape of Good Hope, across the Indian/Southern Ocean, and North between Australia, New Zealand and South Pacific island states before arriving in Japan. And the first-time shipment of high level waste from France to Japan in 1995 sailed along the eastern coast of Latin America, around Cape Horn, and across the Pacific. 
<p>
While formal requests for information and prior notification have been made of Japan (the importer), France (the exporter and country apparently responsible for the transport plan itself) and Britain (which has primary control of the PNTL transport company actually making the shipment) they have proved unwilling to disclose the nature of their safety plans, route preparations, etc. It is clear that Japan, France and Britain remain dedicated to secrecy despite the justified concerns of nations along the transport routes.
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td valign=top>
<img src="pix/plutorad.gif" width=121 height=121 ALT="radiation symbol"><br>
<img src="pix/plutoqt7.gif" width=121 height=235 ALT="Safety considerations have been seriously jeopardized by cost-cutting and secrecy.">
</td>
<td valign=top>
<img align=left src="pix/plutoqt8.gif" width=113 height=127 ALT="The Plutonium Waste Shipments Are Unsafe">
Although the environment and public health are threatened by these transports, safety considerations have been seriously jeopardized by cost-cutting and secrecy. Inadequate design, testing and construction of the transport containers, weak materials, insufficient emergency planning, and the lack of liability coverage suggest that the industry and governments involved are simply unwilling to pay the cost of making anything but their profits safe. Further, they try to cover up these inadequacies by attempting to make their transports in secret without the knowledge and/or agreement of the nations and peoples put at risk.
<p>
The deadly radioactivity of the plutonium waste is supposed to be contained by three overlapping safety features: namely, the nature of the waste glass itself, the stainless steel cylinders containing the glass blocks, and the transport casks.  While these safety systems should provide protection under normal circumstances, it is quite clear that economic considerations have compromised quality control and have cut safety margins to the point where serious accidents could overwhelm safety systems and lead to the calamitous discharge of radioactivity into the environment.
<p>
For example, by adding too much radioactivity to the waste glass itself and, in turn, by putting too much glass into each canister, the integrity of the glass and the steel canisters could be compomised during the kinds of fires, collisions and sinkings that occur at sea. This could lead to the release of radioactive gas and/or glass particles during a serious accident.
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td valign=top>
<img src="pix/plutorad.gif" width=121 height=121 ALT="radiation symbol"><br>
<img src="pix/plutoqt9.gif" width=121 height=400 ALT="A serious accident at sea could overwhelm safety systems and lead to the calamitous discharge of radioactivity to the environment.">
</td>
<td valign=top>
The international nuclear industry maintains that the shipping casks themselves will withstand serious accidents and protect the public and the environment. But these claims do not hold up under the light of scientific scrutiny. The internationally applied standards recommended by the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) for the design and testing of transport containers are not adequate in view of the likely effects of serious fires, collisions and sinkings at sea.
<p>
For example, the IAEA recommends designing and testing casks to withstand an 800&#186;C fire burning for up to 30 minutes. But fires at sea burn for an average of 20-23 hours at temperatures in excess of 1,100&#186;C. Similar inadequacies exist in the impact and immersion tests for these containers.  These glaring shortcomings have led independent experts to suggest that "(m)arine accidents involve significant forces and outcomes that appear to exceed the limits of the standards to which the casks are designed ... there is no substantive evidence to support any claims relative to the integrity of a cask exposed to the consequences of a maximum credible marine accident."     
<p>
The IAEA itself has categorically stated that containers can be built which would entail zero risk to the public, so there can be no justification for the use of inadequate containers: "It would be relatively simple to specify a performance test for a package that would guarantee that no package would ever fail in an accident situation. Such a performance test would reduce public risk from transport of radioactive material or radiation exposure to zero but would exact a tremendous economic toll from world economies."
<p>
For the IAEA, which is charged with encouraging the growth of the nuclear industry, profits are clearly more important than safety. Protecting the nuclear industry simply takes precedence over protecting the true economic and environmental concerns of the global citizenry.
<p>
Rather than address the problems, the governments involved are trying to act in secrecy.  Despite past assurances, nations along the transport route have not been notified about the proposed route or even about fueling or emergency stops the transports might make. Accordingly, they are not informed about the risk, involved in emergency planning or provided the opportunity to place their waters off limits to such cargoes.
<p>
In turn, although official estimates suggest that a nuclear transport accident could cost billions of dollars in damages, there is no liability plan covering these shipments. In addition, the countries involved in these transboundary waste shipments are distributing responsibility for the transports among different governmental and private companies, thereby making it difficult to identify a specific company or government that would be liable for damages stemming from an accident.
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td valign=top>
<img src="pix/amspace.gif" width=121 height=10 ALT="(blank space)">						
</td>
<td valign=top>
<font size=+1><b><a href="part3.html">Ahead to Part 3</a> : An Accident Could Be Catastrophic</b></font>
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<b>
Please see our <a href="/~usa/pubinfo/publist.html">Public Information page</a> for 
other Greenpeace Reports.<p>
<a href="/~usa/index.html">Return to Greenpeace USA Homepage</a></b>
<p>
<font size=-1>
<b>This report &#169; Greenpeace 1996 [on-line version released December 1996; printed version released January 1997].</b>
<p>
On-line bulletin design by Jay Townsend for Greenpeace (based on print version designed by Rob King for Greenpeace).
</td></tr></table>
<pre>

</pre>
</body>
</html>
