<HTML>

<!-- Greenpeace Mediterranean Home Page -->
<!-- (c) 1996 Greenpeace Mediterranean & InArt Systems -->
<!-- Greenpeace Mediterranean Other Countries-->
<!-- others.html -->
<!-- 27/6/96 - 17/9/96 -->

<!-- Created by InArt Systems Ltd. -->
<!-- "Djamanti," Tumas Galea Str., -->
<!-- B'Kara BKR13, MALTA (Europe). -->
<!-- Tel/Fax: +356 486-591         -->
<!-- Pager: 0710194/6408 (Vassallo P.J.) -->
<!-- Designed by Kenneth Scicluna  -->
                                
<HEAD>

<TITLE>Greenpeace Mediterranean: Other Countries</TITLE>

<BODY BACKGROUND="pics/tile.gif" BGCOLOR=white Text=black link=blue VLINK=purple ALINK=white>

</HEAD>

<!--<FONT SIZE=7><TT><B>Other Countries</B></TT><FONT SIZE=3><BR>-->
<IMG SRC="pics/others.jpg" ALT="[Other Countries]" ALIGN="absmiddle"><P>

<IMG SRC="pics/spacer.gif" ALIGN="absmiddle">
   <A HREF="#Albania">Albania</A>
 | <A HREF="#Algeria">Algeria</A>
 | <A HREF="#Egypt">Egypt</A>
 | <A HREF="#Jordan">Jordan</A>
 | <A HREF="#Libya">Libya</A>
 | <A HREF="#Morocco">Morocco</A>
 | <A HREF="#Syria">Syria</A>

<P>
<HR>
<P>

<A NAME="Albania">
<FONT SIZE=5><TT><B>Albania</B></TT><FONT SIZE=3><P>
</A>
- Waste Trade Scandal.  Return to Sender of expired Pesticides donated by Germany to Albania following an intense Greenpeace campaign.  Greenpeace ship  visited for the occasion with humanitarian assistance which would truly be beneficial to Albania.  Waste successfully returned to Germany.
<P>

<HR>

<P>
<A NAME="Algeria">
<FONT SIZE=5><TT><B>Algeria</B></TT><FONT SIZE=3><P>
</A>
- Greenpeace visited Algeria three times and co-operated with local NGOs and Government until  the political strife there forced a suspension of work.<P>

- 1989 : 1st visit of a Greenpeace Ship (the MV Sirius) to Algeria, as part of the Magreb Tour (including Tunisia and Morocco).  Very successful  introductory visit with huge public participation.<BR>
- 1990 : 2nd visit tackled the pollution in Western Algeria, with Greenpeace scientists co-operating with Algerian scientists in taking sampling in Oran.  Good public participation and fruitful co-operation with Government institutes.  Samples analysed by Algerian Institute ISMAL were never announced by Algerian authorities nor handed over to Greenpeace. <BR>
- 1991: 3rd visit  tackles the marine pollution coming from the heavy industry  based in Annaba and Skikda (W. Algeria). <P>

The general picture Greenpeace obtained of the situation in Algeria is that heavy Industry imported in the 60s has never been upgraded and is improperly serviced. The result is intense pollution in the areas where these industries are based. Algeria should seek to leap over the intervening steps and move to clean production. Foreign aid should concentrate on assisting developing countries like Algeria in  closing down their defunct industries and turning over to new, environmentally clean, technologies.
<P>

<HR>

<P>
<A NAME="Egypt">
<FONT SIZE=5><TT><B>Egypt</B></TT><FONT SIZE=3><P>
</A>
Whilst research has been carried out and it is clear that Egypt has many environmental problems that need tackling, and various contacts have been established, little work has actually been done so far. The limitations of Greenpeace resources make it impossible for Greenpeace to tackle the huge problems facing Egypt in a comprehensive and proper way at the moment.
<P>
In Egypt, Greenpeace has so far tackled environmental threats of a more International nature. Egypt being of such geo-political importance inevitably plays a major roles in such matters.
<P>
In 1991 the MV Sirius visited Alexandria to highlight the Barcelona Convention meeting  being held in Cairo. The visited encouraged Mediterranean states to move on environmental commitments.
<P>
One Egyptian authority which Greenpeace is in regular contact with is the Suez Canal authority. There is very good  on-going co-operation between Greenpeace Mediterranean and the Authorities involved. This has proved productive in various instances in tracking ships with hazardous cargoes and campaigning for International waste trade bans.
<P>

<HR>

<P>
<A NAME="Jordan">
<FONT SIZE=5><TT><B>Jordan</B></TT><FONT SIZE=3><P>
</A>
It is only recently that Jordan was added to the Greenpeace Mediterranean list of countries. Whilst not having any Mediterranean shoreline Jordan is close enough, both physically and politically, as to make it relevant for the region.  No work has so far been developed in Jordan.
<P>

<HR>

<P>
<A NAME="Libya">
<FONT SIZE=5><TT><B>Libya</B></TT><FONT SIZE=3><P>
</A>
No activities so far.

<P>

<HR>

<P>
<A NAME="Morocco">
<FONT SIZE=5><TT><B>Morocco</B></TT><FONT SIZE=3><P>
</A>
Morocco was one of the three Magreb countries visited by the MV Sirius on its reconnaissance tour in 1989.  Problematic access to the public and the cold shoulder shown by the authorities did not encourage intensive co-operation.  
<P>

<HR>

<P>
<A NAME="Syria">
<FONT SIZE=5><TT><B>Syria</B></TT><FONT SIZE=3><P>
</A>
Nothing so far.
<P>

<BR><BR><BR>

<HR>

<CENTER>

<A HREF="mailto:grnpeace@email.keyworld.net"><IMG SRC="pics/bottle.gif" ALT="[Send us email!]" ALIGN="bottom" BORDER="none"></A>
