<HTML>

<!-- Greenpeace Mediterranean Home Page -->
<!-- (c) 1996 Greenpeace Mediterranean & InArt Systems -->
<!-- Greenpeace Mediterranean: Cyprus Page-->
<!-- cyprus.html -->
<!-- 28/6/96 - 17/9/96 -->

<!-- Created by InArt Systems Ltd. -->
<!-- "Djamanti," Tumas Galea Str., -->
<!-- B'Kara BKR13, MALTA (Europe). -->
<!-- Tel/Fax: +356 486-591         -->
<!-- Pager: 0710194/6408 (Vassallo P.J.) -->
<!-- Designed by Kenneth Scicluna  -->

<HEAD>

<TITLE>Greenpeace Mediterranean: Cyprus</TITLE>

<BODY BACKGROUND="pics/tile.gif" BGCOLOR=white Text=black link=blue VLINK=purple ALINK=white>

</HEAD>

<!--<FONT SIZE=7><TT><B>Other Countries</B></TT><FONT SIZE=3><BR>-->
<IMG SRC="pics/cyprus.jpg" ALT="[Cyprus]" ALIGN="absmiddle"><P>

<BR><BR>

Before Greenpeace entered the scene, local NGOs had long been campaigning for the establishment of a protected area in the Akamas since 4 years.  When the MV Sirius visited Cyprus for the first time in November 1990  and travelled to the Akamas region with representatives from all the various NGOs involved aboard, a long correspondence between  the Cypriot government and Greenpeace started.  This correspondence contains repeated commitments by the Government of Cyprus to create proper protection for the environment in that area.
<P>
The following April was a moment of intensification for our activities:  
<P>
- One hundred Greenpeace "Sea Turtles" (played by Cypriot schoolchildren) "laid their eggs" in a protest at the Interior Ministry.  
<P>
- Activists from Greenpeace and Cypriot environmental Groups planted forty signs marking and 
calling for protection the area where government planned to establish "service stations" once a 
planned road was opened.
<P>
- Greenpeace activists hung a huge banner with a finger pointing to the office of Photos Photiades, the 
Man of Carlsberg, who would bulldoze Sea Turtles to Extinction.  "Hands off Akamas."
<P>
- Greenpeace activists joined local NGOs to protest outside the House of Representatives on the last 
day of that parliament hoping that the next one would bring about definitive protection measures.         
<P>
Friends of the Earth release results of an opinion poll showing that 83 per cent of Cypriots favour the 
creation of a national park in the region.
<P>
In October 1991 Greenpeace activists occupied the British army shooting range in the Akamas to 
protest destructive activities (i.e. British Army heavy artillery practice) in the peninsula and continued with their call for the protection of the Akamas.  Greenpeace also called upon the Bishop of Paphos, Crysostomos, to abandon plans to develop the land belonging to the church in the Akamas peninsula.
<P>
An International Postcard campaign took place, in the summer 1992, culminating in the carrying of a 
huge Postcard to the presidential Palace.   A special guest on Board the MV Sirius, Papas Pavlos from 
the island of Zakynthos, highlighted the similarity in the threats facing Akamas and  Zakynthos.
<P>
In September 1992, a float portraying a restaurant crushing a turtle was planted in front of the Town 
planning department in Nicosia to protest proposed changes in the construction indicator from 0.5% 
to 15%.
<P>
The following year in February  the outgoing Government significantly endangered the sensitive areas 
of Toxeftra, the Gorges of Avakas and Koufon and the area north of Aylos Yeorgiostis Peylas when it 
approved the planning regulation changes in the construction indicator from 0.5% to 15%.
<P>
In March a Seminar on the Akamas Peninsula was held in Nicosia.
<P>
Four months later in July the recently elected government decided to freeze development in the area 
around the turtle nesting sites for one year declaring that area a "white zone"
<P>
In October 1994 Greenpeace launched a protest at the Commonwealth Heads of State summit to call 
for finalisation of promises to protect the Akamas National Park.
<P>
Last January the Cypriot government relaxed normal building restrictions on the reserve in Akamas 
Bay to allow the development by Thanos Hotels - company owned by Alecos Michaelides who apart 
from being one of the leading hoteliers on the island is also the Foreign Affairs Minister for Cyprus.  
Construction is now moving at a frenetic pace, over an area of 80,000 square meters.  The hotel covers 
areas denominated "protected zone" or "for agricultural use only".  Apart from this it is directly 
adjacent to the sea with the consequent direct interference with the turtle nesting sites.
<P>
Environmental groups in Cyprus, together with the board of the Technical Chamber ( an influential 
technical body for advising the government on technical matters) and with the active support of 
Greenpeace, have been campaigning since years against the destruction of the last sea turtles nesting 
beach in Cyprus and for the establishment of a protected area there.  Governments have come and 
gone, plans changed and/or postponed, promises made but as yet unfulfilled.
<P>

<BR><BR><BR>

<HR>

