<HTML>

<!-- Greenpeace Mediterranean Home Page -->
<!-- (c) 1996 Greenpeace Mediterranean & InArt Systems -->
<!-- Greenpeace Mediterranean: Israel Page-->
<!-- israel.html -->
<!-- 28/6/96 - 17/9/96 -->

<!-- Created by InArt Systems Ltd. -->
<!-- "Djamanti," Tumas Galea Str., -->
<!-- B'Kara BKR13, MALTA (Europe). -->
<!-- Tel/Fax: +356 486-591         -->
<!-- Pager: 0710194/6408 (Vassallo P.J.) -->
<!-- Designed by Kenneth Scicluna  -->

<HEAD>

<TITLE>Greenpeace Mediterranean: Israel</TITLE>

<BODY BACKGROUND="pics/tile.gif" BGCOLOR=white Text=black link=blue VLINK=purple ALINK=white>

</HEAD>

<!--<FONT SIZE=7><TT><B>Other Countries</B></TT><FONT SIZE=3><BR>-->
<IMG SRC="pics/israel.jpg" ALT="[Israel]" ALIGN="absmiddle"><P>

<BR><BR>

In the Summer of 1993 Greenpeace visited Israel for the first time when the organisation`s flagship   
"SV Rainbow Warrior" entered Haifa Harbour. 
<P>
The following year in Autumn, Greenpeace activists took samples from the Kishon River for analysis  
in the Greenpeace laboratories in Exeter University in Britain.  Results proved that the river contains   
a wide variety of heavy metals and organic pollutants. 
<P> 
In May 1995, the ship "MV Greenpeace" launched activists to block the Haifa Chemicals` ship  
"Aribel" from dumping toxic sludge into the Mediterranean Sea.  An opinion poll found out that 72  
per cent preferred to close the factory rather than have the pipe. 
<P>
Later on that summer, a Greenpeace billboard campaign warned Israelis of the threats posed by Haifa  
Chemicals.  Motto: "STOP THE PIPE". 
<P> 
On February 5th 1996, Greenpeace carried out a banner action over the Kishon River and presented  
bottles of water polluted by Haifa Chemicals to the responsible authorities. 
<P>
On February 8th 1996 - i.e. three days later - the Israeli Environment Minister Yossi Sarid finally  
rejected the plan of "Haifa Chemicals" to construct a pipe that would have channelled  
the factories toxic effluents into Haifa Bay.  The US-owned factory discharges more effluents into the sea than any other private enterprise in Israel.  Their pipe was aimed to discharge 270 cubic meters of effluents per hour.
<P>
On July 8th 1996 the ministry of the environment had signed an agreement for a reduction and on-land treatment of these effluents.  Greenpeace`s campaign has been won.  The agreement is far from satisfactory.  Still, it clearly shows the idea that with enough determination even companies like Haifa Chemicals can start a clean up.
<P>
On July 10th 1996 Greenpeace released a report on the hazardous waste management in Israel.  This announced a new focus of activity in Israel: Hazardous Waste Management, Waste Incineration, and Clean Production. 
<P>

<BR><BR><BR>

<HR>

<CENTER>

<A HREF="mailto:grnpeace@email.keyworld.net"><IMG SRC="pics/bottle.gif" ALT="[Send us email!]" ALIGN="bottom" BORDER="none"></A>
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="pics/home.gif" ALT="[Back to the Greenpeace Mediterranean Home
Page]" ALIGN="bottom" BORDER="none"></A>
<A HREF="map.html"><IMG SRC="pics/mapsmall.gif" ALT="[Back to the Greenpeace Mediterranean Map
Page]" ALIGN="bottom" BORDER="none"></A>
