</DOCHDR>
<HTML>

<!-- Greenpeace Mediterranean Home Page -->
<!-- (c) 1996 Greenpeace Mediterranean & InArt Systems -->
<!-- Greenpeace Mediterranean: Lebanon Page-->
<!-- lebanon.html -->
<!-- 28/6/96 - 17/9/96 -->

<!-- Created by InArt Systems Ltd. -->
<!-- "Djamanti," Tumas Galea Str., -->
<!-- B'Kara BKR13, MALTA (Europe). -->
<!-- Tel/Fax: +356 486-591         -->
<!-- Pager: 0710194/6408 (Vassallo P.J.) -->
<!-- Designed by Kenneth Scicluna  -->

<HEAD>

<TITLE>Greenpeace Mediterranean: Lebanon</TITLE>

<BODY BACKGROUND="pics/tile.gif" BGCOLOR=white Text=black link=blue VLINK=purple ALINK=white>

</HEAD>

<!--<FONT SIZE=7><TT><B>Other Countries</B></TT><FONT SIZE=3><BR>-->
<IMG SRC="pics/lebanon.jpg" ALT="[Lebanon]" ALIGN="absmiddle"><P>

<BR><BR>

Our campaign activities  officially started in Lebanon when the Greenpeace  flagship "Rainbow 
Warrior" visited Beirut in November 1994.  It was the first visit of a Greenpeace vessel to Lebanon.  
The local ecological group "Green Line" asked us to sample toxic waste stored in the port to 
determine its origin.  Authorities shortly afterwards opened the containers with the waste and our 
activists took samples.  That was the start of our toxic waste campaign in the country.
<P>
Since then, we have been pressuring authorities to solve the issue of 2,411 tons of toxic waste, which 
were imported in 15,800 barrels and 20 containers from Italy to Lebanon in 1987.  Greenpeace 
Mediterranean published reports about this scandal, identified contaminated areas after sampling the 
soil and released official documents that were kept secret.  The authorities then co-operated with us 
and retrieved 77 tons from several areas and shipped them for incineration to France in April 1996.
<P>
However, two known polluted spots still have to be decontaminated.  But the authorities are refusing 
to do the job.  This is the reason why Greenpeace Mediterranean ended eight months of "co-operation" 
with the Environment Ministry in May 1996.  You can help us pressure Environment Minister Pierre 
Pharaon by signing a petition we want to publish in Lebanon by the end of this year.
<P>
In May 1996, we released a report proving that the cement, asbestos and chemical industries in 
Chekka and Selaata in northern Lebanon are a major source of marine, soil and air pollution.  The 
local "Association for the Protection of the Environment in the Kura" had asked us to sample the sites 
to support their campaign.  The sample tests were carried out by the Greenpeace Laboratory at Exeter 
University in England.  They showed that ground water in Chekka is polluted by a wide range of toxic 
chemicals, while emissions from cement and asbestos factories pollute the air and the Mediterranean 
Sea.  The scientific test results prove that living in and around the Chekka and Selaata region is a 
health hazard.
<P>
Our youngest campaign in Lebanon started in July 1996 when we released a report on plans for 
incinerators and landfills in several southern Mediterranean countries, including Lebanon.  About 1.4 
million tons of household waste and 326,000 tons of industrial waste are produced in Lebanon every 
year.  We are campaigning for an alternative waste management policy focusing on waste reduction, 
reuse and recycling.  In the industry, the solution is the introduction of Clean Production methods.
<P>

<BR><BR><BR>

