<!-- Greenpeace Mediterranean Home Page -->
<!-- (c) 1996 Greenpeace Mediterranean & InArt Systems -->
<!-- Greenpeace Mediterranean: Turkey Page-->
<!-- turkey.html -->
<!-- 28/6/96 - 17/9/96 -->

<!-- Created by InArt Systems Ltd. -->
<!-- "Djamanti," Tumas Galea Str., -->
<!-- B'Kara BKR13, MALTA (Europe). -->
<!-- Tel/Fax: +356 486-591         -->
<!-- Pager: 0710194/6408 (Vassallo P.J.) -->
<!-- Designed by Kenneth Scicluna  -->

<HEAD>

<TITLE>Greenpeace Mediterranean: Turkey</TITLE>

<BODY BACKGROUND="pics/tile.gif" BGCOLOR=white Text=black link=blue VLINK=purple ALINK=white>

</HEAD>

<!--<FONT SIZE=7><TT><B>Other Countries</B></TT><FONT SIZE=3><BR>-->
<IMG SRC="pics/turkey.jpg" ALT="[Turkey]" ALIGN="absmiddle"><P>

<BR><BR>

Greenpeace made its first official visit to meet the public in Turkey in September 1992.  The MV 
Sirius first visited Istanbul then Izmir.  In Istanbul the Greenpeace ship berthed at Ortakoy and it was 
welcomed with great interest both from the public and local environmental groups as well as by the authorities. The Turkish Environment Minister visited the ship and showed his support for Greenpeace's work in general and especially for a Waste Trade Ban which Turkey has long supported.
<P>
In 1993 Greenpeace activists on board the Vega took direct action against the SS United States 
demanding "Return To Sender".  The SS United States was brought to Turkey for  asbestos 
removal.  The ship, which was build in the 1950s and is more than 300m long, was full of asbestos 
and brought to Turkey to cut down on asbestos removal costs.  According to estimates if it were done 
in the US the cost of removal would have been 250 million USD.  Instead Turkey was chosen for 
cheap labour and less strict control. 
<P>
On October 1993 the Greenpeace ship SV Rainbow Warrior entered the Akkuyu nuclear power plant 
construction site.  Its crew members set up a symbolic windmill on the very spot where a nuclear 
reactor is to be built. 
<P>
In 1994 Greenpeace activists from the MV Moby Dick climbed down 30m  from the Bosphorus 
Bridge to draw attention to the movement of hazardous waste and waste trade.  A 25m banner was 
kept hanging by four climber for two whole hours.  Two days later a tanker collision took place in the 
Bosphorus causing a spill of 20 000 tons of crude oil.
<P>
That same year (1994), Greenpeace activists from the MV Greenpeace in attendance in Izmir,and 
Turkish environmentalists staged a radioactive die-off in front of the headquarters of the Turkish 
Electricity Authority in Ankara to demonstrate the threat of building a nuclear power plant while 
others chained themselves to the gates of the building.  The banner read:  "NO MORE 
CHERNOBYLS".  They were all carried out and detained for several hours.  A court later dropped 
charges against them for taking part in an "illegal demonstration" in view of the fact that no violence had occurred.
<P>
In 1995 Greenpeace held a Toxics action in Izmir.  MV Greenpeace crew built a dam on the Meles 
which is one one of the main rivers carrying pollution to the inner Bay in Izmir.  The dam was 4m 
high and 50m long.  Greenpeace campaigned against the dumping of toxic wastes in the rivers 
demanding an immediate STOP of Dumping and a Change to Clean Production. 
<P>
Early this year Greenpeace was awarded the 1995 Peace Prize of the Orhan Apaydin Democracy and 
Peace Foundation for the contribution made by its activists for world peace, and for its ongoing 
peaceful activities against French nuclear testing.
<P>
On March 2nd 1996, five days after the award ceremony, the third session of  a  trial for another activity against Greenpeace and other environmental activists ended in Istanbul with an acquittal. The 32 activists, including many from the Turkish Anti-Nuclear Platform, had been charged of taking part in an "illegal demonstration" in front of the Chinese diplomatic mission in Istanbul on August 19th 1995. If found guilty, they could have been sentenced up to three years in jail.
<P>
On March 26th 1996, Greenpeace held an international press conference in Istanbul, during which it 
revealed to the world the environmental crime carried out by Shell in polluting the Midyat aquifer 
near the city of Diyarbakir in SE Turkey.  It was covered world wide in many well known newspapers, 
televisions and magazines. 
<P>
- It was in August/September 1995 that Greenpeace entered in possession of a number of 
confidential internal reports and memos, written over a number of years by employees of N.V. Turkse 
Shell oil company.  From these documents it became clear that between 1973 and 1994, as a result of 
its oil drilling activities, Shell was severely polluting the Midyat aquifer which supplies potable water 
to the city of Diyarbakir in Eastern Turkey.  About 487.5 million barrels of the plants production 
waters were in fact injected into the aquifer.  According to Shell memos, the amount of oil which 
entered the aquifer in these 20 years, was between 15 and 35 barrels of oil per day. Shell was aware 
that there was a potential threat to the water supply of the city of Diyarbakir over future generations.  
In fact a Shell memo dated July 1994 states that in the worst case scenario, by the year 2006 the 
aquifer under the city of Diyarbakir would be contaminated for the next 100 - 300 years.  Despite this, 
injection continued up to 1995, when Shell sold the plant to Perenco plc - an international company 
operating company formed by merging the two companies, Kelt Energy plc and Perenco.
<P>
On March 27th 1996 - the day following the international press conference in Istanbul - Greenpeace 
representatives visited the Ministry of Environment to brief the authorities in Ankara, who promised 
to follow-up on the case and investigate. 
<P>

<BR><BR><BR>

