<HR>
<FONT SIZE=5><TT><B>Conventions in detail:</B></TT><FONT SIZE=3>
<PRE>
<A NAME="basel"><B><FONT SIZE=+1>
I- BASEL CONVENTION ON THE CONTROL OF TRANSBOUNDARY 
MOVEMENTS OF HAZARDOUS WASTES AND THEIR DISPOSAL
(BASEL, 22 MARCH 1989).
</FONT>
</B>
</A>
<PRE>
    - <B>Objectives:</B>  To set up obligation for State 
    Parties with a view to: 

    (a) reducing transboundary movements of wastes 
    subject to the Basel Convention to a minimum 
    consistent with the environmentally sound and 
    efficient management of such wastes; 

    (b) minimising the amount and toxicity of hazardous 
    wastes generated and ensuring their environmentally 
    sound management (including disposal and recovery 
    operations) as close as possible to the source of 
    generation; 

    (c) assisting developing countries in
    environmentally sound management of the hazardous 
    and other wastes they generate.

    - <B>Entered into force:</B> May 1992,  global. Membership 
    open.

    - <B>Secretariat:</B> UNEP/ Secretariat for the Basel
    Convention, Palais des Nations, 1211 Geneva 10. 
    Switzerland

This convention was modified in September 1995 to include a total 
ban on hazardous waste exports from OECD to non-OECD countries both 
for dumping and for recycling. The ban on waste exports for 
recycling should take effect as from  January 1998.

<B>
Status of signature and  ratification by countries in the 
Mediterranean:
</B>

Countries      Signature of       Signature of       Ratification (r)        Entry into
               Final Act          Convention         Accession (a)           Force         
                                                     Approval (AA)                         
</B><PRE>
<B>ALBANIA</B>        22-03-89           -                  -                       -
<B>ALGERIA</B>        22-03-89           -                  -                       -
<B>CYPRUS</B>         22-03-89           22-03-89           17-09-92 (r)            16-12-92
<B>EGYPT</B>          22-03-89           -                  08-01-93 (a)            08-04-93
<B>ISRAEL</B>         22-03-89           22-03-89           14-12-94 (r)            14-03-95
<B>JORDAN</B>         22-03-89           22-03-89           22-06-89 (AA)           05-05-92
<B>LEBANON</B>        22-03-89           22-03-89           21-12-94 (r)            21-03-95
<B>LIBYA</B>          22-03-89           22-03-89           -                       -
<B>MALTA</B>          22-03-89           -                  -                       -
<B>MOROCCO</B>        22-03-89           -                  28-12-95 (a)            27-03-96
<B>SYRIA</B>          22-03-89           11-10-89           22-01-92 (r)            05-05-92
<B>TURKEY</B>         22-03-89           22-03-89           22-06-94 (r)            20-09-94

<HR>


<A NAME="africa">
<B>
<FONT SIZE=+1>
II- CONVENTION ON THE BAN OF THE IMPORT INTO AFRICA AND 
THE CONTROL OF TRANSBOUNDARY MOVEMENTS AND MANAGEMENT OF 
HAZARDOUS WASTES WITHIN AFRICA (BAMAKO, 30 JANUARY 1991)
</FONT>
</B>
</A>
<PRE>

    - <B>Objectives:</B> To protect human health and the environment 
    from the dangers posed by hazardous wastes by reducing 
    their generation to a minimum in terms of quantity and/or 
    hazard potential. Bans import of hazardous waste to OAU 
    countries including nuclear waste.

    - <B>Regional:</B> Membership restricted to member States of the 
    Organisation of African Unity.

    - <B>Secretariat:</B> OAU, Addis Ababa. Ethiopia.

	Mediterranean countries members of OAU: Algeria, Egypt, 
	Morocco (membership counselled).

<HR>


<A NAME="pollution">
<B>
<FONT SIZE=+1>
III- CONVENTION FOR THE PROTECTION OF THE MEDITERRANEAN
SEA AGAINST POLLUTION.
</FONT>
</B>
</A>
<PRE>
Adopted in Barcelona on 16 February 1976 by sixteen 
Mediterranean States. Entry into force: 12 February 1978. 
The actual number of  Parties to this Convention and its 
related protocols is twenty one (21). It is a broad 
treaty allowing for the adoption of  additional 
implementing protocols. It contains a series of  
framework obligations concerning co-operation in 
emergencies, monitoring, scientific and technological co-
operation, and liability and compensation.
Objectives: To ensure the protection of the Mediterranean 
Sea against pollution from waste dumping, exploration and 
exploitation of the sea-bed and continental shelf , and 
land-based sources and enhance the Mediterranean marine 
environment.

UNEP was designated  as the Convention Secretariat and 
to act as the co-ordinator of the activities agreed upon 
within the framework of the Action Plan agreed upon in 
1975. To this end, the Co-ordinating Unit for the 
Mediterranean Action Plan was created in 1980 and hosted 
by Greece since 1982. 

<B>Address:</B> Co-ordinating Unit of the Mediterranean Action 
Plan, 48, Vas Konstantinou Ave. 11635 Athens. GREECE.
Tel: 30 (1) 725 3190
Fax: 30 (1) 725 3197

The Convention was last amended in 1995 to change title 
and establish the precautionary principle and set the 
elimination of  pollution sources as the ultimate target. 
New title adopted: <B>CONVENTION FOR THE PROTECTION OF THE 
MARINE ENVIRONMENT AND THE COASTAL REGION OF THE 
MEDITERRANEAN.</B>

Status of signatures and ratification of the Convention 
for the Protection of the Mediterranean Sea against 
Pollution and its Protocols (29 February 1996)

<B>
           Convention           Dumping (1)          Emergency (2)        
COUNTRY    Signed     Ratified   Signed     Ratified   Signed     Ratified</B>
<PRE>                                                                             
