                      AC                    AC.R                             

<B>AC = Accession;    AP = Approval;    R = Reservation.</B>

</PRE>
<HR>
<PRE>


1)	- The Protocol for the Prevention of the Pollution of 
	the Mediterranean Sea by Dumping from Ships and Aircraft.
	
	- <B>Adopted:</B> Barcelona, 16 February 1976
	
	- <B>Entry into Force:</B>       12 February 1978

Parties agreed to take appropriate measures to prevent 
and abate pollution of the Med. caused by deliberate 
disposal at of ships and aircraft and of wastes and other 
matter from ships and aircraft. It banned the dumping of 
a list of substances (annex I), allowed the dumping of 
another and put conditions for granting permits to dump 
for a third list (annex III). The last amendment of 1995, 
scrapped the list of materials which were allowed for 
dumping and the only annex remaining kept conditions for 
granting permits.

The amendment also changed the title and the substance to 
introduce a ban on incineration at sea.


2)	- The Protocol concerning Co-operation in Combating 
	Pollution of the Mediterranean Sea by Oil and other 
	Harmful Substances in cases of Emergency. 

	- <B>Adopted:</B> Barcelona, 16 February 1976
	- <B>Entry into Force:</B>       12 February 1978

In virtue of this protocol, the Parties shall co-operate 
in facing grave and imminent danger to the marine 
environment, the coast or related interests of one or 
more of the Parties due to  the presence of massive 
quantities of oil or other harmful substances resulting 
from accidental causes or an accumulation of small 
discharges which are polluting or threatening to pollute 
the sea. Parties were required to promote and maintain 
contingency plans and means for such emergencies.


3)	- The Protocol for the Protection of the Mediterranean 
	Sea against Pollution from Landbased Sources. 

	- <B>Adopted:</B> Athens, 17 May 1980

	- <B>Entry into Force:</B>  17 June 1983
	
	- <B>Objective:</B> combat and abate the dangers posed to marine 
	environment and to human health from land based sources 
	of pollution. Later, in 1995, elimination of these 
	sources became the main objective.

The Parties to this Protocol should adopt appropriate 
programmes and measures to stop polluting the sea by a 
list of nine (9) toxic, persistent and bioaccumulative 
substances and limit the discharge of another twelve (12) 
substances.

<B>Amendments:</B> Adopted in Syracuse, 7 March 1996. 

<B>New title:</B> Protocol for the Protection of the 
Mediterranean Sea against Pollution from Landbased 
Sources and Activities.

New provisions advocated the precautionary principle on 
discharges and clean production as the sustainable and 
alternative to polluting onshore activities. Phase-out 
of nineteen (19) categories of substances which are toxic 
persistent and liable to bioaccumulate was introduced. 
Priority was given to a list of twelve organohalogen 
compounds. To this end, the Parties are obliged to adopt 
timetables and action plans within two years of the 
protocol’s entry into force.
The phase out also includes discharges into internal 
waters and rivers. 


4)	- The Protocol concerning Mediterranean Specially 
	Protected Areas.
	
	- <B>Adopted:</B> Geneva, 3 April 1982
	
	- <B>Entry into Force:</B>   23 March 1986

	- <B>Objective:</B> Protecting and improving the state of the 
	natural resources and sites of the Mediterranean as well 
	as their cultural heritage in the region among other 
	means by the establishment of specially protected areas 
	of marine areas and their environment.

In virtue of the Protocol, protected areas should be 
established to safeguard: 

	- sites of biological and ecological value, 
	
	- the genetic diversity, satisfactory population levels 
	of species and their breeding ground and habitats. 

	- representative types of ecosystems, as well as 
	ecological processes.

	- sites of particular importance because of their 
	scientific, aesthetic, historical,                     
	archaeological, cultural or educational interest.

<B>Amendments:</B>
A new protocol was adopted  on 10 June 1995, replacing 
the 1982 Protocol. The title is:
<B>
The Protocol concerning Specially Protected Areas and 
Biological Diversity in the Mediterranean. Strict and 
clearly provisions for the protection of the marine fauna 
and flora and endangered species were introduced.
</B>

5)	- The Protocol for the Protection of the Mediterranean 
	Sea against Pollution resulting from Exploration and 
	Exploitation of the Continental Shelf and the Seabed and 
	its Subsoil; (the Offshore Protocol). 

	<B>- Adopted:</B> Madrid, 14 October 1994

	<B>- Entry into Force:</B>     - Not Yet Established

</PRE>
<BR><BR><BR>

