<HEAD>

<TITLE>Greenpeace Mediterranean - P/R: 27/Oct/1996 - Ramat Hovav Entrance Blocked</TITLE>

<BODY BACKGROUND="pics/tile.gif" BGCOLOR=white Text=black link=blue VLINK=purple ALINK=white>

</HEAD>

<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=7><TT><B>27/Oct/1996</B></TT>
<FONT SIZE=3><BR>
<IMG SRC="pics/uscore.gif" ALIGN="absmiddle">
</CENTER>

<P>
<BR><BR>

<FONT SIZE=5><TT><B>
Greenpeace Blocks Entrance To Israeli Waste Dump
</B></TT><FONT SIZE=3>
<P>
<IMG SRC="pics/pic_27101996.jpg" ALIGN="absmiddle" ALT="[Wall of Barrels: Greenpeace Activists calling for a ban on Waste Trade]">
<P>
Ramat Hovav, Israel, 27 October 1996 (GP) - Sixteen Greenpeace activists, local
volunteers and crew members of the Greenpeace ship "Arctic Sunrise" blocked today
the entrance of the Ramat Hovav toxic waste dumpsite.
<P>
They erected a wall of barrels and chained themselves to them. On the barrels
was written "Toxic Waste - No Future".
<P>
The Ramat Hovav dumpsite in the Negev hosts most of Israel's industrial toxic
waste. This industrial area is also the home of eight polluting industries. The
major sources of pollution in the area are the dumpsite, the factories
"Machteshim" and "Bromine Compounds" as well as their toxic evaporation ponds.
<P>
Israeli authorities plan to construct a toxic waste incinerator in Ramat Hovav
despite scientific evidence that even state-of-the-art furnaces pollute the
environment and threaten the people living in the region. The Greenpeace
Mediterranean Office demands that these plans be dropped.
<P>
Last week, Greenpeace uncovered that the Ramat Hovav dumpsite received 500
truckloads of contaminated mud. The transport occurred illegally because the
trucks were unmarked and drove through cities. A few days ago a tank full of
hydrochloric acid fell off a truck and nearly killed car drivers.
<P>
"The only solution to this toxic waste crisis in Israel is a preventive
strategy in the framework of clean production in all industrial processes,"
said in Ramat Hovav Ory Zik of the Greenpeace Mediterranean Office. "Greenpeace
demands that the Israeli government adopt a national clean production program
and a clean-up program for Ramat Hovav."
<P>
Greenpeace asked for permission to sample the Ramat Hovav dumpsite and the toxic
waste that was recently brought in. But the company that runs the dumpsite
refused to grant permission.
<P>
"We want to assess the situation now before there is more damage caused by the
planned incinerator. The company seems to have something to hide," said Ruth
Stringer, a Greenpeace scientist from our laboratory in Exeter, England.
<P>
For more information please call Ory Zik, Israeli Campaigner of the Greenpeace
Mediterranean Office, Tel <B>+972-52-433694</B>.
<P>
<BR><BR><BR>

<HR>

