<HEAD>

<TITLE>Greenpeace Mediterranean - P/R: 17/Oct/1996 - Turtles Endangered by Akamas Development</TITLE>

<BODY BACKGROUND="pics/tile.gif" BGCOLOR=white Text=black link=blue VLINK=purple ALINK=white>

</HEAD>

<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=7><TT><B>17/Oct/1996</B></TT>
<FONT SIZE=3><BR>
<IMG SRC="pics/uscore.gif" ALIGN="absmiddle">
</CENTER>

<P>
<BR><BR>

<FONT SIZE=5><TT><B>
Greenpeace Protests Against Hotel In Akamas
</B></TT><FONT SIZE=3>
<P>
<B>Tourism development to destroy turtle nesting area in Cyprus.</B>
<P>

<TABLE CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0>
<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP NOWRAP HEIGHT="100%">
<IMG SRC="pics/pic_17101996.jpg" ALIGN="absmiddle" ALT="[Turtle Ahoy: Greenpeace float used in protest against development of the Akamas peninsula]">
</TD>
<TD ALIGN=RIGHT VALIGN=TOP NOWRAP HEIGHT="100%">
<IMG SRC="pics/pic_17101996a.jpg" ALIGN="absmiddle" ALT="[Turtle Territory: Float & Zodiac off Akamas beach]"><BR>
<IMG SRC="pics/pic_17101996b.jpg" ALIGN="absmiddle" ALT="[Valiant: 'Akamas National Park NOW!']"><BR>
<IMG SRC="pics/pic_17101996c.jpg" ALIGN="absmiddle" ALT="[Mother Turtle: Akamas banner on Arctic Sunrise]"><BR>
</TD>
</TABLE>

<P>
Akamas, Cyprus, 17 October 1996 - Activists from the Greenpeace ship "Arctic
Sunrise" today protested against the construction of a hotel  where
endangered turtles nest. This could lead to more hotels being  built in the
area.
<P>
The activists on inflatables came from the ship and raced to the
construction site. One inflatable, dressed-up like a turtle, manoeuvered
around the area "looking for a nesting site". The activists held banners
saying, "Akamas National Park Now."
<P>
The action was carried out as part of a long-lasting campaign fought by
Cypriot environmental groups and Greenpeace for the Akamas  Peninsula to be
declared a national park. Succeeding Cypriot  governments have made promises
in this direction but have never made  good on them so far.
<P>
The family business of Cypriot Foreign Minister Alecos Michaelides is
currently breaking the law by building the 352-bed hotel that will  directly
impact an area of 80,000 m2. Last January, the government  relaxed building
restrictions in Akamas to allow the development by  the minister's company
"Thanos Hotels". Other firms have asked  permission to build hotels there.
<P>
The Loggerhead Turtles and the Green Turtles nest in the beaches of  Akamas.
The endangered Green Turtles depend on the Akamas  beaches for their
survival in the Mediterranean.(1) A great part of the  construction involved
is actually on the beach in the protected zone.
<P>
"Greenpeace supports the court case of the Cypriot Technical Chamber  and
the Cypriot ecological group Friends of Akamas against the hotel  owners,"
said on the "Arctic Sunrise" Dr. Mario Damato from the  Greenpeace
Mediterranean Office.
<P>
"The construction has to stop at once and the Akamas Peninsula must  be
declared a national park," he said.
<P>
The Greenpeace position is shared by the World Bank which published  a
report on Akamas last March. British Sunvill tourist operators has  said
that embarking on a large-scale development in Akamas will only  worsen the
disastrous environmental reputation of Cyprus.
<P>
Greenpeace met the state minister responsible for the environment, Mr.  K
Petrides, in Nicosia last Monday (Oct. 14). But he did not make a  clear
commitment to protect Akamas.
<P>
Petrides told Greenpeace that his biggest problem in solving the issue is
<P>
Dr. Damato said: "The government of Cyprus must stop hiding behind  the
excuse that the illagers are mistreated by the declaration of a  national
park in Akamas. It is two or three big influential landowners  who possess
the crucial land that has to be dealt with and not the  villagers."
<P>
"All the experts consulted have pointed in the same direction. Halt all
development in Akamas now," he concluded.
<P>
For more information please call in Cyprus Dr. Mario Damato,
Executive Director of the Greenpeace Mediterranean Office, <B>+357-9-
582596</B>, or on the "Arctic Sunrise", mobile via Amsterdam <B>+31-653-
911773</B>; or press officer Fouad Hamdan in Lebanon, <B>+961-1-785665</B>
or mobile <B>+961-3-756429</B>.
<P>
Email: <A HREF="greenpeace.mediterranean@green2.greenpeace.org">
greenpeace.mediterranean@green2.greenpeace.org</A>
.
<A HREF="med.media@green2.greenpeace.org">med.media@green2.greenpeace.org</A> 
<P>
<BR>
<B>Notes:</B>
<P>
1. The IUCN (International Union for the Conservation of Nature) lists
Loggerhead Turtles as vulnerable and Green Turtles as endangered  species.
The annual numbers of Green Turtle nesting females in the  entire
Mediterranean could be as low as 325-375. Apart from Cyprus, they nest in a
very few other states in the basin.
<P>
<BR><BR><BR>

