<HEAD>

<TITLE>Greenpeace Mediterranean - P/R: 5/Oct/1996 - Gokova Power Plant - Update</TITLE>

<BODY BACKGROUND="pics/tile.gif" BGCOLOR=white Text=black link=blue VLINK=purple ALINK=white>

</HEAD>

<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=7><TT><B>5/Oct/1996</B></TT>
<FONT SIZE=3><BR>
<IMG SRC="pics/uscore.gif" ALIGN="absmiddle">
</CENTER>

<P>
<BR><BR>

<FONT SIZE=5><TT><B>
Update On The Gokova Action
</B></TT><FONT SIZE=3>
<P>
<IMG SRC="pics/pic_05101996.jpg" ALIGN="absmiddle" ALT="[Gokova: Greenpeace activists in court]">
<P>
Izmir, Turkey, 5  October 1996 (GP) - The Greenpeace ship Arctic Sunrise  left 
Turkey shortly after the release of 18 activists that took part in a peaceful action 
against a polluting power plant.
<P>
Six Greenpeace activists sneaked into the main building on October 4 of the 
polluting Gokova coal-powered electricity plant.  12 more entered the grounds 
and chained themselves to machines in the building where the three furnaces are 
linked to a 300-meter smokestack, the highest in the Middle East.
<P>
They held flags with the slogan in Turkish and English, "Enough is Enough" and 
flew a banner from window of the building.  Troops from the National Guard 
intervened, cut the chains and detained them all releasing them in the evening.  
Half of the activists were Turkish volunteers, half was from the international ship s 
crew.
<P>
The Gokova power station is the largest and most recent of a triangle of power 
stations built near the city of Mugla in the Aegean region. On  20 June 1996, the 
three power stations in Gokova, Yenikoy and Yatagan received an order of 
closure from the Aydin Administrative Court. However, the Turkish Council of 
Ministers declared on 11 September 1996 its intention to operate the stations 
notwithstanding the court's decision. (1) 
<P>
The Greenpeace Mediterranean Office warns that the court case won by the 
Izmir Lawyers of Environment is a turning point for the future of environmental  
and  legal issues in Turkey.  The  court  decision should  be  implemented  
immediately and  the  government  should comply with its own laws and 
regulations. 
<P>
"The Turkish government violates its own regulations with such ease, 
irresponsibility and cool-headedness that it sets a terrible example for those who 
are up to similar environmental crimes in Turkey," said Melda Keskin, Energy 
Campaigner of the Greenpeace Mediterranean Office in Turkey.  
<P>
The Turkish Ministry of Energy and the Turkish Electricity Authority have been 
operating the three coal-powered  plants since years  without any of the requisite 
licenses.  Furthermore,  the damage to the environment is increased by the fact 
that they have neither flue gas desulphurisation nor treatment for their discharge 
water.  They burn poor quality coal with a high percentage of ash, sulphur and 
uranium.  
<P>
Greenpeace demands that Turkey invests in energy efficiency technologies in 
order to stop wasting energy.  More than 25 per cent of the electricity produced 
in Turkey is lost in the outdated transmission and distribution system.  
<P>
"Present plans to operate these power stations and follow-up with the  
installation  of  Nuclear Power  stations  is  suicidal  and reflects  a short term-
policy," concluded Keskin, "the future  is in  Energy  Efficiency and Alternative 
Energies  like  solar  and wind.  Turkey must adopt an energy policy to meet the 
demands  of the 21st century and stop risking the lives of its people who deserve 
to live in a clean and safe environment. 
<P>
For more information please contact Melda Keskin, Energy Campaigner of the 
Greenpeace Mediterranean Office. 
<P>
Email: <A HREF="melda.keskin@green2.greenpeace.org">melda.keskin@green2.greenpeace.org</A>
.
<A HREF="greenpeace.mediterranean@green2.greenpeace.org">
greenpeace.mediterranean@green2.greenpeace.org</A>
<P>
<BR>
<B>NOTES:</B>
<P>
1. The Constitution of the Turkish Republic is very clear on this matter. In Article 
18/4 it states : "Legislative, executive powers and administration  are obliged to 
obey the decision of the courts. These powers and the administration can never 
change and delay the implementation of the courts' decisions." 
<P>
2. Scientists appointed by the Aydin Administrative Court spent 1.5 years 
working on the expert's report submitted to the court. This report clearly proves 
that the power plants concerned cause environmental damage. The Ministry of 
Environment claims that recent research on all three plants, using mobile 
measuring equipment during one week, showed that these power plants are 
"clean".
 
<P>
<BR><BR><BR>

