<HEAD>

<TITLE>Greenpeace Mediterranean - P/R: 4/Oct/1996 - Gokova Power Plant</TITLE>

<BODY BACKGROUND="pics/tile.gif" BGCOLOR=white Text=black link=blue VLINK=purple ALINK=white>

</HEAD>

<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=7><TT><B>4/Oct/1996</B></TT>
<FONT SIZE=3><BR>
<IMG SRC="pics/uscore.gif" ALIGN="absmiddle">
</CENTER>

<P>
<BR><BR>

<FONT SIZE=5><TT><B>
Enough Is Enough!
</B></TT><FONT SIZE=3>
<P>
<B>Greenpeace sneak into Turkish power plant to support court order.</B>
<P>
<IMG SRC="pics/pic_04101996.jpg" ALIGN="absmiddle" ALT="[Yeter! Greenpeace activists outside Gokova Plant]">
<P>
Gokova, Turkey, 4  October 1996 (GP) - Greenpeace activists sneaked today 
into
the polluting Gokova coal-powered electricity plant. They chained themselves to
machines in the building where the three furnaces are linked to a 300-meter
smokestack, the highest in the Middle East. 
<P>
They held flags with the slogan in Turkish and English, "Enough  is Enough".
Troops from the National Guard intervened, cut the chains and detained the
activists.
<P>
The Gokova power station is the largest of a triangle of power stations built
near the city of Mugla in the Aegean region. On  20 June 1996, the three power
stations in Gokova, Yenikoy and Yatagan received an order of closure from the
Aydin Administrative Court. However, the Turkish Council of Ministers declared
on 11 September 1996 its intention to operate the stations notwithstanding the
court's decision. (1)
<P>
"This is the last straw. Enough is enough," said in Gokova Melda Keskin of the
Greenpeace Mediterranean Office. "It is a  shame  that  the Ministry of
Environment authorizes polluting the environment and disregards an official
500-page experts' report backing the court decision."(2)
<P>
The Greenpeace Mediterranean Office warns that the court case won by the 
Izmir
Lawyers of Environment is a turning point for the future of environmental  and
legal issues in Turkey.  The  court  decision should  be  implemented
immediately and  the  government  should comply with its own laws and
regulations.
<P>
"The Turkish government violates its own regulations with such ease,
irresponsibility and coolheadedness that it sets a terrible example for  those
who are up to similar environmental crimes in Turkey," Keskin said.
<P>
The Turkish Ministry of Energy and the Turkish Electricity Authority have been
operating the three coal-powered  plants since years  without  any of the
requisite licenses.  Furthermore,  the damage to the environment is increased
by the fact that they have neither flue gas desulphurisation nor treatment for
their discharge water.  They burn poor quality coal with a high percentage of
ash, sulphur and uranium. 
<P>
Greenpeace demands that Turkey invests in energy efficiency technologies in
order to stop wasting energy.  More than 25 per cent of the electricity
produced in  
"Present plans to operate these coal-powered plants and follow-up with the
installation of nuclear power stations is suicidal and reflects a short
term-policy,"tive Director Dr. Mario Damato, <B>+90-532-2474314</B>; or Press Officer
Fouad Hamdan in Lebanon, mobile <B>+961-3-756429</B>. 
<P>
Email: <A HREF="melda.keskin@green2.greenpeace.org">melda.keskin@green2.greenpeace.org</A>
.
<A HREF="greenpeace.mediterranean@green2.greenpeace.org">
greenpeace.mediterranean@green2.greenpeace.org</A>

<P>
<BR>
