<HEAD>

<TITLE>Greenpeace Mediterranean - P/R: 24/Sep/1996 - Izmir Ecosystem Collapse</TITLE>

<BODY BACKGROUND="pics/tile.gif" BGCOLOR=white Text=black link=blue VLINK=purple ALINK=white>

</HEAD>

<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=7><TT><B>24/Sep/1996</B></TT>
<FONT SIZE=3><BR>
<IMG SRC="pics/uscore.gif" ALIGN="absmiddle">
</CENTER>

<P>
<BR><BR>

<FONT SIZE=5><TT><B>
Greenpeace Reports Ecosystem Collapse In Izmir
</B></TT><FONT SIZE=3><BR>
<B><TT>Environmental Activists Sample Turkish Industry In Aliaga</B></TT>
<P>
<IMG SRC="pics/pic_24091996.jpg" ALIGN="absmiddle" ALT="[Bouqet, Hardly potable: Greenpeace Activists sample the waters off Aliaga]">
<P>
Izmir, Turkey, 24th September 1996 (GP) - The Greenpeace Mediterranean
Office today published scientific report saying that Izmir Bay is seriously
under threat by the industry in and around the   
port city. 
<P>
Early in the morning, the international environmental organisation also
continued its research by sampling the industrial zone off the coast of
Aliaga 55 kilometres north of Izmir. 
<P>
The activists came in inflatables from the Greenpeace ship "Arctic Sunrise"
and took samples directly from discharges of the Aliaga Petrochemical C.O.
The village of Aliaga was a fishing center until  
metal, petrochemical, paper and chemical fertilizer industries settled
there in the 1980s.(1) 
<P>
Armed soldiers told the activists to stop the sampling action and leave the
area, but these orders were ignored and the samples were taken. 
<P>
"The report on Izmir Bay gives clear scientific evidence of the disastrous
situation building up there," said Tolga Temuge from the Greenpeace
Mediterranean Office in Izmir.  "The test results of the 
samples Greenpeace took last summer prove that the ecosystem in Izmir Bay
will collapse if the systematic discharge of  untreated industrial waste
continues." 
<P> 
The test results, carried out by the Greenpeace laboratory at Exeter
University in England, said that the discharges from the Bornova Industrial
estate are increasing the anthropogenic load of toxic heavy  
metals into the waters of the Meles River - and thus into Izmir Bay. (2)   
<P>
Levels of mercury found in the fresh surface water system are generally
lower than one ug/liter. But the high level of 72 ug/liter in one of the
water samples indicated a serious mercury pollution in Izmir 
Bay, the report said. 
<P>
"Results suggest that if discharging of  untreated industrial effluents,
directly to surface waters flowing into the bay, continues, then severe,
detrimental effects on ecosystems existing within the bay will be observed,"
the report concluded. 
<P>
There are more than 1,000 industries in Izmir that pump industrial fluid
waste.  Only 33 of them have treatment  plants, most of them rudimentary.
Turkish authorities put the limits of toxic substances in  
wastewater far higher than in the European Union.  For example, the limits
for the toxic heavy metal cadmium in wastewater is 2 mg per liter - 10 times
higher than in Britain.   
<P>
The Izmir Sewage Treatment Project is presently underway and should be able
to deal with domestic bio-degradable waste.  Toxic waste should not,
however, continue to flow into common sewers since this cannot be dealt with
in the same way.  The only real solution to toxic waste will come about when
the industry in Turkey embraces the concept and practice of Clean Production.
<P> 
For further information please contact Dr. Mario Damato, Executive Director
of the Greenpeace Mediterranean Office, mobile <B>0090-532-2474314</B>; or 
Press Officer Fouad Hamdan in Lebanon, mobile <B>00961-3-756429</B>. 
<P>
Email: <A HREF="turkey.toxics@green2.greenpeace.org">turkey.toxics@green2.greenpeace.org</A>
.
<A HREF="greenpeace.mediterranean@green2.greenpeace.org">greenpeace.mediterranean@green2.greenpeace.org</A>

<P>
<BR>
<B>ATTENTION EDITORS:</B>
<P>
The report on Izmir Bay and a summary can be ordered from us. 
<P>
<BR>
<B>NOTES:</B>
<P>
1. The air pollution caused by the industries in the Aliaga area is visible.
The air control systems of  the factories are totally inadequate.  Some 6.5
tons/hour of  SO2 and 0.9 ton/hour NOX gases are emitted from these
industries, a report from the Aliaga Municipality said.  The shipyards, the
petroleum refinery and Petrochemical C.O. pollute the sea with their
discharges.   
<P> 
2. The sampling in Izmir Bay was carried out in August 1995 when the
Greenpeace ship Altair visited the port city. Dr. David Santillo of
Greenpeace's Laboratory at Exeter in England and Greenpeace 
Medterranean campaigner Tolga Temuge took the samples. 
<P>
<BR><BR><BR>

