</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Summary</TITLE>
</HEAD><body background="../icons/back5.gif" body bgcolor="345599" text="9cfcfc" LINK="FAF13B" VLINK="FF8300" ALINK="FFFFB8">
<BODY><a href="plunfor.html">Last Page</a>  |  <a href="plun01.html">Next Page</a>   |   <a href="plunindx.html">index</a>
<HR WIDTH=100% ALIGN=left SIZE=3>

<p><font Size=+3>'Chronicle of a Plunder Foretold':</font>
<h2>Summary</h2>

In 1900, 3 million tons of fish were harvested from the global 
seas. The world's catch has increased throughout this century. In 
1989 it reached 86 million tons - but then the increase stopped. 
In recent years the global catches have decreased. RGI is one of 
the largest single players in the world's fishery, with control 
over 10% of the world's whitefish resources. In this report 
Greenpeace provides the arguments for the opposition against 
RGI's factory trawler American Monarch, and its introduction into 
the Chilean southern blue whiting fishery. We evaluate a number 
of research reports and a number of problem areas in connection 
with the crisis in the global fisheries: 
<p>
- according to FAO, over-capacity in the world's fishing fleets 
is more than 100%. In 13 of the 15 most important fishing regions 
catches are declining in spite of increased fishing effort. Today 
we see increasing problems with both food production and 
employment. Both issues are closely linked with the crisis in the 
world's fisheries.
<p>
- in 1996, 800 million people live below the starvation level, 
and the situation continues to worsen. The production of the two 
main sources of food - grain and fish - have first stagnated and 
then declined during the past 6-7 years. 
<p>
- the Norwegian Governemnt is playing an important role in the 
fishing activities of RGI. The Department of Industry and Energy, 
the Foreign Ministry as well as the Government Fund for Business 
and District Development (SND) have provided important economic 
as well as practical support. Now it remains to be seen whether 
the Department of Fisheries will follow suite by granting RGI the 
quotas associated with the takeover of Melbu Fishery Industry. 
<p>
The world has experienced the catastrophic consequences which 
overharvesting of resources can lead to. In those areas which 
have been subject to intensive harvest by the multinational 
factory trawler fleet, stocks have collapsed or been reduced 
substantially. Yet current plans are to send the largest surimi 
supertrawler ever built to an area without any fishery management 
plan, where 8 of the 9 most important fishery resources are 
either considerably reduced or collapsed, where the marine 
ecology is in a critical state due to overfishing and where the 
living conditions of the coastal communities have already been 
degraded. 
<p>
A number of reports, among others that from the fishing trip by 
RGI's own vessel, American Dynasty, discredit RGI's argument that 
the planned fishery will not affect the coastal fisheries. Here 
it is clearly documented that a ship with the capacity of the 
American Monarch will subject both the fishery resources and the 
ecosystem to a considerable amount of damage. 
<p>
The report RGI/IFOP (Chilean Research Institute) completed with 
the American Seafood Company (RGI subsidiary) trawler American 
Dynasty in 1993 does not recommend the kind of fishery into which 
it is planned to send the American Monarch. That report is based 
on 6 months "simulation of commercial fishery", and this is far 
too thin a basis upon which to base a recommendation for an 
intensive harvest of any species. Regardless of how one evaluates 
the figures in the report, it is clear that the extraordinary 
efficiency of the American Monarch constitutes a considerable 
threat to the local fish resources and consequently the living 
standards of the coastal communities. The fact is that the 
American Monarch has such a large capacity that THIS VESSEL ALONE 
is able to harvest the entire stock of southern blue whiting in 
one year. 
<p>Consequently, Greenpeace is sceptical of RGI when they insist 
that they will carry out a sustainable, responsible kind of 
fishery in Chile, in spite of the total fishing capacity of the 
American Monarch. Based on all documentation available, the only 
defensible conclusion is that the American Monarch must never be 
introduced into the southern blue whiting fishery in Chile.




