<! record 0001 of 844>
<TITLE>MASSIVE CYCLONE THREATENS NORTHWEST AUSTRALIA</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<IMG SRC= "../icons/gpclogo.gif" ALT="Greenpeace Logo"><BR>
<H3><B>MASSIVE CYCLONE THREATENS NORTHWEST AUSTRALIA</B></H3><P>

With the strength of Cyclone Tracy that had devastated Darwin in
1974 and packing winds of up 250 kph and a central pressure of
935 hectapascals, Cyclone Annette, caused hundreds to flee their
homes in north Western Australia early in the month. The remnants
of Annette, combined with a low pressure system, also brought
some relief to drought affected farmers in New south Wales later
in the month.  ("Hundreds evacuated as cyclone crosses coast",
The Australian, 19 December 1994; "Beat rain in a year signals
end of drought for some",  The Australian, 29 December 1994).<P>

Note:<P>

Other strong cyclones near Australia in recent years include:<P>

- February 1991. Cyclone Joy: A Category Four (out of five)
cyclone that brought the worst flooding in ninety years to the
Queensland coast.<P>

- March 1992. Cyclone Ian: Category Four storm which hit the
Western Australian coast and caused minimal damage.<P>

- February 1993. Cyclone Oliver: The strongest cyclone to
threaten the Queensland coast since early this century, but
failed to make landfall. Also Category Four.<P>

GREENPEACE Climate Impacts Database<P>

