<! record 0002 of 844>
<TITLE>HEATWAVES COMPOUNDS DROUGHT IN AUSTRALIA</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<IMG SRC= "../icons/gpclogo.gif" ALT="Greenpeace Logo"><BR>
<H3><B>HEATWAVES COMPOUNDS DROUGHT IN AUSTRALIA </B></H3><P>

Record temperatures compounded the growing drought problems
across eastern Australia and Sydney was scorched by the hottest
December day in 37 years. Temperatures reached up to 44oC and 34
were hospitalised in the New South Wales capital and many more
people were treated for heat exhaustion, heat stress, sun burn
and dehydration. Other problems resulted from road surfaces
melting, blackouts resulted from over demand for electricity and
train services were cancelled as the heat created problems with
overhead wires. The heat also contributed to record high levels
of ozone pollution. In the north and west of the state the hot
and dry conditions caused blue-green algae, which can be toxic to
humans and animals, to bloom in Barwon/Darling river system. The
heat also destroyed what little has grown as a result of the
previous months storms. The heat soon gave way to cold weather
however, with Sydney measuring its coldest Christmas Day since
1962. ("44 oC Mercury mayhem", Daily Telegraph Mirror [Sydney],
22 December 1994; "Hot days worsen north-west thirst", Sydney
Morning Herald, 20 December 1994; "Now it's air pollution
apartheid", Sydney Morning Herald, 23 December
1994; "Farmers welcome a little liquid gold", Sydney Morning
Herald, 26 December 1994).<P>

GREENPEACE Climate Impacts Database<P>

