<! record 0005 of 844>
<TITLE>PLEAS FOR HELP IN DROUGHT-STRICKEN CAMBODIA</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<IMG SRC= "../icons/gpclogo.gif" ALT="Greenpeace Logo"><BR>
<H3><B>PLEAS FOR HELP IN DROUGHT-STRICKEN CAMBODIA </B></H3><P>

Rice shortages are expected as drought continues in Cambodia and
one-in-five of the counties population is threatened with
starvation. Three hundred thousand hectares have been affected,
and  in excess of $100 million agricultural damage sustained and
government officials estimate that the rice shortfall will be
between 160,000 to 180,000 tonnes. The drought has come atop the
impact of last August's floods whish destroyed thousands of
hectares of crops. Elsewhere in South-East Asia drought has taken
a further toll. In Indonesia, 700,000 tonnes will be cut from
yearly rubber production, 55,000 tonnes from the annual cocoa
crop will be lost and combined with the impacts of this years
flooding, drought has caused rice production to fall by 3.6
percent in 1994.  The loss of rice production has lead to
government to import 900,000 tonnes to stabilise the domestic
rice market. This years drought in Malaysia has caused cocoa
production to fall by 10 percent.<P>

("Drought-ravaged Cambodia seeks international help", Reuter, 29
November 1994; "Farmers may face starvation if drought
continues",  AP World stream, 4 December 1994; "Indonesia:
Indonesia - drought hurting natural rubber", Chemicals Business
News Wire, 8 December 1994; "Bad weather, pests ravage
Indonesia/Malaysia cocoa",  The Reuter Asia-Pacific Business
Report, 1 December 1994; "Indonesia to continue importing rice",
United Press International, 27 December 1994).<P>

GREENPEACE Climate Impacts Database<P>

