<! record 0008 of 844>
<TITLE>DROUGHT BRINGS MORE STARVATION FEARS TO AFRICA</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<IMG SRC= "../icons/gpclogo.gif" ALT="Greenpeace Logo"><BR>
<H3><B>DROUGHT BRINGS MORE STARVATION FEARS TO AFRICA
</B></H3><P>

Early wet season rainfall has failed across Southern Africa and
serious rainfall deficits have already been recorded in Lesotho,
such of South Africa, Botswana, Zimbabwe, Zambia, southeastern
Angola, Malawi and Mozambique. Crops failures mean that extra
food will be need to feed millions of people. In southern
Mozambique, UN officials are describing the situation as "very,
very serious," with the hardest hit regions among the most
populous in the country of 15 million. Around 300,000 Zambian
families already face starvation, the result of last years failed
rains and it is estimated that 10 million people will need food
aid in Zimbabwe. Zimbabwe, the regions largest grain producer,
has also suspended maize exports for fear of drought. In South
Africa, temperatures rose up to 40 oC and the heatwave brought
fires to the west and south of the country, that have destroyed
crops and pine plantations. Drought and high temperatures have
also killed stock and delayed crop planting in Namibia.
("Southern Africa faces food crisis from drought", BC Cycle
[Reuter], 22 December 1994; "Southern Africa-Drought: Patchy Rain
Worries Farmers",  Inter Press Service, 6 December 1994; "Newly
democratic Mozambique faces food disaster", BC Cycle [Reuter], 22
December 1994; "Heat wave grips southern Africa", The Times, 23
December 1994; "Zimbabwe suspends maize exports on drought
fears", BC Cycle [Reuter], 23 December 1994; "Little rain, hot
temperatures delay planting", AP World stream, 19 December
1994).<P>

