<! record 0011 of 844>
<TITLE>GLOBAL WARMING CONTINUES IN 1994</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<IMG SRC= "../icons/gpclogo.gif" ALT="Greenpeace Logo"><BR>
<H3><B>GLOBAL WARMING CONTINUES IN 1994 </B></H3><P>

Scientists from the British Meteorological Office Hadley Centre
for Climate Prediction and the University of East Anglia suggest
that 1994 will go into the record books as the third hottest year
on record. Temperatures averaged 0.31 oC above the 1951-1980
average.  Temperatures were above average over central and
eastern Europe, Mongolia  and the Middle East, but cooler than
average in Labrador and Greenland.  The 1980s and early 1990s
have been the hottest since reliable land and sea temperature
measurements began in 186,  and nine of the ten hottest years
have  occurred since 1980 (1944 is the exception).  The massive
injection of heat-reflecting ash from the 1991 Mt Pinatubo
eruption kept temperatures down in the early 1990s.  Its effect
has now almost worn off. Other factors, such as the warm oceans
associated with the recent protracted El Nino event in the
Pacific has also influenced this year's  temperature.<P>

Note: The global temperature record this century shows rapid
warming to 1940, a relatively steady period until the mid-1970s
and rapid warming since then. Since the mid-nineteenth century
global temperatures have increased by around 0.5oC and the warmth
in the 1980s was unprecedented. Temperatures have increased in
all seasons in the southern hemisphere and in spring, winter and
autumn in the northern hemisphere. Summers in the northern
hemisphere show very little or no warming since the late 1800s.
(P.D. Jones, T.M.L. Wigley & K.R. Briffa, "Global and hemispheric
temperature anomalies - land and marine instrumental records",
p.603-608, in T.A. Boden, D.P. Kaiser, R.J. Sepanski & F.W. Stoss
(eds), Trends '93: A Compendium of Data on Global Change,
ORNL/CDIAC-65, Carbon Dioxide Information Analysis Center, Oak
Ridge National Laboratory, Oak Ridge, Tenn., USA.<P>

        The Planet's 10 Hottest Years on Record (1854-1994):<P>

--- TABLE ---<P>

The Planet's 10 Hottest Years on Record (1854-1994):<P>

Year Temperatures anomaly (degrees C)<P>

1990  0.38
1989  0.35
1988  0.31
1994*  0.31
1991  0.30
1981  0.26
1987  0.21
1993*  0.21
1986  0.17
1992*  0.17
1944  0.16<P>

Years have been influenced by the eruption of Mt Pinatubo.
Modelling work at NASA suggests that the dust from this eruption
may have temporarily cooled the planet by up to 0.5OC.<P>

*Not corrected for ENSO.<P>

GREENPEACE Climate Impacts Database<P>

