<! record 0012 of 844>
<TITLE>PAST LINKS BETWEEN ANTARCTIC AND GREENLANDIC
CLIMATE</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<IMG SRC= "../icons/gpclogo.gif" ALT="Greenpeace Logo"><BR>
<H3><B>PAST LINKS BETWEEN ANTARCTIC AND GREENLANDIC CLIMATE
</B></H3><P>

Analysis of ice cores from Greenland and from Vostok, Antarctica,
indicate past climatic links between the two regions. While the
Greenland ice cores record 22 interstadials, or warm events,
between 20,000 and 105,000 years ago, and the Vostok ice core
shows 9 interstadials during the same period, the interstadials
occurred in Antarctica whenever they had lasted 2000 years in
Greenland. This suggests that deglaciation and changes in oceanic
circulation may have  linked climatic events between the two
regions. (M. Bender, T. Sowers, M.-L. Dickson, J. Orchardo, P.
Grootes, P.A. Mayewski and D.A. Meese, "Climate correlations
between Greenland and Antarctica during the past 100,000 years",
Nature, v. 372, p.663-666,  15 December 1994).<P>

GREENPEACE Climate Impacts Database<P>

