<! record 0014 of 844>
<TITLE>MODELLING THE CLIMATIC FUTURE.</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<IMG SRC= "../icons/gpclogo.gif" ALT="Greenpeace Logo"><BR>
<H3><B>MODELLING THE CLIMATIC FUTURE. </B></H3><P>

Since many important aspects of human civilisation, like
agriculture, fisheries and energy, are sensitive to extreme
weather events and climatic variations, understanding the way
climate functions and responds to change is crucial. Recent years
this importance has been underscored by the realisation that
global warming may change the climate in a way unprecedented in
human history.  <P>

One of the central ways used to understand the
behaviour of the climate has been by the use of numerical models,
in particular powerful computer based programs called general
circulation models (GCMs). GCM's are powerful computer
simulations of the global climate system and how it operates.
However, many climatic events, like storms, clouds, precipitation
or evaporation take place on much smaller scales than the
resolution of the GCMs, and thus, can not handled by the models
directly. This problem is dealt with by linking them to larger
scale parameters, like air pressure and humidity which the model
can handle. Though GCM's are still not a perfect replication of
the global climate and how it react to various variables,
computers are still not powerful enough to handle all relevant
climatic information, nor do we understand all processes that
influence the climate, they reproduce the features of the current
global climate with considerable accuracy, like distribution of
pressure, temperature, wind and precipitation. The accuracy is
less the smaller the climatic scale, e.g. on sub-continental
scale. <P>

In spite of the small scale inaccuracies, though, GCM's
provide us with reason to believe that the large-scale pattern of
change is largely correct. The world is indeed almost certain to
become warmer. How great the warming, how climatic elements like
soil moisture, precipitation and evaporation will be influenced,
and when these changes will take place is, however, less
certain.<P>

(Henry Hengeveld, "Modelling the Global Climate System",
Atmospheric Environment Service, 13 November 1994).<P>

GREENPEACE Climate Impacts Database<P>

