<HEAD>
<! record 0033 of 844>
<TITLE>NEW MODEL SUPPORTS WARMING SCENARIO</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<IMG SRC= "../icons/gpclogo.gif" ALT="Greenpeace Logo"><BR>
<H3><B>NEW MODEL SUPPORTS WARMING SCENARIO </B></H3><P>

A team of climatologists from the U.K. Meteorological Office
Hadley Centre have released the results of a computer modelling
project which for the first time mimics observed climatic
fluctuations since reliable records began in 1860. This model has
double significance: it refutes claims that climate models are
necessarily unreliable; and it confirms that unprecedented
warming is taking place. The Hadley GCM is the first to
incorporate the effect of sulfate particle pollution, which has a
net cooling effect by reflecting solar heat back into space, and
shows that this effect is slightly greater than expected, and
currently offsets about 30 percent of global warming.<P>

Global temperature trends show a plateau from 1860 to 1920, an
increase of 0.3 oC during the thirties and forties, then another
plateau until 1970, when temperatures again started to rise
steadily.  According to the Hadley GCM, these trends reflect
periods of increased industrialisation during the late 19th
century, and during the World War II. In both these periods,
increased fossil fuel use resulted in sulfate emissions, which
for a time countered global warming until CO2 emissions overcame
the sulfate effect and re-initiated the warming trend.<P>

While the present warming trend is twice as fast as any previous
trend, the Hadley Centre team state that it may still be a decade
before the global warming "signal" is clearly discernible above
background climatic fluctuations.   And more data is required  on
atmospheric sulfate levels  and on the effects of clouds in a
global warming world.  ("The rise and rise of global warming",
New Scientist, p.6, 26 November 1994).<P>

GREENPEACE Climate Impacts Database<P>

<HR>
