<! record 0034 of 844>
<TITLE>SCOTTISH BOGS STORE MOST OF UK'S CARBON</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<IMG SRC= "../icons/gpclogo.gif" ALT="Greenpeace Logo"><BR>
<H3><B>SCOTTISH BOGS STORE MOST OF UK'S CARBON </B></H3><P>

While tropical regions store carbon in vegetation, soil is now
understood to play a larger storage role in temperate regions.  
Total  carbon stored  in British soils, for example, is estimated
at 22 billion tonnes, equivalent to more than 100 years of carbon
dioxide emissions from power stations and vehicles. Researchers
from the Institute of Terrestrial Ecology in Edinburgh have found
that Scotland's peat bogs store 75 percent of the organic carbon 
tied up in soils and vegetation in the UK.  However, Scotland's
largest peat areas are increasingly under threat from draining
for conifer plantations and peat cutting.  Previous government
estimations which suggested a minimal atmospheric release of
carbon from these activities  will now need to be revised and
efforts made to protect this significant carbon sink.  ("Peat
bogs hold bulk of Britain's carbon",  New Scientist, p.6, 19
November 1994).<P>

GREENPEACE Climate Impacts Database<P>

