<! record 0035 of 844>
<TITLE>LAKES MAY ACCOUNT FOR EOCENE WARMTH</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<IMG SRC= "../icons/gpclogo.gif" ALT="Greenpeace Logo"><BR>
<H3><B>LAKES MAY ACCOUNT FOR EOCENE WARMTH </B></H3><P>

Geological evidence suggests that temperatures were considerably
warmer during the early Eocene (50-55 million years ago) than the
present, and that even inland continental winter temperatures
were above freezing. However, the general circulation models
(GCMs) currently used for climate simulations suggest  much lower
temperatures.  Researchers suggest the discrepancy may be
explained by the existence of large lakes during the Eocene,
which may have had a climate-moderating effect as the sea does
today. This hypothesis brings the geological evidence and
modelling into much closer agreement. (P. Valdes, "Damping
seasonal variations", Nature, v. 372,  p.221, 17 November
1994).<P>

GREENPEACE Climate Impacts Database<P>

