<! record 0037 of 844>
<TITLE>THE INDIAN PLAGUE : IS THERE A LINK TO CLIMATE
CHANGE?</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<IMG SRC= "../icons/gpclogo.gif" ALT="Greenpeace Logo"><BR>
<H3><B>THE INDIAN PLAGUE : IS THERE A LINK TO CLIMATE CHANGE?
</B></H3><P>

Paul Epstein from the Harvard School of Public Health raises
concerns about the weather conditions prevalent prior to the
September epidemic of pneumonic plague in India. He points out
that the particularly hot and wet season led to a plague of
fleas, while the severe flooding associated with the prolonged
monsoon left large numbers of dead animals and rats lying around
the city.<P>

Epstein suggests that the pattern of  disease emergence and
resurgence worldwide, of which the Indian plague is part, may be
linked to climate change. For example, mosquitoes which transmit
yellow and dengue fever have formerly  been restricted to less
than 1000 metres above sea level by temperature but are now
reported at 2,200 metres in India and Colombia.  Epstein
considers that climate change may be releasing pests and
pathogens from ecological controls and predation. ("Climate
change played a role in India's plague", letter to New York
Times, 13 November 1994).<P>

GREENPEACE Climate Impacts Database<P>

