<! record 0038 of 844>
<TITLE>TORRENTIAL RAINS AND FLOODS FOR SOUTHERN EUROPE</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<IMG SRC= "../icons/gpclogo.gif" ALT="Greenpeace Logo"><BR>
<H3><B>TORRENTIAL RAINS AND FLOODS FOR SOUTHERN EUROPE
</B></H3><P>

The worst flooding in 80 years hits the northwestern Italian
provinces of  Piedmont, Liguria and Lombardy,  killing 64 people,

leaving 10,000 homeless and causing an estimated $4 billion in
damages. Over 250mm of rain fell in 60 hours; Turin recorded
133mm on 5 November alone. Average November rainfall for the area
is 72.4mm.   With damage reported in 240 towns and cities and
more than 400,000 hectares of cropland flooded, economic losses 
are expected to exceed US$6 billion.  The regional council of
Piedmont describe the flood as "the worst calamity that has
befallen Piedmont in the memory of  man". In Lombardy, the Po
River reaches six metres above the norm.  The government
acknowledges that poor forest management in mountain areas and
development in areas prone to flooding is partially to blame for
the extent of the disaster.  There is also some evidence that
flooding has increased by 50 percent over the past 20 years,
while average rainfall is actually dropping. ("Severe floods hit
northern Italy and kill at least 100 people", La Stampa, 7
November 1994; "Italy counts the costs of disastrous storms",
Reuter,  8 November 1994;   The Irish Times, 10 November 1994;
"Italy admits weak link in flood warning", UPI, 11 November 1994;

Lloyd's List Reuter Textline, 14 November 1994).<P>

