<! record 0039 of 844>
<TITLE>MORE OR LESS FISH IN A GLOBAL WARMING WORLD?</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<IMG SRC= "../icons/gpclogo.gif" ALT="Greenpeace Logo"><BR>
<H3><B>MORE OR LESS FISH IN A GLOBAL WARMING WORLD? </B></H3><P>

New Zealand  researchers from the Ministry of Agriculture and
Fisheries have correlated 27 years  of sea temperature data
against the age structures of fish populations. Sea temperatures
in the five months after spawning will determine the number of
fish maturing to commercial size. They found a clear relationship
between increased temperatures and increased numbers of snapper
and southern blue whiting, important commercial fish species for
New Zealand.  However, for hoki, another important commercial
species, they found a decline in fish numbers with increasing
temperature,  while tuna stocks appear to be pushed south into
cooler water. ("Fish with a flourishing future in the global
greenhouse", New Scientist, p.16, 5 November 1994).<P>

