<! record 0040 of 844>
<TITLE>DOES OCEAN 'CONVEYER  BELT' INFLUENCE CLIMATE?</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<IMG SRC= "../icons/gpclogo.gif" ALT="Greenpeace Logo"><BR>
<H3><B>DOES OCEAN 'CONVEYER  BELT' INFLUENCE CLIMATE?
</B></H3><P>

Some climate models have suggested that past climate fluctuations
in the North Atlantic have resulted from the abrupt "switching on
or off" of the Atlantic Ocean circulation "conveyer belt",  which
transports warm water north and cold "deep water" south. It was
further suggested that the conveyer system switched off  in
response to the infusion of large quantities of fresh water from
melting ice caps.  However, recent geochemical data indicate
that,  rather than switching off, the system moves between a warm
deep mode, a cold shallow mode, and a stable intermediate mode.
In this new model, the infusion of fresh water is still the
trigger.<P>

In the present warm mode, a deep layer of North Atlantic Deep
Water (NADW) overlies a shallow layer of Antarctic bottom water,
with an overall warming effect.  In the cold mode,  such as
possibly occurred at the last glacial maximum, a shallower NADW
is underlain by much thicker Antarctic bottom water.  The models
suggest that only a  relatively small change in heat flux is
required to trigger a switch between the various modes. According
to Stefan Rahmstorf from the University of Kiel, global warming
could have the effect of switching off the transport of warm
water to the North Atlantic, resulting in "sharp cooling" across
the North Atlantic and Europe.  (E. Boyle and A.Weaver,
"Conveying past climates", Nature, v. 372, p. 41-42, 3 November
1994;  S. Rahmstorf, "Rapid climate transitions in a coupled
ocean-atmosphere model", Nature, v. 372, p. 82-85,3 November
1994; D. Paillard and L. Labeyrie, "Role of the thermohaline
circulation in the abrupt warming after Heinrich events", 
Nature, v. 372,  p. 162-164, 10 November 1994;  "Will global
warming plunge Europe into an ice age?", New Scientist, p.20-21,
19 November 1994;  W.S. Broecker,  "Massive iceberg discharges as
triggers for global climate change",  Nature,  v. 372, p.421-
424, 1 December 1994).<P>

GREENPEACE Climate Impacts Database<P>

<HR>
Keywords:\antarctic\ocean_circulation\glaciers\

</BODY>
</HTML>

