<HEAD>
<! record 0050 of 844>
<TITLE>OBSERVED CLIMATE CHANGE IN THE PACIFIC CONSISTENT WITH
GLOBAL WARMING</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<IMG SRC= "../icons/gpclogo.gif" ALT="Greenpeace Logo"><BR>
<H3><B>OBSERVED CLIMATE CHANGE IN THE PACIFIC CONSISTENT WITH
GLOBAL WARMING </B></H3> <P>

Jim Salinger, one of the western Pacific's foremost
climatologists, presenting at the Greenhouse 94 conference
reports on the most comprehensive assessment of recent climate
change throughout the region.  Over Australia temperatures have
increased by 0.4-0.8 oC since 1951, and increased by 0.1-1.0 oC
over eastern Australia and 1.2 oC over southwest Australia since
1910. The diurnal range has decreased over northeast interior of
the continent, probably linked to increased cloudiness in the
region. Rainfall over Australia has generally increased, mainly
due to increases in tropical and summer precipitation.  Winter
rainfall has decreased over southwest Australia. Temperatures
have increased by about 0.7 oC over the southwest Pacific and New
Zealand since 1900 and 1860 respectively.  Sea surface
temperature increases are consistent with this.  Rainfall has
increased over the central Pacific since the 1940's and decreased
over the subtropics in the same period.  El Nino - Southern
Oscillation (ENSO) warm events (El Nino events) have been more
frequent than cold events (La Nina) since the late 1970's and
with only one intervening cold event (La Nina). ENSO impacts (ie
drought in Australasia) were strong early this century, weak from
1920-1940, and strong since then.  Ocean temperatures between
1000-3000 metres have increased in both the Tasman Sea and the
Indian Ocean.  Sea level rise has occurred at about 2mm/year.
Aerosols are unlikely to have a direct impact in oceania but may
indirectly have an impact in the future as increased emissions in
south and southeast Asia affect the monsoons.  Changes in ENSO
have had the a visible impact on rainfall in the region, however
increases in temperature are consistent with a global trend and
recent climate change is "not inconsistent" with global warming.
(M.J. Salinger, R. Allan, N. Bindoff, J. Hannah, B. Lavery, Z.
Lin, J. Lindesay, N. Nicholls, N. Plummer & S. Torok, "Observed
Variability and Change in Climate and Sea-Level in oceania",
presented at Greenhouse 94, An Australian-New Zealand Conference
on Climate Change, 10-14 October, CSIRO/NIWA, 1994. See also M.J.
Salinger, R.E. Basher, B.B. Fitzharris, J.E. Hay, P.D. Jones,
J.P. MacVeigh & I. Schmidely-Leleu, "Climate Trends in the
Southwest Pacific", International Journal of Climatology, in
press; N. Nicholls & B. Lavery, "Australian rainfall trends
during the twentieth century", "International Journal of
Climatology", v.12, p.153-163; R.J. Allan, "Historical
Fluctuations in ENSO and Teleconnection Structure 1879: Near-
Global Patterns", Quaternary Australasian, v.11, p.17-27, April
1993). <P>

Note: At the conference, leading climate experts also presented
projections for life in oceania in a global warming world. By the
year 2030, at present emission rates, atmospheric carbon dioxide
levels will have doubled, with an attendant rise in temperature
of between 1.5-4.5ƒC, and more frequent extreme weather events
such as droughts, floods, and intense storms.  Southern and
eastern Australia are likely to see a "dramatic" increase in the
incidence of intense storms with accompanying heavy rain and
severe floods, snow cover in the Australian Alps will decline,
crops such as winter cereals will be disadvantaged, and water
management will be complicated by the heavy runoffs associated
with the new rainfall regime. While insects and micro-organisms
(including diseases such as malaria and dengue fever) are likely
to be favoured by the new climate, many native animals will be
faced with shrinking habitat. ("Life in a hot new world", Sydney
Morning Herald, 8 October 1994; P. Whetton, B. Mullan & A.B.
Pittock, "Climate Change Scenarios for Australia and New
Zealand," presented at Greenhouse 94, An Australian-New Zealand
Conference on Climate Change, 10-14 October, CSIRO/NIWA, 1994; J.
Minnery & D. Smith, "Climate Change, Flooding and Urban
Infrastructure", presented at Greenhouse 94, An Australian-New
Zealand Conference on Climate Change, 10-14 October,<P>

GREENPEACE Climate Impacts Database<P>

