<TITLE>CLIMATE CHANGE WILL CHANGE GRASSLANDS</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<IMG SRC= "../icons/gpclogo.gif" ALT="Greenpeace Logo"><BR>
<H3><B>CLIMATE CHANGE WILL CHANGE GRASSLANDS </B></H3><P>

Many parameters of grassland plant distribution and production
may be affected by climate change.  Global assessment by
modelling indicates that some areas such as humid temperate
grasslands will have higher production, while more arid temperate
grasslands in North America and Eurasia may be substantially
reduced.  All grassland types are likely to lose soil carbon,
most particularly the extreme continental grasslands. It is
further suggested that increased atmospheric CO2 may directly
impact photosynthesis and water use in wetlands, as well as
lowering nitrogen content of forage, and making it less
digestible. (W.J. Parton and  D.J. Ojima, "Environmental change
in grasslands: assessment using models", Climatic Change, v.28,
p.111-141, October 1994).<P>

GREENPEACE Climate Impacts Database<P>

