<! record 0052 of 844>
<TITLE>FOSSIL FUELS A RISKY INVESTMENT</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<IMG SRC= "../icons/gpclogo.gif" ALT="Greenpeace Logo"><BR>
<H3><B>FOSSIL FUELS A RISKY INVESTMENT </B></H3><P>

A former chief investment manager at the Chase Manhattan Bank in
London, Mark Mansley, has suggests that anthropogenic climate
change creates many risks for long term investment in the fossil
fuel industry.  The consensus of the Intergovernmental Panel on
Climate Change (IPCC) is that carbon dioxide emissions from oil,
coal and gas are major contributors to the global warming which
is now in progress, and that there will be potentially serious
effects on human activities.<P>

There are several possible scenarios regarding the intensity of
climate change and its effects; and several scenarios regarding
policy measures to reduce emissions of greenhouse agents.
Currently, it seems that measures actually being taken would at
best result in stabilisation of atmospheric CO2 at high levels. 
However, if "high impact" climate scenarios are realised, carbon
taxes and drastic reductions in carbon use may be necessary.  The
effects of these on the carbon fuel industry may be to reduce
demand and to decrease the prospect of long term energy price
rises. In short, global warming poses major long term financial
risks to the carbon fuel industry which financial markets have
not yet addressed, particularly to oil explorers, who are heavily
dependent on future oil prices.<P>

Mansley suggests that long term investment in the fossil fuel
industry is unwise until the risks of doing so have been
discounted. The alternative energy industry, on the other hand,
offers greater prospects for growth,  as well as a positive means
of offsetting the effects of climate change due to fossil fuel
use. (Mark Mansley, "Long term financial risks to the carbon fuel
industry from climate change", The Delphi Group, October
1994).<P>

GREENPEACE Climate Impacts Database<P>

