<! record 0053 of 844>
<TITLE>ARCTIC POLLUTION: DOES IT HEAT OR COOL?</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<IMG SRC= "../icons/gpclogo.gif" ALT="Greenpeace Logo"><BR>
<H3><B>ARCTIC POLLUTION: DOES IT HEAT OR COOL? </B></H3><P>

At a recent meeting organised by the Royal Society in the UK,
there was disagreement as to whether the Arctic is warming or
cooling. Industrial haze from northern continents has become a
feature of the Arctic in recent decades, but its overall effect
on heat balance is not yet clear. According to one recent study,
sunlight has decreased 15 percent over the past 40 years, with
the haze acting as a shade, and the net effect is of cooling. 
Another study reported that there has been an increase of 0.75ƒC
in some parts of the Arctic since the 1950's, and that the haze
could increase the greenhouse effect by trapping heat. ("Does
polluted air keep the Arctic cool?", New Scientist, p.19, 29
October 1994).<P>

GREENPEACE Climate Impacts Database<P>

