<! record 0054 of 844>
<TITLE>BLAME THE EL NINO FOR THE LACK OF SALMON?</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<IMG SRC= "../icons/gpclogo.gif" ALT="Greenpeace Logo"><BR>
<H3><B>BLAME THE EL NINO FOR THE LACK OF SALMON? </B></H3><P>

A third of Canada's west coast sockeye salmon have failed to
arrive at their annual breeding ground in British Columbia. The
fish are counted by acoustic beams, first at the mouth of the
Fraser River, where 10 million were counted, and then again
upstream at the breeding grounds, where, after allowing for
numbers fished by Local communities, there were 3  million fewer
than expected. While uncertainties in the methods used for
counting the fish might be to blame, water temperatures in the
river have been maintained at a degree or so above normal for the
past three years, as a consequence of the El Nino event.  This
may mean that salmon migrating up the river use energy at a
faster rate, and thus die before they reach the breeding areas.
("Missing salmon spawn political battle", New Scientist, p.11, 
29 October 1994).<P>

GREENPEACE Climate Impacts Database<P>

