<TITLE>HOT SUMMER FOR CANADA</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<IMG SRC= "../icons/gpclogo.gif" ALT="Greenpeace Logo"><BR>
<H3><B>HOT SUMMER FOR CANADA </B></H3><P>

Canada records its second hottest summer on record (after 1989),
and third worst year for forest fires. Over 5 million hectares
burn, mainly in the western Arctic. Summer 1994 is also one of
the wettest since rainfall records began in 1948. (Environment
Canada, Climatic Perspectives, v.16; Canadian Forest Service
Records, October 1994).<P>

Note: A provisional analysis of rainfall trends over Canada shows
a generally increasing trend from 1895-1992 with regional
variations. Rainfall seems to have increased over large areas of
southern Canada, including Atlantic Canada, the Great Lakes
Basin/St Lawrence Lowlands, the south British Columbia Mountains
and the Pacific Coast. Decreasing trends occurred across Prairies
region of central western Canada and increasing trends over the
boreal forest regions of eastern and western Canada are evident
from the 1930s, however drops to below average rainfall occurred
in both these regions in the 1980's and the 1970's respectively.
(B.F. Findlay, D.W. Gullett, L. Malone, J. Reycraft, W.R.
Skinner, L. Vincent & R. Whitewood, "Canadian national and
regional standardized annual precipitation departures",
p.800-828, in T.A. Boden, D.P. Kaiser, R.J. Sepanski & F.W. Stoss
(eds), Trends '93: A Compendium of Data on Global Change,
ORNL/CDIAC-65, Carbon Dioxide Information Analysis Center, Oak
Ridge National Laboratory, Oak Ridge, Tenn., USA).<P>

