<! record 0059 of 844>
<TITLE>CHANGES IN HIGH ARCTIC POND BIOLOGY</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<IMG SRC= "../icons/gpclogo.gif" ALT="Greenpeace Logo"><BR>
<H3><B>CHANGES IN HIGH ARCTIC POND BIOLOGY </B></H3><P>

Researchers have examined ancient deposits from pristine ponds on
Ellesmere Island, in the Canadian Arctic, and found that
assemblages of diatoms have changed markedly since the beginning
of the 19th century.  In contrast, there were few changes in pond
life during periods of up to 8,000 years before the present. 
Several possible causes for these changes have been proposed,
including airborne pollution and increased UV radiation, but the
most likely cause is climatic warming . This study suggests that
warming was occurring a century before other studies in the
Arctic and elsewhere have previously indicated.  The authors also
suggest that attempts to catalogue pristine Arctic ecosystems may
already be too late. (M.S.V. Douglas, J.P. Smol and W. Blake,
"Marked post-18th century environmental change in high-Arctic
ecosystems", Science, v.266, p.416-419, 21 October 1994).<P>

GREENPEACE Climate Impacts Database<P>

