<! record 0061 of 844>
<TITLE>INDIAN OCEAN COLD SPOT AGGRAVATES EL NINO EFFECT</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<IMG SRC= "../icons/gpclogo.gif" ALT="Greenpeace Logo"><BR>
<H3><B>INDIAN OCEAN COLD SPOT AGGRAVATES EL NINO EFFECT
</B></H3><P>

Oceanographers from Australia's Commonwealth Scientific and
Industrial Research Organisation (CSIRO) have identified a "cold
spot" in the Indian Ocean which appears to be exacerbating  the
severity of the Australian drought. In La Nina (non-El Nino)
years, warm water in this oceanic region stimulates the formation
of moist clouds which then drift over the continent and fall as
rain.  El Nino prevents easterly winds from pushing warm water
into a "pool" in the Indian ocean;  instead upwelling cold deep
water creates a high-pressure cell which prevents cloud
formation. Sea temperatures over this area are currently 1-2ƒC
cooler than in 1985, the last strong La Nina year. ("Big dry made
worse by a spot in the ocean", Sydney Morning Herald, 12 October
1994).<P>

GREENPEACE Climate Impacts Database<P>

