<! record 0063 of 844>
<TITLE>FLOODS, DROUGHTS AND STORMS FOR AUSTRALIA IN A WARMING 
WORLD?</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<IMG SRC= "../icons/gpclogo.gif" ALT="Greenpeace Logo"><BR>
<H3><B>FLOODS, DROUGHTS AND STORMS FOR AUSTRALIA IN A WARMING 
WORLD? </B></H3><P>

In the lead-up to a major regional greenhouse conference a team
of Australian climate scientists suggest that  by the year 2030,
at present emission rates, atmospheric carbon dioxide levels will
have doubled, with an attendant rise in temperature of between
1.5-4.5ƒC. Extreme  weather events such as droughts, floods, and
intense storms, will be more common.  Southeast  Australia may
expect a dramatic increase in the number of intense storms with
accompanying heavy rain and severe floods, snow cover in the
Australian Alps will decline, and crops such as winter cereals
will be disadvantaged. Water management will be complicated by
the heavy runoffs associated with the new rainfall regime. While
insects and micro-organisms (including diseases such as malaria
and dengue fever) are likely to be favoured by the new climate,
many native animals will be faced with shrinking habitat. ("Life
in a hot new world", Sydney Morning Herald, 8 October 1994).<P>

The scientists suggest that average temperatures rose between
0.4-0.8 oC between 1951 and 1993 in the southwest Pacific. These
findings exceed the expectations of the Intergovernmental Panel
on Climate Change (IPCC), which suggested that temperatures have
risen 0.3-0.6 oC during the past century. ("We're getting warmer,
study reveals", Sydney Morning Herald, 11 October 1994).<P>

GREENPEACE Climate Impacts Database<P>

