<TITLE>WINDSTORM WHIPS THROUGH SYDNEY</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<IMG SRC= "../icons/gpclogo.gif" ALT="Greenpeace Logo"><BR>
<H3><B>WINDSTORM WHIPS THROUGH SYDNEY </B></H3><P>

Gusts up to 125 kph sweep through Sydney injuring several people,
initiating and fanning bushfires, and causing property damage
over a wide area. ("Three hurt as fierce winds cut a swathe of
damage", Sydney Morning Herald, 8 October 1994).<P>

Note: Sydney strongest storm hit in  January 1991, when  winds
gusting up to 180 kph and cricket ball-sized hailstones caused
Aus$185 million in insured losses throughout the city.
Meteorologist L. Eyre asks whether the extra energy formed by
global warming might be dissipated by such huge thunderstorms:
"Are atmospheric energies increasingly vigorous in extra-tropical
latitudes, as many airline pilots suggest?  More careful
monitoring is evidently needed before hard conclusions can be
drawn. But, qualitatively and subjectively, we may tentatively
postulate that more severe weather in on the way". (L.A. Eyre,
"How severe can a thunderstorm be? An investigation into two
violent electrical storms in Australia", Weather, v.47,
p.374-383, 1992).<P>

GREENPEACE Climate Impacts Database<P>

