<! record 0065 of 844>
<TITLE>CARBON CYCLING IN THE PACIFIC</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<IMG SRC= "../icons/gpclogo.gif" ALT="Greenpeace Logo"><BR>
<H3><B>CARBON CYCLING IN THE PACIFIC </B></H3><P>

Upwelling of carbon-dioxide rich water in the central and eastern
equatorial Pacific ocean is regarded as the largest global ocean
source of carbon to the atmosphere. It is also tied to biological
production, as nutrients are brought to the surface by upwelling.

This oceanic region is also regarded as a major site of carbon
export to the deep sea, as detritus from biological production
sinks. James W. Murray from the University of Washington and
colleagues have conducted a study which concludes that winds and
waves are major influences on biological and chemical variability
in the equatorial Pacific, with El Nino the most significant
source of variability between years. (J.W.Murray, R.T. Barber,
M.R. Roman, M.P. Bacon and R.A. Feely, "Physical and biological
controls on carbon cycling in the equatorial Pacific", Science,
v.266, p.58-65, 7 October 1994).<P>

GREENPEACE Climate Impacts Database<P>

