<! record 0067 of 844>
<TITLE>DOUBT ABOUT CO2 FERTILISATION</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<IMG SRC= "../icons/gpclogo.gif" ALT="Greenpeace Logo"><BR>
<H3><B>DOUBT ABOUT CO2 FERTILISATION </B></H3><P>

There has been debate about whether enhanced levels of
atmospheric carbon dioxide would stimulate photosynthesis by
plants, creating a form of negative feedback: the more CO2
available, the more plants grow and  absorb CO2, and so on.
Walter Oechel of  San Diego State University and colleagues
recently tested CO2 fertilization effect with undisturbed tussock
tundra in Alaska. When CO2 levels were artificially raised,
increased CO2- fixation was dependent on several other factors,
notably temperature and water-logging.  The work supported the
conclusions of earlier studies "which showed little or no CO2
fertilization effect on plants after some brief period of
adjustment". Oechel et al concluded that "these results sound
cautionary notes for those who feel that elevated atmospheric CO2
will necessarily lead to net ecosystem sequestration". (W.C.
Oechel et al., "Transient nature of CO2 fertilization in Arctic
tundra", Nature, v.371, p.500-503, 6 October 1994).<P>

GREENPEACE Climate Impacts Database<P>

