<! record 0069 of 844>
<TITLE>AUSTRALIAN DROUGHT WORSENS</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<IMG SRC= "../icons/gpclogo.gif" ALT="Greenpeace Logo"><BR>
<H3><B>AUSTRALIAN DROUGHT WORSENS </B></H3><P>

The drought is now regarded as the worst in 100 years, with
losses to the Queensland State economy of nearly A$2 billion. The
prolonged drought is not expected to lift until March next year.
More than 90 percent of the state of NSW is now drought-declared.
Cotton growers in northern New South Wales will be unable to sow
their 1994-95 crop if rains are not received soon. Stock routes,
regarded as the traditional 'last resort' for drought-affected
cattle herds, are increasingly devoid of feed. The lack of feed
is forcing graziers to sell their herds,  which  will take at
least 5 years to replace upon the breaking of the drought.  Many
towns are running out of water and Local businesses are closing.
Food prices are starting to rise.  ("Crunch time nears for
cotton", Australian Financial Review, 4 October 1994; "State
reels under worst drought for 100 years", Australian Financial
Review, 6 October 1994; "Drought-hit cattle farmers sell their
future as stock routes close", Sydney Morning Herald, 6 October
1994; "Big dry hits food prices", Sydney Morning Herald, 7
October 1994, "Souris launches cloud seeding plan to fight dry",
Sydney Morning Herald, 8 October 1994; "The deadly drought: at
last we learn the truth", Sydney Morning Herald, 14 October
1994).<P>

The drought may force Australia, usually the world's fourth
largest wheat exported,  to import grain. Australia was last
forced to import grain in the severe drought of  1982, which
broke before the grain was unloaded. The cattle feedlot industry
believe that grain imports are essential for it to survive this
period, and the Federal Government has approved the import of
130,000 tonnes of sorghum and maize, which will cost A$25
million. (Sydney Telegraph Mirror, 6 October 1994; "Grain imports
vital: lot feeders," Sydney Morning Herald, 8 October 1994;
"Drought forces $25m grain imports," The Australian, 11 October
1994).<P>

Note: The Australian Bureau of Meteorology reports that rainfall
was below average for September in many parts of the country, and
predicts that it will remain below average during the October-
December period in the north and east. The monsoon season in the
tropical north is likely to be delayed. (Seasonal Climate
Outlook, Bureau of Meteorology, 21 October 1994).  And forecasts
compiled by the US National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration (NOAA) suggest that the current El Nino  will
continue to intensify over the next six months.  Tim Barnett of
the Scripps Institute of Oceanography predicts that El Nino could

be "particularly strong" in 1995, with temperatures in some areas
up to 2 oC higher than normal. Prior to 1991, El Nino events
occurred every two to ten years and lasted only a few months.
("ocean convulsions", New Scientist, 22 October 1994).  The
Columbian Institute of Environmental Studies (IDEAM)has also
suggested that the El Nino is again intensifying. According to
IDEAM, sea temperatures in the equatorial region of the Pacific
ocean are warming, and are currently warmer than normal at 30 oC.

The Southern oscillation index used to follow up the 'El Nino'
has been strongly negative in recent months, indicating the
existence of the phenomenon.  IDEAM expect the event to be in
full force throughout October and November, and may get stronger
into 1995.  The 1991 El Nino was blamed for 1500 deaths and
damage of $US8 billion. ("El Nino appears again in Latin
America", Xinhua News Agency, 1 October 1994; "Warm Water in the
tropics: A New weather threat?", AP Worldstream, 19 October 1994;
Reuter World Service, 19 oct 1994).<P>

GREENPEACE Climate Impacts Database<P>

