<! record 0071 of 844>
<TITLE>ICE CORE RESEARCH RAISES MANY QUESTIONS</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<IMG SRC= "../icons/gpclogo.gif" ALT="Greenpeace Logo"><BR>
<H3><B>ICE CORE RESEARCH RAISES MANY QUESTIONS </B></H3><P>

The recent Greenland Ice Core Project (GRIP) provided indications
that the last glacial period was interspersed with warm intervals
and rapid changes between warmer and cooler periods.
Palaeoclimatologists have since looked for corroboration of these
results.  Two recent studies of  sediment cores from the North
Atlantic, one looking at deep ocean chemistry and the other at
the remains of surface-dwelling phytoplankton, have provided some
support for the GRIP argument. Both studies suggest considerable
variability in water circulation during the last interglacial,
and general agreement with climate profiles from the Greenland
ice cores, except in the Eemian interglacial period. The sediment
studies provide no evidence of the rapid temperature fluctuations
indicated in the ice core study. However, French researchers
believe their studies of pollen in lakes do support the GRIP
hypothesis of a fluctuating climate during the Eemian. (R. Zahn,
"Core correlations", Nature, v.371, p.289-290, 22 September 1994;
L. Keigwin, W.B. Curry, S.J. Lehman and S. Johnsen, "The role of
the deep ocean in North Atlantic climate change between 70 and
130 kyr ago", Nature, v.371, p.323-326, 22 September 1994; J.F.
McManus, G.C. Bond, W.S. Broecker, L. Labeyrie and S. Higgins,
"High-resolution climate records from the North Atlantic during
the last interglacial", Nature, v.371, p.326-329, 22 September
1994).<P>

GREENPEACE Climate Impacts Database<P>

