<HEAD>
 <! record 0072 of 844>
<TITLE>MORE FREQUENT EL NINO EVENTS HAVE CONTRIBUTED TO RECENT
GLOBAL WARMING</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<IMG SRC= "../icons/gpclogo.gif" ALT="Greenpeace Logo"><BR>
<H3><B>MORE FREQUENT EL NINO EVENTS HAVE CONTRIBUTED TO RECENT
GLOBAL WARMING </B></H3> <P>

Researchers suggest that recent global temperature changes have
been greatly influenced by the increased sea surface temperatures
(SST) in the tropical Pacific.  These high SST are associated
with the El Nino-Southern Oscillation (ENSO). El Nino and La
Nina, which form the two extremes of ENSO, generally see-saw
between each other, however, since the late 1970s, there have
been three El Nino events and only one La Nina. It is not unknown
if this bias, or "climate shift" towards warm events is the
result of natural variability or global warming, but if it the
more frequent El Nino events is due to global warming than it may
indicate that as the world continues to warm these events may
become more frequent.  Other research by Nicholas Graham at
Scripps, also suggests that the "tropical heat machine" has speed
up and that global warming may be responsible.  The Pacific
warming, he suggests, has increased evaporation, which in turn
enhances humidity and boosts the release of latent heat high in
the atmosphere (as water vapour condenses into rain). Since 1976,
in both the instrumental records and his model, Graham finds that
the tropical heat machine has sped up. He suspects the enhanced
greenhouse effect might be the culprit because in models that
include increased greenhouse gas concentrations tropical heat
engine accelerates. In another study reported in Geophysical
Research Letters (v.21, p.2295-8, 1994), future El Nino events
were modelled using current levels of atmospheric CO2, and
increased levels of CO2. They found that the magnitude of El Nino
events at current levels exceeded those at increased levels of
the gas.(A. Kumar, A. Leetmaa & M. Ji, "Simulations of
Atmospheric Variability Induced by Sea Surface Temperatures and
Implications for Global Warming," Science, v.266, p.632-634, 28
October 1994; R.A. Kerr, "Did the Tropical Pacific Drive the
World's Warming", Science, v.266, p.544-545, 28 October 1994; "El
Nino may explain much of recent warming trend"; "Warming may not
increase strength of El Nino events", Global Environmental Change
Report, v.VI(21), 11 November 1994).<P>

Note: In 1989, German researchers also reported an
intensification of the tropical hydrological cycle and changes in
tropical circulation. In the tropics, average lower atmospheric
temperatures have increased markedly since 1965 and the water
vapour content of the middle troposphere has increased by 20-30
percent.  The authors report that the increase in the tropical
hydrological cycle is evident in the increases in sea surface
temperatures, evaporation, atmospheric moisture and mean wind
speeds. The authors suggested that intensification of the
tropical hydrological cycle via positive feedback processes (such
as increases in sea surface temperatures and evaporation) will
enhance low latitude warming, lead to acceleration of tropical
circulations and, possibly, to more frequent and/or intense warm
ENSO events. (H. Flohn & A. Kapala, "Changes of tropical sea-air
interaction processes over a 30-year period", Nature, v.338,
p.244-246, 16 March 1989).<P>

GREENPEACE Climate Impacts Database<P>

