<TITLE>AUSTRALIAN DROUGHT BILL NOW A$2 BILLION</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<IMG SRC= "../icons/gpclogo.gif" ALT="Greenpeace Logo"><BR>
<H3><B>AUSTRALIAN DROUGHT BILL NOW A$2 BILLION </B></H3><P>

The National Farmers Federation believes that the current drought
will cost the Australian economy Aus$2 billion, threatening a
recovery in agriculture after the recent recession.  It is
estimated that the drought will cut economic growth by one per
cent. Farm production could fall by 12-15 percent in 1994-95,
with potential production losses of 40-50 percent in wheat, 15-25
percent in cotton, and 5-10 percent in wool.  The drought is
spreading south, and without good rain before Christmas, summer
crops will be threatened and the economic situation will worsen.
("Drought costs farmers $2 bn in lost production", The
Australian, 28 September 1994; "Drought may cost $2 billion",
Sydney Morning Herald, 28 September 1994).<P>

