<! record 0078 of 844>
<TITLE>FLOODING IN AFRICA</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<IMG SRC= "../icons/gpclogo.gif" ALT="Greenpeace Logo"><BR>
<H3><B>FLOODING IN AFRICA </B></H3><P>

Record seasonal rains in Niger's deserts causes flooding which
kills 42, displaces 127,000 people and leaving 83,000 homeless,
and destroys 30,000 hectares of crops and 7,400 livestock. In
some areas the average annual rainfall (350mm) falls in a single
day. Heavy flooding in southern Nigeria causes deaths and
widespread destruction of property. (BBC Summary of World
Broadcasts, 25 September 1994, 27 September 1994; Lloyd's
Information Casualty Report, 26 September 1994, 27 September
1994).<P>

Note: A study of daily rainfall amounts from 1919 to 1985 in
Nigeria indicates that floods are becoming less frequent over
much of the country and droughts are becoming more common in the
middle and north of the country. Downward trends in light and
heavy rainfall have been observed throughout the country and have
been most evident in recent decades. No period on the record
shows a comparable dry period in magnitude or scope to that which
occurred from 1966 to 1985. (O.J. Olaniran, "Evidence of Climatic
Change in Nigeria Based on Annual Series of Rainfall of Different
Daily Amounts, 1919-1985", Climatic Change, v.19, p.319-341,
1991).<P>

GREENPEACE Climate Impacts Database<P>

<HR>
