<TITLE>WETLANDS DRY IN DROUGHT</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<IMG SRC= "../icons/gpclogo.gif" ALT="Greenpeace Logo"><BR>
<H3><B>WETLANDS DRY IN DROUGHT </B></H3><P>

The current Australian drought is affecting the viability of the
Macquarie Marshes, in western New South Wales, Australia.  These
wetlands support bird and other wildlife and supply water to
graziers in surrounding areas.  Researchers fear that the
unprecedented draining of the Marshes, resulting from the 
drought, in combination with diversion of upstream water for
cotton irrigation,  will threaten the ecological diversity of the
area. Areas under irrigation have increased from 17,500 hectares
in the late 1960s to well over 85,000 hectares in the 1990s.
("Thirsty farmers squeeze marshes", Sydney Morning Herald, 21
September 1994).<P>

GREENPEACE Climate Impacts Database<P>

