<TITLE>EARLY START TO AUSTRALIAN BUSHFIRE SEASON</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<IMG SRC= "../icons/gpclogo.gif" ALT="Greenpeace Logo"><BR>
<H3><B>EARLY START TO AUSTRALIAN BUSHFIRE SEASON </B></H3><P>

Hot, dry, windy conditions in eastern Australia fuel 200
bushfires in New South Wales and Queensland, bringing an early
start to the (summer) bushfire season. Severe drought has left
large tracts of forest vulnerable to burning, and many fires have
been deliberately lit.  New South Wales and Queensland suffered
serious fires in January 1994, when four died, 189 homes were
destroyed and 600,000 hectares of forest burnt.  The windstorms
cause significant property damage elsewhere, including in Sydney.
By the end of September 140 fires are still burning in New South
Wales, many of them in inaccessible areas. (Reuter, 20 September
1994; "Windstorm havoc", Sydney Telegraph Mirror, 20 September
1994; "No rest for firefighters as danger warning remains", The
Australian, 30 September 1994).<P>

