<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<IMG SRC= "../icons/gpclogo.gif" ALT="Greenpeace Logo"><BR>
<H3><B>TYPHOON AND FLOODS IN JAPAN </B></H3><P>

Heavy rain brings relief to drought-affected Japan, but causes
major flooding in Tokyo.  An intense tropical storm lies to the
southeast of Hokkaido, bringing strong winds and 245mm of rain to
the city of Nemuro. (Reuter, 19 September 1994; Japanese Economic
Newswire, 19 September 1994; Japan Economic Newswire, 23
September 1994).<P>

Note: Japan recorded its worst typhoon in thirty years in
September 1990. One year later an even stronger storm, Typhoon
Mireille, resulted in $2.21 in insured losses. In September 1993,
Typhoon Yancy, one of the strongest typhoons to hit Japan in
fifty years and of similar strength to Mireille, caused
widespread destruction from flooding and winds up to 212 kph.<P>

