<! record 0084 of 844>
<TITLE>HOW USEFUL ARE PAST CLIMATE MODELS?</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<IMG SRC= "../icons/gpclogo.gif" ALT="Greenpeace Logo"><BR>
<H3><B>HOW USEFUL ARE PAST CLIMATE MODELS? </B></H3><P>

A recent workshop of US and Russian researchers (Workshop on
Palaeocalibration of Climate Sensitivity) discussed the relevance
of reconstructing past climate change to predictions of future
climate change.  Past climates may be inferred from fossil
pollens, shells of marine organisms, ice core records and glacial
landforms. The climate of  the Last Glacial Maximum of 20,000
years ago, for example, has been reconstructed in this way.<P>

Reconstructions of ancient climate are also useful for estimating
the global climate sensitivity, or the ratio of global
temperature change to the change in radiative forcing. 
Palaeocalibration, as this method is known, assumes that this
ratio is linear since the mid-Cretaceous (about 100 million years
ago), and has enabled a projection predicting a warming of 2.3ƒC
with doubled levels of carbon dioxide. This is within the range
predicted by global climate models.<P>

GREENPEACE Climate Impacts Database<P>

<HR>
Keywords:\Russia\CO2\glaciers\

</BODY>
