<! record 0085 of 844>
<TITLE>IPCC REPEATS WARNINGS</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<IMG SRC= "../icons/gpclogo.gif" ALT="Greenpeace Logo"><BR>
<H3><B>IPCC REPEATS WARNINGS </B></H3><P>

The Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC)'s Working
Group 1 issues a special report which  repeats its earlier
warning that emissions of carbon dioxide must be reduced so as to
stabilise atmospheric greenhouse gas concentrations and avoid
'dangerous' climate change. The Working Group has the task of
assembling scientific information pertinent to the Climate Change
Convention.  Recent criticisms have suggested that the IPCC's
assessment of the problem ignored uncertainties such as the role
of sulfate aerosol particles in reversing warming. However, the
IPCC states that the effect of sulfates is "highly Localised" and
"cannot be seen as a simple offset to greenhouse gas forcing".<P>

While the Framework Convention on Climate Change states that
signatory nations should aim to reduce greenhouse emissions to
1990 levels by the year 2000, there have been disputes over the
exact wording. Some countries claim that they are not bound to
stabilise CO2 emissions at 1990 levels after 2000, while others
feel that the current commitment is not strong enough. Germany
recently proposed that industrialised countries cut emissions by
a specific proportion before a set date, but this proposal was
rejected in August at a meeting of the International Negotiating
Committee, a forum of signatory states to the Convention.
According to climate models, pre-industrial levels of carbon
dioxide were 280 parts per million by volume (p.p.m.v.), present
levels are 360 p.p.m.v., and stabilising levels at 750 p.p.m.v.
would require emission reductions to below 1990 levels. ("Climate
group rejects criticism of warnings", Nature, v.371, p.274, 22
September 1994).<P>

GREENPEACE Climate Impacts Database<P>

