<TITLE>WARMING INCREASES ANTARCTIC PLANT LIFE</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<IMG SRC= "../icons/gpclogo.gif" ALT="Greenpeace Logo"><BR>
<H3><B>WARMING INCREASES ANTARCTIC PLANT LIFE </B></H3><P>

Scientists from the British Antarctic Survey report that the
continent's only two indigenous flowering plants, hairgrass and
Antarctic pearlwort, are rapidly increasing as a result of global
warming, with hairgrass showing a 25-fold increase on Galindez
Island.  New species are also appearing as melting ice frees
long-trapped seeds. (Reuter, 18 September 1994; "Plants warm to
Antarctica", Sydney Telegraph-Mirror, 19 September 1994;
"Greening of the Antarctic Peninsula", Science, v.266, p.35, 7
October 1994).<P>

