<TITLE>SOUTH AMERICAN GRASSES STORE CARBON</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<IMG SRC= "../icons/gpclogo.gif" ALT="Greenpeace Logo"><BR>
<H3><B>SOUTH AMERICAN GRASSES STORE CARBON </B></H3><P>

Analysis of the global carbon dioxide balance has proposed a
"missing sink" of between 0.4-4.3 billion tonnes. Researchers in
Colombia have found that deep-rooted introduced pasture grasses
may store 100-507 million tonnes deep in the soil each year, thus
partially offsetting the effects of CO2 emissions. ("Carbon
storage by introduced deep-rooted grasses in the South American
savannahs", Nature, v.371, p. 236-238, 15 September 1994).<P>

