<TITLE>CLIMATE CHANGE AND CORAL REEFS</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<IMG SRC= "../icons/gpclogo.gif" ALT="Greenpeace Logo"><BR>
<H3><B>CLIMATE CHANGE AND CORAL REEFS </B></H3><P>

A report has recently been released on the implications of
climate change on coral reef ecosystems and those people who live
with them. Compiled by the UNEP-IOC-ASPEI-IUCN Global Task Team
on Coral Reefs, the report set out to provide an overview of the
global situation with regard to coral reefs and climate change,
and to identify case study sites.  Many of the world's coral
reefs are already severely stressed by human damage and over
exploitation, and while climate change per se is not likely to
eliminate coral reefs, the combination of existing stresses and
climate change threatens their short-term survival. The time
frame for assessment and mitigation of the problem is mere
decades, before these problems become too advanced.<P>

In terms of specific threats, rising sea levels are not likely to
threaten most reefs, and may even advantage some, but will have a
devastating effect on human occupation of many low-lying islands,
and probably on the nesting requirements of such animals as sea
turtles. Rising temperatures are not considered likely to have
immediate large-scale endangering on corals, but would enhance
coral bleaching and mortality, thus contributing to the general
stresses on them. Increased atmospheric CO2 levels may increase
seawater acidity, which is likely to benefit algal competitors to
corals by fertilising them.  Lastly, increased rainfall may
radically change the influx of nutrients, sediments and
contaminants into reef  areas, with unknown effects. Increasingly
intense and frequent tropical storms may significantly increase
storm damage to some reefs.<P>

The report then makes several recommendations. In brief, these
are:<P>

-  "prompt and aggressive management to mitigate human stresses",
as unstressed reefs will be better able to cope with a changing
climate;<P>

- assessment of vulnerability of specific reefs areas, combined
with Local and regional measures to reduce greenhouse gas
emissions;<P>

- prompt action to manage and conserve reef resources, undertaken
as part of an integrated coastal zone strategy including
surrounding marine and coastal environments;<P>

- declaration of some remote reefs as international marine
protected areas, in order to protect reef biodiversity and
preserve representative reefs, and to permit monitoring in reef
areas free from human disturbance, so that effects of climate
change can be more apparent;<P>

- education of individuals and societies to minimise over
exploitation of reefs, and to develop a long-term sustainable
view of them;<P>

- contingency plans for the displacement of societies from low-
lying islands.<P>

(C.R.Wilkinson and R.W. Buddmeier, "Global Climate Change and
Coral Reefs: Implications for People and Reefs." Report of the
UNEP-IOC-ASPEI-IUCN Global Task Team on the Implications of
Climate Change on Coral Reefs, 1994).<P>

Note: Increased sea surface temperatures may have a greater
impact than suggested here. The IPCC suggests that sea surface
temperatures may increase by as much as 3 oC by the end of the
next century and Dr Ove Hoegh-Guldberg, from the University of
Sydney, suggests that it is "extremely unlikely that the majority
of coral reef organisms will be able to evolve quickly enough to
keep pace with the predicted changes in sea temperature." 
Further, the increases in temperature are "likely" to exceed the
tolerable levels of keystone organisms such as reef-building
corals and entire reef systems may collapse (as has been reported
in the Eastern Pacific and Caribbean) after even small increases
in temperature. (O. Hoegh-Guldberg, Global Warming and Coral reef
Ecosystems: Ecological Consequences of Increased Tropical Sea
Temperatures, a report prepared for Greenpeace International,
October 1994).<P>

GREENPEACE Climate Impacts Database<P>

