<! record 0098 of 844>
<TITLE>AUSTRALIA'S DROUGHT MAY BE WORST ON RECORD</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<IMG SRC= "../icons/gpclogo.gif" ALT="Greenpeace Logo"><BR>
<H3><B>AUSTRALIA'S DROUGHT MAY BE WORST ON RECORD </B></H3><P>

Australia's Bureau of Meteorology forecasts that all Australia's
farming areas may be drought-effected by the end of 1994. The
Southern Oscillation Index, a key indicator of wet or dry
conditions, has declined since February to a low of -17. Sea-
surface temperature, another significant indicator, also points
to worsening conditions. The drought now officially covers almost
all of Queensland and New South Wales, as well as parts of all
the remaining states, and could continue until next autumn. The
Minister for Primary Industries, Senator Collins, says: "[the]
forecast simply confirms the previous worst case scenarios". The
Federal Government is bringing forward its review of emergency
drought aid.  Some areas have been hand-feeding their stock for
four years now. The cotton, wheat and grazing industries are
badly affected in northern NSW, with only 15 percent of the
normal winter cereal crop being planted, and in some areas no
crops planted at all. Estimates of the NSW wheat crop are falling
by 100,000 tonnes per week, with a predicted loss of Aus$1.5 bn,
raising the possibility of the fourth largest wheat exporter
having to import wheat. Prices of food, including bread, fruit,
meat and dairy products are predicted to rise by as much as 25
percent. The drought is driving large numbers of rabbits into the
outskirts of Sydney. ("Drought alarm: urgent aid plan", The
Australian, 2 September 1994; "No rain relief during spring",
Sydney Telegraph-Mirror, 2 September 1994; "The annual fodder
insurance that's fast running out of oats", Sydney Morning
Herald, 2 September 1994;  "North-west feels four years of hell",
Sydney Morning Herald, 7 September 1994; "Drought fight looks to
sky", Sydney Morning Herald, 8 September 1994;  "Lush lawns of
Sydney spark a plague of rabbits", Sydney Morning Herald, 10
September 1994; "Up to 25 percent rise in food prices expected
soon", Sydney Morning Herald, 14 September 1994; "Drought strips
$1.5 bn off wheat crop", The Australian, 14 September 1994;
"Economy to suffer from $2 bn drought", The Australian, 20
September 1994).<P>

GREENPEACE Climate Impacts Database<P>

