<! record 0099 of 844>
<TITLE>JAPAN'S LONG DRY SUMMER</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<IMG SRC= "../icons/gpclogo.gif" ALT="Greenpeace Logo"><BR>
<H3><B>JAPAN'S LONG DRY SUMMER </B></H3><P>

Japanese industry is now faced with importing water as a result
of prolonged drought.  3 million households are on daily water
rationing in  western Japan.  The drought is responsible for a
US$774 million damage bill to agriculture, and a number of
textile and petrochemical plants have had to shut down.  Tokyo
summer temperatures were 1.8 oC higher than average, while
rainfall was half the average. As water demand has lowered the
Lake Biwa reservoir, which supplies Osaka and Kyoto, the ruins of
a sixteenth-century castle has emerged.  The Asahi News Service
asks why the record-breaking drought has not prompted more
discussion of global warming as a possible cause.   A spokesman
for the Japan Climatic Data Centre says: "the possibility of
warming can be pointed out, but cannot be proved"; Emeritus
Professor Ryuzaburo Yamamoto of Kyoto University states: "I am
sure that warming is advancing". ("Living on Earth" World Media
Foundation, 30 August 1994; ("Living on Earth" World Media
Foundation, 30 August 1994;  Reuter, 1 September 1994; Asahi News
Service, 2 September 1994; Report from Japan Inc., 14 September
1994).<P>

