<! record 0102 of 844>
<TITLE>RECORD  INSURANCE LOSSES ON "NATURAL" DISASTERS LINKED TO
CLIMATE CHANGE</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<IMG SRC= "../icons/gpclogo.gif" ALT="Greenpeace Logo"><BR>
<H3><B>RECORD  INSURANCE LOSSES ON "NATURAL" DISASTERS LINKED TO
CLIMATE CHANGE </B></H3> <P>

A report in the journal Reinsurance points to the recent dramatic
increase in catastrophe losses linked with changing weather
patterns.  It says that given the scientific predictions of an
average global rise in temperature of 0.3 degrees Celsius per
decade, the world can expect more torrential rain, flash floods
and landslides, more thunderstorms, hailstorms, lightning and
tornadoes and longer, more intense and more frequent tropical
cyclones.  Since 1987, there have been 13 natural disasters
costing the insurance industry more than US$1 billion each, with
11 of them since 1990. The most disastrous and costly was
Hurricane Andrew with insured losses of up to US$20 billion.
Reinsurance says: "the evidence that emerging climate changes are
having an ever greater influence on the frequency and intensity
of natural disasters has become stronger",  and "unless
appropriate measures are implemented by insurers, the inevitably
increasing natural disasters will have devastating effects on
results".<P>

GREENPEACE Climate Impacts Database<P>

