<TITLE>WILDFIRES DEVASTATE WESTERN USA AND CANADA</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<IMG SRC= "../icons/gpclogo.gif" ALT="Greenpeace Logo"><BR>
<H3><B>WILDFIRES DEVASTATE WESTERN USA AND CANADA </B></H3><P>

More than 20,000 firefighters are battling thirty major forest
fires across 2 million hectares of forest in California, Idaho,
Montana, Oregon, Washington, Nevada and Wyoming. Damage is
already estimated at $1 billion.  The largest fire, covering more
than 50,000 hectares, is at Tyee Creek, Washington.  A recent
report published by the National Commission on Wildfire Disasters
predicted that: "dangerous conditions exist over very large areas
and wildfires can attain a size and intensity that defies
control...[C]ompared to historic fires, these wildfires attain
intensities and impact levels that cause...globally significant
emissions of carbon and other greenhouse gases."  The Canadian
province of British Columbia is also hard hit by more than 400
fires after weeks of dry weather and temperatures around 40 ƒC.
("Fire crews battle 100 lightning fires",  UPI, 31 August 1994;
"Fired with enthusiasm",  The Guardian, 4 September 1994; "USA:
fires and explosions; forest and premises", Lloyd's List, 27
August 1994; CHECK "US Wildfires illuminate oversight in US
Climate Policies", Energy, Economics and Climate Change, 17
August 1994; "USA: fires and explosions; forest and premises",
Lloyd's List, 24 August 1994; "Forest fires spread in Western
Canada", Reuter, 27 July 1994).<P>

