<H3><B>FLOODS IN MOLDAVIA  THREATENS ECONOMY </B></H3><P>

 Flooding in the former Soviet Union state causes an estimated
$300 million damage - equal to the country's annual budget.  26
industrial enterprises, 46 agricultural ventures and 34,000
hectares of land, over  4,000 buildings, 26 schools and five
hospitals are flooded.  Earlier in August, a collapsed dam killed
16 people and caused substantial damage to 380 farms with damage
estimated at 40 billion roubles, while flooding in the Crimean
district destroyed 400 homes and caused fuel spills. ("Weather
and navigation: Moldavia",  Lloyd's List, 3 October 1994; "Damage
caused by flood assessed," BBC Summary of World Broadcasts, 8
September 1994; "Dam collapse in Bashkortostan", Lloyd's List, 22
August 1994; "Crimean district flooding causes damage", Lloyd's
List, 5 August 1994).<P>

GREENPEACE Climate Impacts Database<P>

